<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Otis, Ore. On Sale for $3 million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTIS, Ore. (AP) -- A northwest Oregon town that doesn't have a  
stoplight, a bank or even a drugstore is for sale. The price: $3 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Some folks wonder whether this blip on the map where beach-bound  
travelers can fill their tanks is really worth that much. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not exactly an exciting place for things to happen,''  
said 57-year-old Ben Noland, who pumps gas at the BP station. ``The 
only excitement on this corner is when the ambulance goes by and 
everyone gets on the horn to see what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not excitement, but vanity that owner Vivian Lematta is  
selling as she tries to unload the 193-acre town that her 
grandfather bought from descendants of the Siletz Indians for $800 
back in 1910. 
</P>
<P>
	``How would you like to buy a town that you could rename after  
yourself?'' said real estate agent Tamaris Courter. 
</P>
<P>
	She has shown the town to two parties so far, one who was  
looking to put in time-share condos and another who wanted to 
develop a golf course community. Neither showed much interest. 
</P>
<P>
	The handful of businesses and buildings included in the  
$2,995,000 asking price make up most of the town. They include the 
gas station and its mini grocery, the Pronto Pup hot dog stand, two 
houses, an empty 25-stall horse barn. 
</P>
<P>
	How many people live in Otis is unclear, since it is  
unincorporated and keeps no exact records. 
</P>
<P>
	Lematta doesn't get too sentimental when she talks about selling  
the town. After all, she lives in Seattle now and hasn't lived in 
Otis since the 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's anything special because I grew up here,''  
she said in a matter-of-fact tone. ``In fact, sometimes I think 
it'd be nice to get rid of it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
