<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Occidental Services To Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAKERSFIELD, Calif. (AP) -- Occidental Oil and Gas Corp. said it  
will close its Bakersfield office and move its international 
exploration, engineering and technical services groups to Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will layoff 12 of 124 employees immediately and  
another 42 when the move is completed at the end of January 2000. 
Sixty workers will be offered the opportunity to transfer to 
Houston and another 10 will be transferred to other offices. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement on Tuesday is the latest in a series of  
cutbacks by the company's parent, Los Angeles-based Occidental 
Petroleum Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Last November, Occidental announced a two-year, $200 million  
cost-cutting program that included the elimination of more than 
1,000 jobs. In January, Occidental announced it would cut capital 
spending from $1 billion in 1998 to $350 million during 1999 to 
offset record low oil prices that plagued the industry throughout 
1998 and the first months of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	After the pullout of Occidental Oil and Gas, about 1,000  
Occidental employees will continue to work in Kern County in the 
parent company's Elk Hills oil field. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
