<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Liberty Group, Lee Enterprises Swap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORTHBROOK, Ill. (AP) -- Liberty Group Publishing and Lee  
Enterprises announced a swap Tuesday involving five newspapers in 
Iowa, Illinois and Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty Group added to its stable of more than 300 community  
newspapers by trading the 8,000-circulation Daily Sun in Beatrice, 
Neb., and an undisclosed amount of cash for papers that include two 
dailies: the 18,000-circulation Ottumwa Courier in Ottumwa, Iowa, 
and the 6,000-circulation Kewanee Star Courier in Kewanee, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty also gets the weekly Aledo Times Record in Aledo, Ill.,  
and the Henry County Advertiser, a shopper in Geneseo, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenneth L. Serota, president and chief executive officer of  
Liberty, said the acquisitions of Kewanee, Aledo and Geneseo ``will 
allow us to provide greater value to advertisers in our existing 
newspaper cluster in western Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	``In addition, the Ottumwa Courier becomes our largest daily  
newspaper and gives us a strategic entry into southeast Iowa,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard D. Gottlieb, president and chief executive of Lee, said  
the trade strengthens the company's position in Lincoln, Neb. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will take advantage of the $30 million printing facility  
under construction at the Lincoln Journal Star, as well as provide 
other operating efficiencies and regional marketing 
opportunities,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee, headquartered in Davenport, Iowa, owns 22 daily newspapers  
and more than 75 other publications as well as 16 television 
stations and a commercial printing division. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty Group Publishing, headquartered in Northbrook, owns  
newspapers in 16 states and is controlled by Leonard Green &AMP; 
Partners, a Los Angeles-based private merchant banking firm. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
