<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paper: Chiefs, Tait Agree To Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, (AP) -- Offensive tackle John Tait, the 14th player  
taken in this year's NFL draft, told a newspaper on Monday that he 
has agreed to the terms of a five-year contract with the Kansas 
City Chiefs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was prepared to do what it took to get a good deal,'' Tait  
told The Kansas City Star. ``I didn't break the bank, but I got a 
good deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Monday, Tait's agent, Ethan Locke, had said the two  
sides were close to a deal but did not expect an agreement before 
Tuesday at the earliest. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chiefs made the 6-foot-6, 306-pound Brigham Young junior the  
first offensive lineman taken in the 1999 draft. But negotiations 
stalled at the outset and he did not make an offer to the Chiefs 
until the eve of the opening of training camp July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, after missing the entire camp in River Falls, Wis.,  
Tait was quoted as saying he might even sit out the year and go 
back into the 2000 draft. But the Chiefs doubted that, since Tait 
is 24 years old after serving a two-year Mormon mission and is 
already entering his peak earning years as an athlete. 
</P>
<P>
	Tait was expected to join the Chiefs in meetings Tuesday morning  
and practice with the team Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday is the first mandatory cutdown day for NFL teams.  
</P>
<P>
	The club was hopeful Tait could provide immediate help this year  
at left tackle and develop into the next John Alt, who was named to 
the Pro Bowl twice while manning left tackle from 1984-96. 
</P>
<P>
	Tait disputed reports that the Chiefs had had second thoughts  
about drafting him after watching him in offseason minicamps. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe I can come in and compete for a job,'' Tait said.  
``I know I've got a lot of work to do. I know what people in Kansas 
City have said about me, and we'll find out who's right and who's 
wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tait was on several All-America lists in his junior year at  
Brigham Young. 
</P>
<P>
	He missed the 1994 and 1995 seasons while he was on an LDS  
church mission to Tennessee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
