<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Loans to Russia Said OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Contrary to suspicions of the House Banking  
Committee chairman, the International Monetary Fund says it has 
seen no evidence that its loans to Russia have been illegally 
diverted through U.S. banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Michel Camdessus, the head of the IMF, said adequate controls  
are in place and he sees no reason to block new aid to Russia. The 
international lending agency's board is expected to consider 
approving a $640 million loan installment in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	Camdessus said in an interview published today in the French  
newspaper Liberation that he has ordered additional inquiries into 
relations between Russia's central bank and companies it controls 
that are located outside Russia, such as in the Channel Islands off 
Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	``This aid goes from one IMF account to another. There is  
therefore no reason to block it,'' he said. ``Morever, I have 
ordered additional inquiries into the relations between the 
(Russian) central bank and its offshore subsidiaries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, a senior IMF official also said the agency already  
has put tight controls in place to prevent siphoning off of its 
loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The comments by Tom Dawson, the IMF's director of external  
affairs, followed a statement by the chairman of the House Banking 
Committee that IMF loans to Russia should be halted until controls 
are put in place to prevent diversions of the sort that reportedly 
have occurred through Bank of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to have absolutely no indication of any IMF money  
having been diverted'' through Bank of New York or other U.S. 
banks, Dawson told reporters in a conference call. Nonetheless, he 
added, ``We continue to take the allegations seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Banking Committee chairman, Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, spoke  
Friday amid concern that some of the $10 billion or so allegedly 
funneled through the bank by Russian gangsters in a 
money-laundering scheme may have involved IMF loans to Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal authorities are investigating whether there was a  
diversion of IMF loans or of U.S. credits extended to the Russian 
government for buying grain, corn and other farm products. 
</P>
<P>
	An IMF team has been in Russia for several days reviewing a $4.5  
billion loan and is scheduled to return at the end of the week, 
Dawson noted. He said the IMF's board of directors likely will 
review the money-laundering allegations at some point when it 
considers approving the second loan installment, for $640 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe we are being open and transparent in terms of  
what's been going on,'' Dawson said. ``We just don't believe there 
are any grounds for this particular accusation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Russian government's request, auditing firm  
PricewaterhouseCoopers has been conducting a study for the IMF of 
possible manipulations of loan money by Russia's central bank, 
Dawson noted. He said the IMF had previously instituted tight 
controls, keeping the loan money at the international fund rather 
than transferring it to the central bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The study was prompted by an earlier audit by the accounting  
firm that found the central bank in 1996 funneled $1.2 billion in 
IMF money to a company it controlled in the Channel Islands off 
Britain. The money transfer made Russia's financial picture look 
more favorable than it was when President Boris Yeltsin was running 
for re-election, thereby misleading the IMF, agency officials have 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, another PricewaterhouseCoopers audit, completed earlier  
this month, concluded there was no evidence the central bank 
misused $4.8 billion it received from the IMF in July 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The money was used partly in an unsuccessful attempt to prop up  
Russia's currency, the ruble. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
