<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Camp Has Raised About $50M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Fund raising for Texas Gov. George W. Bush's  
presidential race is poised to top $50 million and continue its 
record-breaking pace, according to a published review of 
contributions and interviews with his campaign associates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas Morning News reports in today's editions that Bush is  
on target to collect more than $60 million, with another month to 
go in the current reporting period. That's more than three times 
the amount raised by the top presidential candidates at the same 
time four years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing. Every time Bush goes out, it means he comes back  
with another million dollars or more,'' Herbert Alexander, 
professor emeritus of political science from the University of 
Southern California, told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	By comparison, Republican Bob Dole raised $19 million through  
Sept. 30, 1995 en route to winning the GOP nomination, according to 
the Federal Election Commission. President Clinton had raised $19.5 
million through that period for his re-election. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent weeks of campaigning and a series of out-of-state  
fund-raisers have added to Bush's war chest, which had already 
dwarfed the GOP field with $37 million through June 30. Now, the 
campaign will soon exceed $50 million from more than 108,000 
contributors, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fund raising is going very well,'' said Mindy Tucker, a  
spokeswoman for the Bush campaign. ``We'll file with the FEC again 
at the end of September.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush in recent weeks has had a string of high-dollar  
fund-raisers, collecting $1.1 million last week in Georgia and 
North and South Carolina. The events, since July, have netted $1.5 
million in New Jersey, $500,000 in Roanoke, Va., and $300,000 in 
Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to Bush's coffers were fund-raisers in Colorado, Maine,  
Minnesota, Oklahoma, Utah and Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign has also raised more than $1.25 million in direct  
mail solicitations since July 1, Bush associates said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
