<HEADLINE> Bush To Announce Farm Endorsements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush is getting the  
endorsement of more than 100 prominent Iowa farm activists, 
including backers in each of the state's 99 counties. 
</P>
<P>
	The list includes prominent commodity group leaders, political  
figures and local farm leaders. It's by far the most extensive 
compilation of Iowa farm leaders compiled by a GOP presidential 
candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	The group will be headed by former Iowa Agriculture Secretary  
Robert Lounsberry of McCallsburg and popular former farm 
broadcaster Herb Plambeck of Des Moines. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush was headed to the Dallas Center farm of Tom and Judy  
Barrett on Wednesday to announce the endorsements. 
</P>
<P>
	The move is an impressive organizational feat, and solidifies  
Bush's standing as the front-runner in the battle for Iowa's 
precinct caucuses, which launch the nominating season next winter. 
</P>
<P>
	The backing from farmers is important in the caucus campaign, in  
part because the farm economy is suffering from historic low 
commodity prices, and many farmers face bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	Some activists blame the farm recession on GOP-led efforts to  
revamp the nation's farm policy and eliminate many traditional farm 
subsidies. 
</P>
<P>
	``He truly understands agriculture and the need to develop  
strong markets,'' said former Iowa Farm Bureau president Merlin 
Plagge, among those joining the endorsement effort Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The farm leaders said they favored Bush's approach to bolster  
sales of farm commodities overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Governor Bush's commitment to market development is crucial to  
cattle producers, and his commitment to ethanol is equally crucial 
to corn growers in Iowa and throughout the Midwest,'' said Nancy 
Pellett, past president of the Iowa Beef Industry Council. 
</P>
<P>
	The group backing Bush includes key lawmakers, including the  
chairmen of the House and Senate agriculture committees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
