<HEADLINE> Hornets' Coleman Faces Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Prosecutors have approved a misdemeanor warrant  
charging Charlotte Hornets forward Derrick Coleman with disorderly 
conduct, following accusations that he urinated in front of dining 
room patrons at a downtown restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	Coleman's attorney has been notified that his client must turn  
himself in, Detroit Police Investigator Mattie Lewis told The 
Detroit News for a story Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 32-year-old Coleman has denied any wrongdoing, saying he  
spilled a drink on himself. His attorney, Harold MacDonald, 
couldn't be reached for comment Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Intermezzo Italian Ristorante manager Ralphie Apone alleged that  
on Aug. 7, Coleman urinated in full view of patrons, then again 
outside the restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the police report, Coleman was seen relieving  
himself about 1:30 a.m. in the dining room and was asked to leave 
by the manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Coleman, the 1991 NBA rookie of the year and former Detroit high  
school basketball star, has done a lot of charity work in Detroit, 
including coaching city kids during summer months and buying 
basketball shoes for less-fortunate students. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said they lacked enough evidence to charge Coleman  
with indecent exposure, a more serious charge. Conviction on that 
count brings inclusion on a state sex offender list for 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	While he doesn't have a criminal record in Michigan, Coleman has  
had numerous run-ins with police. 
</P>
<P>
	He faces a civil suit filed by Tammie Phillips in 1997. She is  
suing him for trespass and battery stemming from an alleged Aug. 
26, 1997 assault at her Detroit home. His attorney in that case has 
said the allegation is untrue. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Coleman was arrested and charged with refusing to move  
his truck and swearing at a police officer in Detroit. The jury 
failed to reach a verdict and the case ended in a mistrial. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
