<DOCNO> APW19990831.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 04:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Detroit To Test Parking Meter Cards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Motorists fumbling for coins to feed this city's  
parking meters soon may see some convenient change -- in the form of 
meters that also will accept plastic. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit's parking department will test meters that allow users  
to swipe a special debit card to pay for parking. About 3,000 such 
meters are in place downtown, in the city's New Center area and at 
Wayne State University, ready to begin accepting the 
microchip-equipped cards by this year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	Not interested in the debit card? Fear not, the meters still  
will take quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Each year, the city collects about $9 million in parking fines,  
with about 40 percent of the tickets issued by the parking 
department for meter violations. 
</P>
<P>
	To parking officials, coin-strapped motorists should embrace the  
debit cards, which the city plans to sell for various dollar 
amounts. They'd work like phone cards, with the amount spent 
deducted after each use. 
</P>
<P>
	``I constantly receive letters from people who say, `I was going  
to get change, and I came back and had a ticket,''' Ronald Ruffin, 
the parking department's head, told the Detroit Free Press in a 
story Tuesday 
</P>
<P>
	``This will give them the opportunity to always have money.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
