<HEADLINE> Plea Entered for Wisconsin Fullback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- A judge entered innocent pleas Tuesday on  
behalf of Wisconsin fullback Jael Speights, who is charged with 
sexually assaulting a woman. 
</P>
<P>
	The freshman from Zion, Ill., was charged last week with two  
felony counts of second-degree sexual assault and one count of 
burglary. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman told police that she was repeatedly threatened, beaten  
and choked as she was sexually assaulted in her apartment on July 
31. 
</P>
<P>
	DNA evidence linked the 18-year-old Speights to the assault, a  
criminal complaint said. 
</P>
<P>
	Speights did not know the woman, officials said.  
</P>
<P>
	He waived his preliminary hearing and Judge Paul Higginbotham  
entered innocent pleas on his behalf. He is being held on $15,000 
bond and could face up to 80 years in prison if convicted on all 
the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Public defender Dee Watson said Speights' bond should be lowered  
to $3,000, arguing that he was a responsible student who graduated 
from high school with honors and came to the university in June on 
an academic and athletic scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson said Speights' family could not afford to get him out of  
jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Higginbotham refused to lower the bond, saying the charges  
``scream out for public reaction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This sits right up there in terms of one of the worst cases  
I've seen,'' Higginbotham said. ``Not only is the victim at risk, 
but the general public is at risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speights has been indefinitely suspended from the football team.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
