<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Panel Urges Athlete Drug Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- A drug-use report card for Olympic athletes was  
among the recommendations offered today by an IOC reform panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``health passport'' would contain the athetes' drug-test  
records. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel also said the IOC itself should be more accountable by  
simplifying its financial records to make it easier for the public 
to understand its sources of income and expenditure. 
</P>
<P>
	And it urged the IOC to continue making the Olympics open to all  
by promoting the use of free television networks, rather than pay 
TV channels, and by encouraging affordable seating prices at 
Olympic venues. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want the Olympics on free television so that everybody  
without social barriers can watch,'' said Thomas Bach, the 
coordinator of the 23-member Working Group on the Role of the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	``Financial considerations can only take second priority,'' Bach  
said in a telephone interview after the meetings in Lausanne. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel said the IOC should improve its communications with  
athletes and give them a stronger voice. But, despite the wish to 
encourage universal participation in the games, the number of 
athletes and coaches should be kept at 10,000 and 5,000, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to greater rights, athletes should also have more  
responsibilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Working Group encouraged the athletes to reconfirm their  
pledge not to take prohibited substances to enhance their 
performances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The recommendations followed a rash of flunked drug tests by  
big-name athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamaican sprinter Merlene Ottey, who dominated sprint events for  
two decades and won 14 World Championship medals, pulled out of the 
world championships in Seville after testing positive for the 
steroid Nandrolone. 
</P>
<P>
	In previous weeks, Cuban high jumper Javier Sotomayor, the world  
champion and world-record holder, tested positive for cocaine at 
the Pan American Games and was stripped of his gold medal. The 1992 
Olympic and world 100-meter champion Linford Christie of Britain 
was suspended for a positive Nandrolone test; and U.S. 100-meter 
champion Dennis Mitchell was suspended for two years after testing 
positive for high testosterone. 
</P>
<P>
	Bach said all the recommendations were agreed unanimously by the  
panel, part of the 80-member IOC 2000 Commission, set up following 
the Salt Lake City bribery scandal to overhaul the organization and 
prevent future vote-buying. 
</P>
<P>
	Six IOC members were expelled and four resigned in the Olympic  
movement's worst ever corruption scandal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
