<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers OK New Milk Pricing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Even though it could cost them money, dairy  
farmers overwhelmingly approved an overhaul of the way milk is 
priced around the country rather than have the government end its 
regulation of their industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The new plan, which was developed by the Agriculture Department  
to smooth regional disparities in the prices that farmers receive 
for milk, is likely to undergo revision in Congress this fall 
before it takes effect. The current system expires Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA's plan received near-unanimous approval in most regions of  
the country, according to results of the Aug. 2-6 referendum that 
were released today. 
</P>
<P>
	The smallest margin of victory for the plan was in the  
Northeast, where 90.5 percent of the 13,921 producers voting 
supported it. The plan was approved by 96 percent of the 20,013 
farmers who voted in the upper Midwest. The margin was even larger 
in most other regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists say the USDA plan would hurt most producers outside  
the upper Midwest, but producers had no choice but to vote for it 
given that the current system is scheduled to end, said Chris 
Galen, a spokesman for the National Milk Producers Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The referendum was a choice between the lesser of two evils.  
The most egregious evil is having no federal order program. ... 
It's no surprise that dairy producers very grudgingly and with a 
great deal of reservation did vote in the USDA proposal,'' Galen 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	His group estimates that farmers would lose $200 million a year  
compared to the current system. Consumers would likely see little 
impact. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to USDA, the largest dairy cooperative in the  
nation, Dairy Farmers of America, said its members were approving 
the pricing plan reluctantly. ``Our 'yes' vote does not mean that 
dairy farmers can live with the final rule. They cannot. 
Economically, the income and livelihood of many dairy farm families 
will suffer significantly under your proposal,'' the group said. 
</P>
<P>
	The current pricing system, which was set up in the 1930s to  
stimulate milk production in areas where it was scarce, guarantees 
that farmers in the South and West receive up to $3 per hundred 
pounds more for their fluid milk than producers in the upper 
Midwest. The USDA plan would narrow those disparities although some 
regional differences would continue. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers in Texas would lose more than $1 per hundred pounds  
under the plan, while producers in the Chicago area would gain 55 
cents. 
</P>
<P>
	The prices vary under a network of regional ``milk marketing  
orders.'' Under the USDA plan, the 31 regions in the current system 
would be consolidated into 11. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA was ordered by Congress in 1996 to come up with a  
replacement for the existing system. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Agriculture Committee voted 32-15 earlier this month  
to block the USDA plan and implement an alternative proposal that 
is closer to the existing system. The legislation is sponsored by 
more than 220 lawmakers, a majority of the House. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dairy farmers across the country have voiced their support for  
these modest reforms because they know it is time to introduce the 
concept of fairness back into our milk marketing order system,'' 
said Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
