<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 08:00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Funds Can Fit Religious Beliefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The proliferation of mutual funds during the  
past decade has made it possible for investors of almost any 
religion or lifestyle to find a fund that fits their beliefs. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of these funds fall under the category of so-called  
socially responsible funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Socially responsible funds are those funds that use  
non-financial criteria as at least part of the reason for selecting 
certain stocks,'' said Emily Hall, an analyst at Morningstar Inc., 
a Chicago firm that tracks mutual funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall said religious and lifestyle funds emerged -- and grew --  
following the popularity of funds focused primarily on 
environmental and labor practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``For religious reasons, many investors weren't comfortable with  
certain stocks in their portfolios,'' she said. With that in mind, 
fund managers set about creating funds that met investors' diverse 
philosophies. 
</P>
<P>
	Naturally, different faiths and lifestyles frequently find  
themselves in opposition to one another's goals. Yet mutual fund 
investors all have the same goal -- financial security through savvy 
investing. 
</P>
<P>
	So it's interesting to see how different funds that represent  
different groups go about meeting the goals of their investors 
through divergent strategies. 
</P>
<P>
	Take the Meyers Pride Value Fund, for example, whose objective  
is to invest only in companies with ``progressive policies toward 
gays and lesbians.'' The fund's five top holdings include such 
well-known, blue chip stocks as AT&AMP;T Corp., J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., and 
General Instrument. 
</P>
<P>
	To meet the fund's requirements for receiving investment  
dollars, all of these companies must have stated policies against 
discrimination in their hiring and promotion based on sexual 
orientation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that companies which are more responsive toward  
addressing the concerns of all its employees and other 
constituencies will benefit financially from the consumer loyalty 
generated by such social awareness,'' the fund's prospectus states. 
</P>
<P>
	At the other end of the spectrum is the Timothy Plan, a family  
of funds founded in 1992 and geared toward the retirement plans of 
Christian ministers. The funds' list of investment principles 
includes avoiding companies that promote ``nontraditional married 
lifestyles.'' The fund's Web page asserts: ``We feel strongly that 
we must steer clear from any company that is helping to promote 
unbiblical lifestyles by providing Domestic Partner Benefits,'' 
which afford gay and lesbian couples the same benefits as married 
couples. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Timothy Plan funds also avoid investing in  
companies that are pro-choice, including insurance companies that 
pay for abortions and firms that contribute to Planned Parenthood, 
the nonprofit organization that provides abortion and family 
planning services. And like many socially responsible funds, 
Timothy Plan also shies away from companies that are connected to 
pornography, alcohol or gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	In order to meet the funds' stringent criteria, fund managers  
apparently have to look beyond standard lists of household name 
stocks. Timothy Plan's top five holdings list includes lesser-known 
companies such as publishing firm John Wiley &AMP; Sons, computer 
reseller Comdisco Inc., and aviation equipment company Kellstrom 
Industries Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslims can also find a family of funds that adhere to Islamic  
tenets against drinking alcohol and usury. Amana Funds, which avoid 
bonds altogether because they are interest-based financial 
instruments, lean heavily on technology stocks. Indeed, eight of 
Amana's Trust Growth fund's top 10 holdings fall under the 
technology umbrella, including America Online Inc., Microsoft 
Corp., and Apple Computer Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Morningstar's Hall said technology stocks are popular among  
socially responsible fund managers because many tech companies are 
relatively new and have grown up in more socially aware times. 
Consequently, they have better track records on labor policies and 
the environment than companies that have been around for many 
decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot easier to have a software company with a good  
environmental record than a paper company with a good environmental 
record,'' she observed. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the small Mennonite community in the United States has a  
family of funds dedicated to their beliefs. The Mennonites are 
pacifists, so the MMA Praxis funds prohibit investments in 
companies that manufacture weapons, as well as in securities 
directly issued by the U.S. Treasury Department because the agency 
provides funding for the U.S. military. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 21:10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 69 Said Dead in Argentine Jet Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- An Argentine airliner carrying at  
least 90 people crashed on takeoff Tuesday night, slamming into a 
golf course and bursting into flames. Local news reports said at 
least 69 people were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	There were unconfirmed reports of 26 survivors, at least two who  
jumped to safety from the disintegrating Boeing 737 as it skidded 
in flames across the course. 
</P>
<P>
	The LAPA, Lineas Aereas Privadas Argentinas, plane went down as  
it was taking off from Jorge Newberry airport, one of the city's 
largest, fire and police officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The jet, which was beginning a trip to Cordoba, 475 miles to the  
northwest, burst into flames after it slammed into the golf course 
along the Rio de la Plata river. 
</P>
<P>
	One bystander said the plane had barely cleared a fence  
surrounding the airport before plunging to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	The man, around 30 who declined to give his name, said people on  
the course shouted for passengers to get out of the wreckage. He 
said he saw a man and a woman leap from the craft. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were shouting frantically, `We're safe! We're safe','' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters poured streams of water on the wreckage. Ambulances  
took away victims, reportedly to two area hospitals, sirens blaring 
amid a scene of nighttime confusion. 
</P>
<P>
	It was left a smoldering tangle of metal and other debris after  
being consumed by flames. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities at the scene told local news agency Noticias  
Argentinas that there were at least 69 dead and 26 survivors. The 
account could not be immediately confirmed independently and there 
was no immediate comment from the airline. 
</P>
<P>
	Local news agency Diarios y Noticias quoted one survivor as  
saying he escaped through the rear of the plane. The report, which 
did not give the man's name, quoted him as saying the plane barely 
lifted off when it crashed into the earth. 
</P>
<P>
	Police blocked routes all around the airport, creating huge  
traffic jams along key arteries that pass the airport. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are doing all we can,'' said Fernando de la Rua, the Buenos  
Aires mayor, who said he had ordered civil defense workers, 
ambulance and fire crews from around the city to the scene. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
