<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McConnell Ruled Blue Jackets' Owner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Lamar Hunt has lost another round in the  
dispute over who will control the NHL's Columbus Blue Jackets. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio's 10th District Court of Appeals ruled Tuesday that steel  
magnate John McConnell and his partner, Wolfe Enterprises Inc., did 
not do anything improper when they excluded Hunt from the Blue 
Jackets' ownership group. The ruling upheld a decision in May by 
Judge John Bessey of Franklin County Common Pleas Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The team is to begin play in October 2000 in Nationwide Arena,  
which is being built downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	McConnell and his partners reached a deal with Nationwide to  
build an arena for the expansion franchise after Hunt turned down a 
contract with Nationwide. They sued Hunt to validate the group's 
ownership claim without him. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunt, of Dallas, has accused the NHL and Nationwide of bad-faith  
bargaining and breach of contract. The owner of the NFL's Kansas 
City Chiefs and Columbus Crew of Major League Soccer has 
countersued in a New York court, seeking to have the NHL franchise 
taken away from Columbus and asking for $50 million in damages. 
</P>
<P>
	That case was put on hold while Hunt appealed the Columbus  
verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	``We perceive that we won the case very substantially,'' said  
John W. Zeiger, a lawyer representing McConnell, the Blue Jackets' 
principal owner. 
</P>
<P>
	McConnell did not respond to a message seeking comment, but  
Zeiger said, ``I think it's fair to say that all of our clients are 
extremely pleased.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hunt's attorney said the franchise was never in jeopardy.  
</P>
<P>
	``What you have here is a business deal where the partners had a  
falling out and it's in the court trying to get sorted out who did 
what and gets what,'' Anthony Celebrezze said. ``The franchise is 
not at issue at this point. It's going to be in Columbus. What is 
at issue is who owns the franchise and what part of it each of the 
owners has.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't a total loss for Hunt.  
</P>
<P>
	The appellate court ruled that the lower court was wrong when it  
ordered Hunt to pay McConnell's group $920,000 in legal fees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, we're grateful that they decided that Hunt Sports  
didn't have to pay the legal fees of the other side,'' Celebrezze 
said. ``We're disappointed that the court didn't reverse other 
aspects of the trial court judgment that would allow three of the 
investors to walk off with the franchise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Celebrezze said he and the rest of Hunt's legal team would  
probably decide within the next 10 days whether to appeal to the 
Ohio Supreme Court. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
