<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sheppard Drops Exhumation Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Prosecutors can exhume the body of Dr. Sam  
Sheppard's wife without a court fight from the couple's son, who 
has brought a wrongful imprisonment suit in the case that inspired 
TV's ``The Fugitive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sam Reese Sheppard reluctantly agreed Monday to allow the  
exhumation of his mother to proceed, even though it may mean 
another delay in the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is emotionally wearing,'' Sheppard said.  
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors want to obtain DNA samples from Marilyn Sheppard to  
help them defend the state in the lawsuit filed by Sheppard's son. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Sheppard spent a decade in prison after being  
convicted of beating his wife to death in July 1954 at the couple's 
home on Lake Erie. He was acquitted at a retrial in 1966 after the 
U.S. Supreme Court overturned the original verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Sheppard contends a window washer killed his mother  
and has worked for the last 10 years to try to clear his father's 
name. If he wins the wrongful imprisonment lawsuit, damages could 
reach as much as $2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheppard, his attorneys and prosecutors met behind closed doors  
for nearly two hours Monday with Judge Ron Suster of Cuyahoga 
County Common Pleas Court to discuss the exhumation of Mrs. 
Sheppard. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheppard, 52, of Oakland, Calif., is upset about the exhumation  
because he feels prosecutors have had 45 years to investigate the 
case and views the exhumation as a last-minute stalling tactic. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheppard's attorney, Terry Gilbert, said the exhumation wasn't  
worth fighting over. ``We feel it's going to confirm our case or 
not determine much of anything, frankly,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	County Prosecutor William Mason ordered the exhumation last week  
and plans to have an anthropologist, forensic dentist and DNA 
expert examine Mrs. Sheppard's remains. No date has been set for 
exhuming the body from Knollwood Cemetery in suburban Mayfield 
Heights. 
</P>
<P>
	The remains of Sheppard, who died in 1970, were exhumed for DNA  
samples in 1997, at his son's request. The doctor always insisted 
that a bushy-haired intruder killed his wife, then knocked him 
unconscious when he came to her aid. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
