<HEADLINE> Education Secretary Starts Bus Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- Fifteen-year-old Lisa Wright got kudos  
for being a good student straight from the top. 
</P>
<P>
	Education Secretary Richard W. Riley thrilled the high school  
junior by telling her to ``keep up the good work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the 100-member marching band from Lisa's school, Ooltewah  
High, blared in the background, Riley greeted his constituents 
Monday as he kicked off a five-state back-to-school bus tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just glad to get as chance to tell him what I think,''  
said Lisa, who met the nation's top education policy-maker at the 
airport here. 
</P>
<P>
	For the record, Lisa, a self-described A student who does her  
homework every night, thinks schools need more money and that all 
kids should stay in school until they graduate. 
</P>
<P>
	At Howard School of Academics and Technology in Chattanooga,  
Tenn., Riley launched his bus tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``Better education is everybody's business,'' Riley told a crowd  
of students and teachers gathered in the school library today. 
``When parents and communities are involved in a serious way, 
students learn better, have better discipline and stay in school 
longer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before boarding a large charter coach decorated in yellow to  
resemble a school bus, Riley touted Clinton administration 
initiatives to go before Congress this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``If ever there was a time to be investing in the future, that  
time is now,'' he said. ``This is why we should use our nation's 
budget surplus to protect Social Security, shore up Medicare ... 
and invest in quality education.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He praised a new generation of Southern governors for what he  
called ``pro-education agendas.'' The governors will ride various 
legs of the ``Success Express'' along the way as Riley visits their 
schools, some of which are running well and others the state has 
had to take over. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Riley's caravan was visiting local schools to launch the  
Mars Millennium Project -- a program to help schoolchildren 
nationwide learn about science by designing a Mars colony. He also 
was stressing parental involvement at Litchfield High School in 
Gadsden, Ala., the first school in Alabama to fall under state 
control because of poor scores on the Stanford Achievement Test. 
</P>
<P>
	A math and technology magnet school, Litchfield was targeted for  
takeover after it failed to improve its poor performance on the 
test, which is the only measure of academic achievement under state 
law. 
</P>
<P>
	Those are the sorts of reforms Southern governors are being  
praised for, said Mark Musick, president of the Southern Regional 
Education Board, an advisory panel to Southern governors in 16 
states including the ones Riley will visit -- Alabama, Georgia, 
Tennessee, North Carolina and South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not trying to shame schools into doing better by  
putting their names in the paper,'' Musick said. ``(Riley is) going 
to sense in these stops some feeling that we're making progress, 
that there's some determination about the direction we're moving 
in.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
