<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Hits 7-Month Low Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar hit a seven-month low against the  
surging yen, and also lost ground to the euro Tuesday as traders 
lost confidence in the U.S. currency during another turbulent day 
on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0578, up  
from $1.0462 late Monday. The dollar also was quoted at 109.59 
Japanese yen, down from 110.73. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's movements continue be ``reasonably well  
correlated'' with those of the U.S. stock and bond markets, said 
Guillermo Estebanez, currency strategist at the Bank of America. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. stocks were mixed after a volatile trading day. The Dow  
Jones industrial average lost more than 80 points, its fourth 
straight day of losses, but the technology-laden Nasdaq composite 
index rose more than 26 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said currency traders sold dollars to purchase yen and  
euros in order to capitalize on optimism for the Japanese and 
European economies. 
</P>
<P>
	Estebanez said traders had believed the Bank of Japan would  
intervene to prop up the dollar if it fell below the 110 figure. A 
weakened dollar and a rising yen could hurt Japan's economic 
recovery by making Japanese exports more expensive to U.S. 
consumers. ``An excessive appreciation of the yen will make it 
harder for Japan to sell its goods overseas,'' Estebanez said. 
</P>
<P>
	But since the Japanese bank failed to intervene, the dollar is  
likely to fall further against the yen as traders sell U.S. 
currency to buy into Japan's recovering economy, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5136 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5306, and 1.4925 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4935. The British 
pound rose to $1.6064 from $1.5896. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8507 German 
marks, down from 1.8694; 6.2071 French francs, down from 6.2695; 
and 1,832 Italian lire, down from 1,851. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
