<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 23:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat, Drought Take Toll on Catfish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, Ga. (AP) -- The drought that has withered trees and  
crops, lowered lakes and creeks and frustrated lawn-obsessed 
homeowners has also hurt farm-raised catfish. 
</P>
<P>
	Catfish eat less -- and grow less -- when the temperature climbs  
above 90 degrees, says Gary Burtle, a University of Georgia catfish 
specialist. High temperatures also can cause outbreaks of disease, 
and excessive sunlight is dangerous, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been no catastrophic fish kills,'' Burtle said.  
``It's more of a chronic situation. We had one farmer who had been 
losing a few fish a day since June.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burtle predicts below-average production and higher prices.  
Catfish rank fifth among America's most popular fish or shellfish. 
</P>
<P>
	But Henry Gantz, president of the Catfish Institute in Belzoni,  
Miss., says that any price increase will be marginal. 
</P>
<P>
	Commercial catfish producers make sure they have wells to  
maintain water levels and equipment, such as aerators, to oxygenate 
the ponds, Burtle said. 
</P>
<P>
	``People with plenty of well water and who are careful managers  
have fewer problems,'' Burtle said. ``When you get to the small 
pond owner who may not be as intensively managing, you can have 
some problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But even commercial producers are affected by the weather.  
</P>
<P>
	Burtle predicts there will be fewer catfish to market this year.  
A harvest-size catfish should weigh at least a pound, and the 
industry average is approaching 2 pounds, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	With catfish eating less, producers have to care for them longer  
and that raises their costs, Burtle said. Also, pond owners who 
would normally restock their ponds may be reluctant to buy more 
fish until water levels stabilize. 
</P>
<P>
	``You might see catfish filet prices increase to nearly $5 a  
pound in the grocery store,'' Burtle said. ``Normally, it sells for 
less than $4 per pound.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As of August, the industry had processed 347 million pounds of  
catfish, compared with 335 million for the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm hopeful we'll be just ahead of last year,'' said Mike  
McCall, editor of the Catfish Journal in Jackson, Miss. ``Catfish 
farmers fight heat and oxygen problems every summer, especially in 
August.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Simmons, manager of Owens &AMP; Williams Inc., Georgia's  
largest commercial producer, said his company is having a 
productive summer, despite the drought. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have more fingerlings than we have ever had, but the fish  
are not selling,'' he said. ``A lot of the ponds are low and people 
are not buying. They're waiting on rain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's really too soon to judge the market because pond owners  
don't usually start restocking until late August and early 
September, Simmons said. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens &AMP; Williams has been able to maintain normal water levels  
in its 80 ponds, occupying 300 acres near Newton and Hawkinsville, 
because they are all supplied by wells. 
</P>
<P>
	Many ponds in the Hawkinsville area are at a half or third of  
their normal levels, and fish kills are the largest in four or five 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of it is just the extreme heat,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 12:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
