<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury To Be Picked in Dragging Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRYAN, Texas (AP) -- A pool of 161 potential jurors crowded a  
courtroom today for the murder trial of a second white supremacist 
accused in the gruesome dragging death of a black man last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence Russell Brewer is charged with murder in the death of  
James Byrd Jr. Lawyers will spend two weeks whittling the group to 
12. Testimony is set to begin Sept. 15 and should take about three 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 161 prospective jurors who reported, 19 are black. In  
early questioning of the entire jury pool, 20 potential jurors, 
five of them black, were excused for health or legal reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer, wearing a coat and tie, was seated at a table facing  
away from potential jurors, who sat in the audience area of the 
courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer, 32, is the second of three men to be tried. Co-defendant  
John William King was convicted in Jasper last February and 
sentenced to death. Shawn Allen Berry is to be tried later. Both 
Brewer and Berry face a death sentence if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	The three were accused of beating Byrd in June 1998, chaining  
him to a pickup truck and dragging him for nearly three miles 
outside Jasper, a town of 8,000 about 150 miles northeast of 
Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer's trial was moved to the Brazos County Courthouse in  
Bryan, 150 miles west of Jasper, at the request of prosecutors who 
didn't want the defense to use a Jasper location as an issue for 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray believes King led  
the other two men to murder. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no question that King had the charisma,'' Gray said  
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gray says it was Brewer -- a member of the pro-Aryan  
Confederate Knights of America prison gang since 1995 -- who lured 
King down the path to organized hate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone had to teach Bill King,'' Gray said. That someone, he  
says, was Brewer. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventy-two reporters from around the nation have been granted  
courtroom seats, indicating public interest remains strong more 
than a year and a half after the crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors believe the death of Byrd, 49, was an event King and  
Brewer staged to launch their own fledgling hate group, the Texas 
Rebel Soldiers, and initiate King's friend Berry as a member. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer's attorney, Doug Barlow, did not return calls from The  
Associated Press. Prosecutors are preparing for a defense similar 
to one they heard six months ago, when King's lawyers claimed their 
client joined a white supremacist prison gang to survive beatings 
or rape by black prisoners 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
