<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of New York Reputation Defended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The chairman of the Bank of New York, in a  
strongly worded memo to employees, defended his institution's 
reputation amid allegations that it may have been used by Russian 
mobsters to launder money. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas A. Renyi said in the memo sent Monday that he was  
``deeply troubled'' by the possibility that the bank's controls may 
have been compromised. ``We will do whatever is needed to prevent 
illegal or improper activities that involve the Bank. Period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The memo, which the bank provided to The Associated Press on  
Tuesday, was sent just days after the bank dismissed a London-based 
executive who had been involved in the bank's Eastern European 
operations. Lucy Edwards, who was born in Russia, is married to a 
Russian businessman reportedly under investigation in the 
laundering scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	In his memo, Renyi assured employees that the bank was  
cooperating with investigators, that the bank has not been accused 
with any wrongdoing, and that no funds have been lost or customer 
services interrupted. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our reputation, built on our collective hard work and sound  
business practices, is our most valuable asset. We will do 
everything in our power to protect and enhance it. We will not 
tolerate any action that tarnishes our reputation,'' Renyi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are examining allegations that as much as $10  
billion may have passed through accounts at the Bank of New York in 
a major money laundering operation involving Russian organized 
crime figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Money laundering involves moving around profits from criminal  
activities through a series of transactions until they appear to be 
gains from legitimate businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to firing Ms. Edwards, the bank has also suspended  
another executive, Natasha Kagalovsky, who supervised the bank's 
business in Eastern Europe from her post in New York. Ms. 
Kagalovsky has denied any wrongdoing. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
