<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Steelmakers Appeal Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Three major Japanese steelmakers have lodged an  
appeal in the United States against the Commerce Department over an 
anti-dumping measure, officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nippon Steel Corp., Japan's largest steelmaker, and NKK Corp.  
appealed to the U.S. Court of International Trade on Tuesday, after 
Kawasaki Steel Corp. filed with the same court Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are taking action since the anti-dumping investigation by  
the U.S. Commerce Department has been conducted under an unfair 
procedure,'' said Nippon Steel spokesman Takashi Kanke. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department in late April determined that Japanese  
steel companies were engaged in illegal steel dumping -- selling 
abroad at less than home-market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, the U.S. International Trade Commission ruled in favor  
of the Commerce Department's position, allowing the United States 
to impose tariffs of up to 67 percent on hot-rolled carbon steel, a 
widely used product. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. steel industry has filed dumping complaints against  
Japanese and other competitors over eight different steel products. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, the U.S. International Trade Commission  
ruled that steel beams from Japan and South Korea are being dumped 
on the U.S. markets at less than fair value. 
</P>
<P>
	That ruling clears the way for the Commerce Department to  
continue its investigation into the case. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the Commerce Department found preliminary evidence that  
Japan and five other countries have been selling steel plates in 
the United States at an unfairly low price compared with their 
domestic markets. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
