<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Lower; Gold Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mostly lower against other  
major currencies in European trading today. Gold rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0566 in late European trading, up from  
$1.0453 Monday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro 
traded at $1.0582. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday,  
included 109.67 Japanese yen, down from 111.12; 1.5141 Swiss 
francs, down from 1.5310; 1.4895 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4879. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6080, up from $1.5878.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 109.09 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.6086. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8511 German marks, down from 1.8711; 
6.2082 French francs, down from 6.2753; 2.0857 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.1082; 1,832.55 Italian lire, down from 1,852.36. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at 254.90 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$253.80 on Friday. Markets were closed Monday for a holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $254.45, up from $253.05. Gold rose  
70 U.S. cents in Hong Kong to close at $254.65. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver in London closed at $5.19 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.08 on Friday. 
</P>
