<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 31, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Close Mixed; Dow Down 84.85  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as a report of continued  
growth in the manufacturing sector ignited fears of inflation and 
hurt blue-chip companies. But technology stocks, benefiting from a 
wave of new deals and products, rose. The Dow Jones industrial 
average ended down 84.85 at 10,829.28. Earlier in the session, the 
Dow was off as much as 132 points, a dip large enough to spur some 
buying by bargain hunters and computer-driven trading programs, 
analysts said. Broader stock indicators were mixed, with the 
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index up 25.13 at 2,737.82. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,829.28  - 84.85
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1309  Declines 1664  Unchgd  573
NYSE Volume:         774,370,050
Most Active NYSE issue:         Office Depot 10 7/16  - 1/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1319.20  - 4.82
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          775.41   +   .20
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,737.82  + 25.13
Gold(final) -    $255.80    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.
Silver(final) -   $5.180  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.

</P>
<P>
	Economic Reports Are Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consumer confidence fell for the second straight  
month in August as interest rates rose, while economic activity in 
the manufacturing sector grew for the seventh consecutive month, 
according to two private reports released today. The Conference 
Board said its consumer confidence index, which measures consumers' 
likeliness to spend, edged down 0.4 of a point, less than analysts 
expected, to 135.8 from a revised 136.2 in July. Separately, the 
National Association of Purchasing Management said its index 
measuring industrial activity rose to 54.2 percent, up from 53.4 in 
July. A measure of inflation, which tracks prices paid by industry 
for raw materials and supplies, also rose. The purchasing 
executives report had been scheduled for tomorrow, but the figures 
were mistakenly released today, the group said. 

</P>
<P>
	European Stocks Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks fell to their lowest point in a  
week and a half today, driven by weakness in the bond market 
hurting insurers and a decline in pharmaceutical shares headed by 
SmithKline Beecham. Allianz AG, the biggest stock in the Dow Jones 
Stoxx Insurance index, closed with a loss of 7.30 euros, at 247.00 
euros, while in London, Allied Zurich was the worst blue-chip 
performer, with a loss of 45.5 pence to 760.5 pence. Banks and 
insurance companies hold large bond portfolios and are more 
sensitive to rising interest rates. SmithKline led the drop in 
European pharmaceutical stocks after the U.S. Food and Drug 
Administration requested modifications to its license application 
for Bexxar leukemia treatment. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 
European companies fell 5.89 points, or 1.9 percent, to close at 
308.69. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies 
in countries that joined the single currency, closed down 5.89 
points at 323.44. 

</P>
<P>
	Apple Unveils New Computer  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Apple Computer Inc. unveiled what it called  
the world's first desktop supercomputer, its new G4 model for 
professionals, in an attempt to extend the company's technological 
and financial rebound. ``This is the most powerful personal 
computer ever brought to market,'' said Apple interim CEO Steve 
Jobs today during his keynote address at the Seybold publishing 
conference. Heartened investors pushed shares of Apple up 3 3/16 to 
65 1/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. The new computers, powered by chips 
made by Apple, Motorola Inc. and IBM, cost between $1,600 and 
$3,500. 

</P>
<P>
	American Airlines Absorbs Reno  
</P>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- American Airlines absorbed Reno Air  
Inc. today with little effect on the schedule of the nation's 
second-largest carrier despite the airline's inability to reach 
agreement about the deal with its pilots. As part of the 
transition, white Reno jets sported American decals and airport 
signs were changed over in the middle of the night. The purchase of 
tiny Reno has been a sore point between American's parent company, 
AMR Corp., and its pilots, many of whom called in sick to show 
displeasure with the company's dealings. The sickout was halted by 
federal judge. 

</P>
<P>
	Adobe, Xerox Announce Alliance  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Adobe Systems Inc. and Xerox Corp.  
announced an alliance today that will help publishers and authors 
sell their books and publications over the Internet in secure file 
format that prevents piracy. The deal integrates Adobe's PDF file 
format with Xerox's ContentGuard rights management software, which 
prevents unauthorized copying of the file. Consumers who download 
books or publications can print them out or view them on the screen 
with Adobe's Acrobat software. 

</P>
<P>
	Sun Micro Is Buying Star Division  
</P>
<P>
	PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Sun Microsystems is taking aim again at  
Microsoft's domination of the personal computer software market. 
Sun has announced the purchase of Fremont, Calif.-based Star 
Division Corp. The company makes a suite of office software called 
StarOffice, which includes e-mail, word processor, spreadsheet and 
presentation applications. Sun will offer the applications over the 
Internet for free as part of its ``StarPortal'' initiative. 

</P>
<P>
	New Child Car Seat Regulations Here  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Child car seats take on a new look starting  
tomorrow, when stricter head protection standards take effect. That 
means most seats will come equipped with a tether strap that 
anchors the top of the seat more securely so children move less in 
a crash. The change is the first phase of a three-year federal plan 
to create a universal, easy-to-use child seating system. The goal 
is to eliminate the confusion among parents that results in 
incorrect installation of up to 80 percent of car seats. 

</P>
<P>
	Amana Recalls Over 5,000 Gas Ovens  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amana Appliances is recalling more than 5,000  
gas-fueled, down-draft ovens that have a faulty lock. The oven can 
open during the self-clean cycle, exposing people to high 
temperatures, the Consumer Product Safety Commission said today. No 
injuries have been reported. The commission said customers should 
stop using the self-cleaning feature but can use the oven for 
cooking. 

</P>
<P>
	Allergic Reaction Kits Recalled  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- American Home Products is recalling hundreds of  
allergic reaction kits in North America because the epinephrine 
syringes in them may not work. Epinephrine, which increases blood 
flow and promotes breathing, is used to treat anaphylactic shock 
and asthma attacks. For American Home, which faces legal problems 
from its diet drugs and Norplant contraceptive device, the recall 
is the latest setback. American Home's Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories 
division said it is voluntarily recalling Epinephrine Injection, 
USP1:1000 in 1 mL Tubex syringe. The company said it's taking the 
action after observing discolored samples in routine 
quality-control tests. A few of the discolored samples were found 
to be less potent than they should be. 

</P>
<P>
	GUESS? Recalls 78,000 T-shirts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Clothing designer GUESS? is recalling more  
than 78,000 girls' T-shirts with a liquid-filled bubble patch on 
the front. The liquid contains a petroleum distillate that can be 
harmful if ingested, the Consumer Product Safety Commission said 
Tuesday. No injuries have been reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Wary of The Pill  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- By Thursday, Japanese women will at last have the  
pill -- the convenient, effective birth control that has been 
available to women elsewhere for four decades. But no rush by 
Japanese women to take it is expected. In Japan's male-dominated 
society, major obstacles remain among both men and women to the 
pill's social acceptance. Despite gains in the workplace and 
society, women who take initiative -- especially about their 
sexuality -- are frowned upon in Japan. That attitude was evident 
during the pill's nine-year struggle against opposition in the 
government and among conservatives who thought it would erode 
morals. The pill finally was approved in June. 

</P>
