<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Wildfires Near Lake Resorts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE ARROWHEAD, Calif. (AP) -- The biggest of the giant wildfires  
burning in the West came within miles of lake resorts high in the 
mountains Tuesday after destroying a dozen homes in the Mojave 
Desert below. 
</P>
<P>
	The 50,000-acre blaze chewed through dense stands of tall trees  
on 8,000-foot peaks in the San Bernardino Mountains, and residents 
of the areas around Lake Arrowhead and Big Bear Lake nervously 
watched billowing plumes of smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	``My house is right over this ridge, and if those flames come  
much closer I'm getting my wife and my kids in my car and we're 
getting out of here,'' said Dick Solter, a Los Angeles man who has 
a vacation home at Arrowhead. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire, which was only 10 percent contained, was the largest  
of the blazes being battled by more than 9,000 firefighters in 
California, Idaho, Montana, Nevada and Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	A 40,000-acre blaze started by a downed power line had charred  
miles of grass in southern Idaho, five miles from the Snake River 
town of Glenns Ferry. 
</P>
<P>
	In Lake Arrowhead, a group of people cried and hugged as they  
stood atop a dam and watched helicopters repeatedly dip buckets 
into tiny Papoose Lake and roar off to drop the water two miles 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	Restaurant worker Karen Hanson said she hadn't seen anything  
like it in 26 years at Arrowhead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I live on the other side of the lake so I'm not worried about  
the flames getting to me,'' she said. ``What hurts me is seeing all 
of this wildlife destroyed. There is some really old growth around 
Arrowhead and Big Bear and if it catches I don't know how they'll 
put it out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters were not sure where the fire was going. Even though  
the biggest flames were high in the mountains, there still was 
concern for homes on the fringes of the desert communities of Apple 
Valley and Lucerne Valley, where scorched earth smoldered. 
</P>
<P>
	``The winds are very erratic,'' said Kathy Saindon, a San  
Bernardino County fire spokeswoman. ``They blow northwest one 
minute and southeast the next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 people voluntarily left homes down in the desert, but  
by evening there were no evacuation orders in Arrowhead or Big Bear 
Lake, seven miles from the nearest flames. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
