<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D-Backs Acquire Harris From Colorado </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Arizona Diamondbacks picked up an experienced  
left-handed hitter for the final month of their playoff drive 
Tuesday, acquiring utility infielder Lenny Harris from the Colorado 
Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange, the Rockies got 20-year-old minor-league second  
baseman Belvani Martinez. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris, who has played all four infield positions and the  
outfield in his 12 years in the major leagues, is hitting .297 this 
season. He has a major league best 20 pinch hits this year, the 
latest one a double in Colorado's 11-8 loss to Pittsburgh on Monday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a good addition for us,'' Arizona manager Buck Showalter  
said. ``He's been in a lot of wars. He's got a great reputation in 
baseball. He'll fit right in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harris, 34, is first among all active players and eighth on the  
career list with 109 pinch hits. 
</P>
<P>
	To make room for Harris, the Diamondbacks placed shortstop Andy  
Fox on the disabled list, retroactive to Aug. 28, with strained 
ribs. Arizona also purchased the contract of outfielder Turner Ward 
from Triple-A Tucson and placed him on the 15-day disabled list 
with tendinitis in his right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	The DL moves came just before Tuesday night's deadline for teams  
to establish their 25-man playoff rosters. Players on the disabled 
list also are eligible for the playoffs, leaving the Diamondbacks 
room to maneuver later. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona had an 8 1/2-game lead over second-place San Francisco in  
the NL West going into Tuesday night's action. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris has a career .272 batting average with Cincinnati, Los  
Angeles, the New York Mets and Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's capable of playing third base, second base, first base,  
shortstop and corner outfield,'' Showalter said. ``He's even caught 
a little.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez was the second-leading hitter in the Class A California  
League with a .333 average for High Desert. 
</P>
<P>
	``Arizona needed a left-handed hitter and were willing to pay  
the price,'' Colorado director of business administration Tony 
Siegle said. ``We looked over their organization and got the best 
player available.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockies filled Harris' roster spot by recalling second  
baseman Chris Sexton from Triple-A Colorado Springs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
