<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Camp Specializes in Ethnic Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHNSONBURG, N.J. (AP) -- Alec Powell broke boards during tae  
kwon do, dished up Thai chicken with satay during cooking class and 
sang Korean grace before each meal. But the best thing about summer 
camp for this 10-year-old? ``It has people just like you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holt Heritage Camp provides the usual swimming and singing  
around the fire of sleep-away summer camp, but most importantly, it 
lets people like Alec learn about the cultures of their birth 
countries and meet others who were adopted from overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	For once, children like Emily Goldberg, Christine Van Hise, Mike  
Viscardo and Alison Zukowski don't have to explain why their names 
don't match their faces. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't ask you stupid questions here,'' Alec said,  
recalling a lifetime of queries, usually from staring strangers 
trying to compare his Korean features with those of his white 
parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Campers, who range from 9 to 15, are grouped by age. At any  
given time, one set may be outside playing mook chee bah, a Korean 
variation of scissors, rock and paper in which children pair up 
with partners and contort their bodies in shapes according to the 
word being called out. 
</P>
<P>
	Another group of campers may be inside the mess hall measuring  
soy sauce for the bul go gi, or Korean barbecue, they are learning 
to make. A third group may be across the room gluing glitter, 
sequins, feathers and string to Indonesian masks. 
</P>
<P>
	Alec, from Hamilton, N.J., picked tae kwon do over fan dancing  
and Korean language class as his elective. He began to regret his 
decision toward the end of the week when his instructor punished 
him and others for chitchatting during class. The punishment: 10 
pushups. 
</P>
<P>
	``The longer you guys talk, the longer we do this,'' instructor  
Brian Parise barked, shortly before he ordered them to do five 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	Conversations among campers aren't different from others their  
age -- summer romances, make-up, cars -- except when the topic turns 
to adoption. Questions then turn to how old they were when they 
were adopted or whether they plan to visit their birth countries. 
The answers vary -- some desperately want to visit, and have even 
made plans to do so, while others have no interest in such a trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly all of the campers were adopted from Asia -- more than 90  
percent are Korean, said Korean-born camp director Todd Kwapisz of 
Eugene, Ore., where Holt International is based. Others were 
adopted from China, India, Vietnam, the Philippines and one from 
Romania. 
</P>
<P>
	The Asian influence at Heritage Camp is noticeable in the names  
campers pick for their cabins: Seoulful Sweeties, Mocha Men, 
Kimchee Kuties, Sarang Sisters, Biggie's Buddha Boys and Pretty Fly 
for Asian Guys. 
</P>
<P>
	The camp is one of three organized by Holt International, an  
adoption agency, and is similar to more than a dozen other culture 
camps nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	It provides a ``safe environment'' for people who grew up with  
similar experiences, said Katie Cieplik, a 22-year-old former 
camper from Parsippany, N.J.,who has returned the past four summers 
as a counselor. Prejudices toward Asian-Americans sometimes feel 
worse for adopted children because their parents usually cannot 
relate to taunts about ethnic features or people who question their 
identity as Americans, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cieplik said her first culture camp, back in 1987, boosted her  
self-confidence and pride in her Korean heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I learn more about myself in the five days I'm here than the  
other 360 days of the year,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	All counselors at Heritage Camp are adopted. Most of them, like  
Cieplik, attended a cultural camp when they were younger. 
</P>
<P>
	Counselor Phil Golowatsch, 23, of Philadelphia, has a different  
situation from most, in that both of his adoptive parents are 
foreign-born -- his mother is from Brazil and his father is from 
Poland. Growing up, he felt more comfortable with his parent's 
cultures than his own. And, as a child, he often felt ashamed of 
being Korean and found it difficult relating to other Asians. 
</P>
<P>
	``You think you're alone,'' he said. Heritage Camp provided him  
with ``the comfort of knowing that someone else is going through 
similar experiences.'' It also led him to his girlfriend, Shelah 
Reber, another Korean-born adoptee and fellow counselor who now 
lives in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Camp concludes with a dinner of multiethnic dishes and a variety  
of skits and dances for the parents, who arrive to find their 
children dressed identically in navy blue T-shirts. Unlike other 
times they would pick up their child at school or a friend's house, 
many parents found it difficult to single out their child. 
</P>
<P>
	``At home, I could pick out the brown haired girl in the pool --  
that was my Kate, no problem,'' said Cami Reynolds of Philadelphia. 
``Here, I couldn't spot her at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, her 10-year-old daughter found her, she said.  
</P>
<P>
	``She goes, 'Hey, Mom. These people look like me. You're the one  
who looks different here.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
