<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 15:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall for Fourth Session / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell for a fourth straight session  
Tuesday as a report on strength in the industrial economy and 
rising prices for raw materials kept inflation worries alive. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1/8 point,  
or by $1.25 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, rose to 6.06 percent from 6.05 percent late 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were caught by surprise by a National Association of  
Purchasing Management report, released by mistake a day earlier 
than scheduled, that said the industrial economy grew in August for 
a seventh straight month. The inflation component of the survey 
also rose sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	The stronger-than-expected figures pointed to a continued  
resurgence in manufacturing and rekindled inflation jitters. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders worry that unless the economy starts to cool off,  
inflation-fighters at the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates 
for a third time this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher interest rates push down the value of fixed-income  
investments such as bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged, and intermediate maturities fell 1/32 point to 1/8 
point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.96 percent as the  
discount fell 0.05 percentage point from Monday's treasury auction 
to 4.83 percent. Six-month yields were 5.20 percent, as the 
discount rose 0.01 percentage point from the weekly auction to 5.00 
percent. One-year yields were 5.27 percent as the discount fell 
0.01 percentage point from late Monday to 5.00 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.62 1/2 percent from 5.31 1/4 percent late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 5/32 point to 114 11/32. The average 
yield to maturity rose to 5.78 percent from 5.77 percent late 
Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
