<DOCNO> APW19990831.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 15:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Brazil Eyes Budget Surplus, Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Caught between conflicting demands to  
create jobs and cut spending, President Fernando Henrique Cardoso 
on Tuesday promised something for everyone. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardoso unveiled a stripped-down budget for next year that calls  
for a surplus of 28.5 billion reals, now about $14.8 billion. The 
surplus is part of Brazil's agreement with the International 
Monetary Fund to qualify for a $41.5 billion loan. 
</P>
<P>
	He also announced a massive four-year program of 358 projects to  
be undertaken by the government and private enterprise. Called 
``Advance Brazil,'' the program is expected to bring investments of 
$165 billion, create 8.5 million jobs and help kick-start a 
stagnant economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brazil is hungry for growth,'' Cardoso said in a speech at the  
presidential palace. But he added that growth ``must be a 
consequence of organized public accounts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hunger has been building for two years, while Latin  
America's biggest economy was a victim of its own artificially 
strong currency. The strong real kept inflation down but hurt 
exports and aggravated a chronic budget deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Rocked by the Asian crisis in 1997 and Russia's meltdown last  
year, Brazil was forced to devalue its currency and raise interest 
rates. The IMF's rescue package came with austere targets for 
shrinking the deficit, but Brazilians are chafing under years of 
stagnation and high unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 2000 budget, the government tried to juggle the demand  
for renewed growth with the need to generate a primary surplus -- 
which doesn't count interest payments -- equivalent to 2.65 percent 
of the gross domestic product. 
</P>
<P>
	Budget Minister Martus Tavares said the government plans to  
guarantee the surplus by conditioning expenses to the availability 
of financing. Without ready funds, spending is prohibited. 
</P>
<P>
	The budget includes a forecast of 4 percent growth and inflation  
of 6 percent. Interest rates, now at 19.5 percent, will fall to 13 
percent next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardoso also unveiled a broad outline for development, a  
multiyear plan the president is required to submit. The plan -- 
which ranges from building railroads in the midwest to encouraging 
ecotourism in the Amazon -- would depend on estimated investments of 
about $513 billion, from federal and local governments, lending 
agencies and the private sector. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, which is separate from the ``Advance Brazil'' project,  
earmarks 60 percent of expenses for ``social'' investments that 
benefit mainly the poor. Cardoso has come under fire from 
opposition and allies alike that his government does little for 
needy Brazilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 15:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
