<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Farmers Mobilize, Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French farmers dumped vegetables in front of  
government buildings and protested against McDonald's and the U.S. 
government Tuesday in France's latest outbreak of rural anger. 
</P>
<P>
	In the southern city of Montpellier, hundreds of farmers  
protested the imprisonment of an activist who led the ransacking of 
a new McDonald's restaurant several weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Bove and four other men were jailed Aug. 19 after they  
vandalized the McDonald's construction site in the southern town of 
Millau. Bove, a sheep farmer and local leader of a radical farmer's 
union, says he is fighting globalization. 
</P>
<P>
	Bove's union has called for a wave of demonstrations at  
McDonald's restaurants to protest U.S. sanctions on a slew of 
luxury French food products, ranging from Roquefort cheese to foie 
gras. The sanctions were slapped on European goods earlier this 
summer in retaliation for the European Union's decision to ban 
imports of U.S. hormone-treated beef. 
</P>
<P>
	During the past several weeks, protesters have vandalized many  
McDonald's, sometimes dropping tons of manure outside the 
restaurants. The company says the union has the wrong target 
because 90 percent of the beef served in French McDonald's 
restaurants comes from cows raised in France. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald's France, hoping to ease farmers' concerns, has dropped  
its civil charges against Bove. The Court of Appeals in Montpellier 
is expected to decide Thursday whether to release him. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, smaller milk producers targeted big business,  
saying the wave of mergers that has swept through France this 
summer will continue to lower the prices they receive for their 
product. A farmer's association in Brittany cited, among others, 
this week's merger of two major French food retailers, Carrefour 
and Promodes. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the milk producers, fruit and vegetable farmers are  
concerned that large-scale distribution is hurting their profits. 
</P>
<P>
	In Marseilles on Monday night, fruit and vegetable producers  
dumped several tons of apples, tomatoes and peaches on the 
doorsteps of local politicians to press farm concerns. Similar 
protests were held in other cities. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 10:04:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Carolina Coast Dodges Hurricane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAGS HEAD, N.C. (AP) -- Hurricane Dennis weakened and slowed to a  
near halt today just off the coast, leaving relatively sparse 
property damage in its wake along the North Carolina seaboard. 
</P>
<P>
	``All in all, we did dodge a bullet,'' Danny Couch, owner of a  
shopping center in Buxton, said Monday evening. ``It was a pretty 
impressive system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A hurricane warning along the North Carolina coast was  
downgraded to a tropical storm warning but forecasters said it was 
too early to write off Dennis completely. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis, almost stationary this morning, could linger without  
moving much through Saturday, said Rod Gonski, forecaster at the 
National Weather Service office in Raleigh. ``It likes that moist, 
warm air on the Gulf Stream, and that's where it's centered now,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If it starts moving again, it's just as likely to head south or  
southwest as it is to reverse course toward the Outer Banks or 
southeastern Virginia, Gonski said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a chance it could come back, a little less than 50-50,  
but certainly worth talking about for sure,'' he said. ``There is 
nothing nudging it out in the ocean right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the uncertainty about the storm, people have started  
calling oceanfront hotels in southeastern Virginia to cancel 
reservations for Labor Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis ``puts a lot of things into sort of a holding pattern,''  
said Jimmy Capps, president of the Virginia Beach Hotel-Motel 
Association. ``What we probably need to do is give it another day 
and see where it's going to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. today, Dennis was nearly stationary about 150 miles  
east of Cape Hatteras, the National Hurricane Center said. Its 
motion was expected to continue to be slow and erratic at least 
into Wednesday morning. Its maximum sustained wind had slowed to 
about 75 mph, barely above the minimum wind speed for a hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to North Carolina, the tropical storm warning  
stretched northward to Chincoteague, Va., and a gale warning 
extended from there to Great Egg Inlet, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	For a time Monday, it seemed yet another hurricane might cross  
Cape Fear, directly south of Wilmington, just like Bertha and Fran 
in 1996 and Bonnie in 1998. Fran killed 25 people and caused up to 
$6 billion in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	But just as Dennis approached the Outer Banks, it began edging  
away. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm's eye stayed 60 miles from shore, but it still  
pummeled the coast with high wind and up to 8 inches of rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Two people died Monday in Onslow County in a head-on car  
collision blamed on poor visibility from wind and rain. A surfer's 
death Saturday at St. Augustine Beach, Fla., was attributed to 
heavy surf from Dennis. 
</P>
<P>
	In Dare County, a Coast Guard helicopter rescued four men from a  
small boat that was blown into a marsh after its engine failed in 
the 30-foot surf. 
</P>
<P>
	On Hatteras Island, the ocean washed out Route 12, the only  
highway along the narrow barrier island. Part of the road was 
closed near Kitty Hawk and up to 3 feet of sand covered the 
highway. 
</P>
<P>
	Farther south, the community of Cedar Island in Carteret County  
was cut off by high water, and Ocracoke Island was drenched by rain 
and waves. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole village was covered with water ... 6 feet above sea  
level,'' Hyde County Manager Jeff Credle said of the town of 
Ocracoke. 
</P>
<P>
	Damage on Ocracoke Island can't be estimated until the water  
recedes, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cindy Babbitt rode out the storm in her Hatteras Landing Marina,  
just across the inlet from Ocracoke. ``We're faring OK,'' she said. 
``I tried to look outside, but the rain is so sideways I can't 
see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Storm damage was light. New Hanover's losses totaled $217,000,  
while in Brunswick County, the collapse of a beachfront house at 
Ocean Isle Beach was the worst property damage reported, said Cecil 
Logan of the county emergency management office. 
</P>
<P>
	Utility companies said about 67,000 customers in coastal and  
inland counties lost power. The outages stretched as far inland as 
the Raleigh in central North Carolina. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
