<DOCNO> APW19990831.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 12:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schoolteachers in Detroit Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The city's schoolteachers went on strike today,  
canceling the first day of fall classes and dealing another blow to 
the effort to revive Detroit's underperforming schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike -- in part over such contentious reform proposals as  
merit pay -- will now test a state law that bars public school 
teachers from walking out. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rhetoric's the same. We don't have a contract and we don't  
see any real change,'' Mike Pahl, a science teacher at Spain 
School, said this morning. ``This is the only way we're going to 
get any real improvement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The district's 172,000 students were told to stay home today.  
Classes will not be held until officials know that enough of the 
district's 7,200 teachers will report for work. 
</P>
<P>
	The previous contract between the Detroit Federation of Teachers  
and the school system expired June 30, and an extension ran out 
Monday after teachers voted to reject their negotiators' 
recommendation for another extension. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have liked for them to follow my recommendations to go  
back to work for 10 days while I negotiate,'' union President John 
Elliott said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the walkout, talks to resumed at midafternoon today,  
said Greg Bowens, press secretary to Mayor Dennis Archer. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks are the first negotiations with the teachers since  
Detroit's elected school board was replaced earlier this year with 
one appointed by Archer. 
</P>
<P>
	The issues still unresolved included salary increases, merit  
pay, extended work days and a dress code. Teachers said merit pay 
was the most contentious issue. Many prefer to keep the old 
standards of experience, seniority and education; and say the real 
way to improve schools would be steps such as cutting class size. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody in our building deserves merit pay because everyone  
here's a good teacher,'' said Rita Greenberg, a second-grade 
teacher at Spain School. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have to say the rejection today does reflect an  
unwillingness by some teachers to engage themselves in significant 
change,'' said David Adamany, the district's interim chief 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the union's first walkout 1992. Under a 1994 Michigan  
law, public school employees who strike lose a day's pay in 
addition to being fined a day's pay. The law has never been tested. 
</P>
<P>
	Adamany said the school district will not seek a court  
injunction to try to force the teachers back to work, but is 
looking into the question of seeking fines. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor said in a statement that he is troubled by the strike  
vote after the work the district had done to prepare for the school 
year. Over the summer, district employees and private sector 
volunteers combined to make $80 million worth of repairs and 
renovations to the district's 263 buildings, some of them nearly 
100 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointed school board -- an idea pushed by Republican Gov.  
John Engler and approved by the Legislature -- followed decades of 
declining performance and alleged mismanagement and pork-barrel 
politics in Detroit schools. Supporters said an appointed school 
board would be better able to make difficult political decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Samona, a math teacher at Redford High School, said he  
would ideally like to be teaching today, but that working for a 
better contract was also important. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate really that we are not doing what we do  
best,'' he said. ``But we want to be back in the classroom with a 
fair contract.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The median salary for Detroit teachers with a bachelor's degree  
is $50,978 and with a master's degree is $58,494, said Janna 
Garrison, executive vice president of the Detroit Federation of 
Teachers. The median salary for teachers in Wayne County, and 
neighboring Oakland and Macomb counties is $55,700 for teachers 
with a bachelor's degree and $64,822 with a master's degree, she 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 15:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stocks Close Mixed; Dow Down 84.85 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed Tuesday as a report of  
continued growth in the manufacturing sector ignited fears of 
inflation and hurt blue-chip companies. Technology stocks, 
benefiting from a wave of new deals and products, moved higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 84.85 to close at  
10,829.28. The Dow suffered its fourth straight loss during a 
volatile session in which the index rose as much as 67 points and 
tumbled as much as 132 from Monday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The technology-dominated  
Nasdaq composite index rose 26.66 to 2,739.35, and the Standard &AMP; 
Poor's 500 fell 3.61 to 1,320.41. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks fell after the National Association of Purchasing  
Management inadvertently released its monthly survey on August 
manufacturing activity a day early. 
</P>
<P>
	The report showed the NAPM's monthly index of business activity  
rose to 54.2 percent from 53.4 percent in July. A reading above 50 
is a sign of growth in the industrial sector of the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Most troubling to stocks was a segment of the report that tracks  
prices paid by industry for raw materials and supplies. That figure 
rose to the highest levels since June 1995, and suggested inflation 
may be building as the economy continues to grow. 
</P>
<P>
	Many cyclical stocks, whose performance is tied to the fortunes  
of the broader economy, fell. Sears fell 2 to 37 1/2 and Caterpillar 
lost 2 7/8 to 56 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately Tuesday, the Conference Board said its consumer  
confidence index fell in August for the second straight month. The 
index, which measures consumers' likeliness to spend, edged down 
0.4 of a point, but still remains near the 30-year high reached in 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts expect the Labor Department's employment report, due on  
Friday, to provide the next spark in trading. Any suggestions that 
the U.S. economy is growing too quickly -- a trend that would be 
shown by the number of new jobs created -- could convince investors 
that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates for a third time 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a market searching for leadership,'' said Ned Riley,  
chief investment officer at BankBoston. ``Most people are waiting 
for the payrolls (job creation) report to formulate opinions about 
what the Fed might do next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Higher rates threaten stocks by cutting into corporate profits  
and increasing the value of alternative investments, like bonds. 
Tuesday, yields on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose to 6.06 
percent from 6.05 percent late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most oil companies were higher, including Dow components  
Chevron, up 1 to 92 5/16, and Exxon, up 1 1/16 to 78 7/8. Crude oil 
futures jumped sharply Monday after Venezuela, Mexico and Saudi 
Arabia decided against raising production. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks bucked the market's weakness as several  
companies announced new deals or new products. Hewlett Packard rose 
2 9/16 to 105 3/8 after the company unveiled several new printers and 
paper. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Nasdaq, Sun Microsystems rose 3 3/4 to 79 3/8 after the company  
bought Star Division Corp., a small maker of office productivity 
software. Analysts viewed the acquisition as an assault on 
Microsoft's dominance of the office software market. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple rose 3 3/16 to 65 1/4 after the company unveiled a new,  
high-speed desktop computer. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE composite volume totaled 1.01 billion shares, compared with  
731.46 million in the previous session. The pickup in volume 
heartened analysts, although many attributed the higher volume to 
end-of-the-month settling of portfolios and computer-driven 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.47 to 427.83.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas indexes were mostly lower. Japan's Nikkei stock average  
fell 2.7 percent. Germany's DAX index fell 2.3 percent, Britain's 
FT-SE 100 lost 2.0 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 1.5 percent 
lower. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
