<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 31, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Confidence Falls in August  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consumer confidence fell for the second straight  
month in August as higher interest rates started to weigh on the 
minds of more people, the Conference Board reported today. The 
private business group's index of consumer confidence, which 
measures consumers' likeliness to spend, edged down 0.4 of a point, 
less than analysts expected, to 135.8 from a revised 136.2 in July. 
The July figure originally was reported as 135.6. The July drop 
from a 30-year high of 139.0 marked the first decline after eight 
consecutive monthly gains. Consumer sentiment is an important 
economic indicator since consumer spending accounts for two-thirds 
of the nation's overall economic activity. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Turn Up; Dow Gains 34.51  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned higher after a lower opening this  
morning as continuing worries over interest rates continued. Just 
before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 34.51 
at 10,948.64. Broader stock indicators were generally up, too. The 
Nasdaq composite index was up 8.05 at 2,720.74. In a quiet week, 
with many Wall Street professionals taking vacations, many 
investors are willing to wait for each new piece of economic data 
to guide their decisions. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 11 a.m. EDT:  
Dow Industrials:        10948.64  + 34.51
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1238  Declines 1158  Unchgd  654
NYSE Volume:         168,520,580
Most Active NYSE issue:         Office Depot 10 1/8   -   3/8
S&AMP;P 500:         1330.05  + 6.03
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          777.05  + 1.84
Nasdaq Composite Index        2720.74  + 8.05
Gold(final) -    $254.20    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.

</P>
<P>
	Sun Micro Is Buying Star Division  
</P>
<P>
	PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Sun Microsystems is taking aim again at  
Microsoft's domination of the personal computer software market. 
Sun has announced the purchase of Fremont, Calif.-based Star 
Division Corp. The company makes a suite of office software called 
StarOffice, which includes e-mail, word processor, spreadsheet and 
presentation applications. Sun will offer the applications over the 
Internet for free as part of its ``StarPortal'' initiative. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Fixes Hotmail Flaw  
</P>
<P>
	REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Microsoft said a security flaw in its free  
Hotmail e-mail system that left millions of accounts vulnerable was 
patched before anyone was hurt by the breach. ``The good news is 
the Hotmail servers are back up and running now and the issue has 
been resolved,'' Deanna Sanford, lead product manager for MSN 
marketing, Microsoft Corp.'s Internet division, said Monday. ``We 
haven't heard any reports, any customers calling to say they were 
affected by this directly.'' Microsoft shut down its Hotmail e-mail 
system, which has 40 million accounts, for about two hours 
yesterday morning after discovering the flaw that made accounts 
vulnerable to outside access. The company said the trouble was 
fixed by 1 p.m. 

</P>
<P>
	Fruit of the Loom CEO Steps Down  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Fruit of the Loom Ltd. CEO William Farley is  
stepping down as part of a corporate restructuring at the clothing 
company, though he will stay on as chairman. The Chicago-based 
company also said yesterday that production and customer service 
difficulties will cause financial results for the rest of the year 
to fall significantly below analysts' expectations. Board member 
Dennis Bookshester will serve as acting chief executive officer of 
the company, best known for its underwear and active wear, until a 
replacement is found for Farley. The search is expected to take six 
to nine months. 

</P>
<P>
	Cigarette Packs To Jump 22 Cents  
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Smokers already hit hard by price increases  
stemming from the $206 billion tobacco settlement soon will be hit 
with another double-digit markup. The nation's leading cigarette 
manufacturers have raised wholesale prices 18 cents a pack, 
anticipating an upcoming excise tax increase and higher costs 
associated with their settlement with the states over health care 
costs. After markups, retail prices are likely to increase by about 
22 cents per pack, analysts said yesterday. Cigarettes now cost 
about $2.50 to $3.25 a pack, depending on the region of the 
country. 

</P>
<P>
	Jury: Exxon Doesn't Owe California  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A jury has rejected claims that Exxon Corp.  
owed the state of California $750 million for allegedly 
underpricing oil pumped from public lands. Superior Court jurors 
decided yesterday that the state received fair royalty payments 
during the 1980s for oil taken from the 8,000-acre Wilmington field 
off Long Beach. Jurors also said Exxon did not act in bad faith or 
manipulate oil prices. In its 13-year-old civil suit against Exxon, 
California claimed that the company had shortchanged the state 
about $350 million for oil pumped from 1981 to 1989. With interest, 
that sum would have grown to $750 million, said Larry Feldman, a 
lawyer who represented Exxon. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Steelmakers Appeal Penalty  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Three major Japanese steelmakers have lodged an  
appeal in the United States against the Commerce Department over an 
anti-dumping measure, officials said Tuesday. Nippon Steel Corp., 
Japan's largest steelmaker, and NKK Corp. appealed to the U.S. 
Court of International Trade today, after Kawasaki Steel Corp. 
filed with the same court yesterday. ``We are taking action since 
the anti-dumping investigation by the U.S. Commerce Department has 
been conducted under an unfair procedure,'' said Nippon Steel 
spokesman Takashi Kanke. 

</P>
<P>
	Asian Stock Markets Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower today,  
dragged down by another sharp fall on Wall Street. The Japanese 
225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 482.41 points, or 2.69 percent, 
to close at 17,436.56. In Hong Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index 
fell 205.89 points, or 1.5 percent, closing at 13,482.77. The 
Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index edged up 0.356 point to 
567.026. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:  
</P>
