<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras Exits Open With Back Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pete Sampras withdrew from the U.S. Open today  
before his first match because of a back injury, delaying his bid 
for tennis history. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-time champion has a small herniated disc in his lower  
back and said he injured himself hitting a return during practice 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt my back just got ... stabbed by a knife,'' Sampras  
said. ``I immediately stopped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras, the world's No. 1 player and seeded first at the Open,  
said he would be out for ``quite some time.'' Later in his news 
conference, he said he would miss at least a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras is bidding for a record 13th Grand Slam men's singles  
title. He tied Roy Emerson with 12 major championships by winning 
his sixth Wimbledon title in July. 
</P>
<P>
	After injuring himself, he canceled Monday's practice and asked  
that his first-round match at the Open be delayed, believing an 
extra day of rest would help. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Brian Hainline, the U.S. Open medical director, suggested  
Sampras undergo a CAT scan and an MRI, which revealed the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not allowing him to move as he should,'' Hainline said.  
``He has some pain, but he's completely normal otherwise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hainline examined Sampras and said the tear in the disc could  
have worsened, jeopardizing his future. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know we caught it early and he should recover fully,''  
Hainline said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras was to have played Marat Safin of Russia on Wednesday.  
His spot in the Open draw was taken by Mikael Tillstrom of Sweden, 
ranked 130th in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know that he always want to play,'' Hainline said. ``So  
ultimately he made the decision on whether to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras retired during a match two weeks ago in Indianapolis  
with a hip injury. 
</P>
<P>
	He played several additional tournaments last fall in a  
successful attempt to finish No. 1 for a record sixth straight 
time. But he then skipped the Australian Open in January, citing 
fatigue. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his success on the Open's hardcourts, the 28-year-old  
star has been beset by injury and illness at Flushing Meadows. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, he retired from his semifinal against eventual winner  
Patrick Rafter with an injured thigh. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Sampras vomited on the court during his five-set  
victory against Alex Corretja but recovered and went on to win the 
Open. 
</P>
<P>
	This marks the second time this year a top-seeded man has pulled  
out of a Grand Slam tournament before stepping onto the court. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Marcelo Rios of Chile pulled out of the Australian  
Open because of a stress fracture in his back. He didn't return to 
the tour until March. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time the No. 1 seed withdrew from the U.S.  
championships was in 1950 when Budge Patty injured his ankle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
