<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Adobe, Xerox Announce Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Adobe Systems Inc. and Xerox Corp.  
announced an alliance Tuesday that will help publishers and authors 
sell their books and publications over the Internet in secure file 
format that prevents piracy. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal integrates Adobe's PDF file format with Xerox's  
ContentGuard rights management software, which prevents 
unauthorized copying of the file. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers who download books or publications can print them out  
or view them on the screen with Adobe's Acrobat software. Adobe has 
updated Acrobat with a feature called ``Web Buy,'' which allows 
users to buy encrypted PDF, or portable data format, files over the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Adobe, based in San Jose, says it has distributed more than 100  
million copies of Acrobat, which enables users to view documents 
exactly as intended on different computer platforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox, based in Stamford, Conn., is a leader in the document  
business, integrating fax machines, printers, scanners, and 
copiers, as well as PC and workstation software. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
