<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns' Rainer a 'Hard-Nosed' Player </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEREA, Ohio (AP) -- Wali Rainer's nose split wide open for the  
first time back in Pop Warner when he planted his helmet in some 
poor 10-year-old quarterback's chest. 
</P>
<P>
	Now every year around this time, Rainer cuts the bridge of his  
nose. It's become a ritual, and a badge of courage, signaling to 
the Cleveland Browns rookie linebacker that football season has 
arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	``It always happens,'' Rainer said. ``I hit with my face, not  
with my helmet. It helps me coming off blocks. I think of myself as 
a hard-nosed player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rainer had better be. He's the man with the challenge of  
replacing Chris Spielman at middle linebacker. 
</P>
<P>
	Spielman reluctantly retired on Monday after being momentarily  
paralyzed from a blindside block during Cleveland's exhibition game 
against Chicago last weekend. His departure strips the expansion 
Browns of their biggest-name player, their defensive leader, their 
heart and soul. 
</P>
<P>
	Rainer, who has already shown some of Spielman's traits -- he's  
intense, hardworking and aggressive -- thinks he can fill Spielman's 
shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ready for this,'' said Rainer, taken by the Browns in the  
fourth round out of Virginia. ``I'm ready to step up. I provide the 
team intensity and hard work. I've been a linebacker my whole life. 
I'm ready to prove to everyone that I can play the position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rainer already sounds like Spielman. Now he has to show he can  
play like him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns were delighted when the 6-foot-2, 235-pound Rainer  
slipped to the fourth round in April's college draft. Cleveland 
needed to address some other needs before worrying about a middle 
linebacker, and in Rainer they think they found a good one. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were very pleased when Wali was there,'' Browns coach Chris  
Palmer said. ``Some people had some reservations about him. But 
when you get him between the white lines he's quite a player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rainer began making an impression on the Browns from the moment  
he walked on the field for his first practice. He didn't act like a 
rookie, taking command of the second-unit defense by barking out 
the defensive signals and making plays all over the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far I've been impressed,'' said outside linebacker Jamir  
Miller, who will now play alongside Rainer. ``He's been flying 
around, he doesn't lose his cool. I think he'll be a good 
linebacker in this league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And if he's destined to live up to Spielman's name, maybe  
everyone should learn Rainer's name -- first name, that is. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not Wally. It's pronounced Wah-LEE. His father, James, gave  
him the name, which translates in Arabic to protector, leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it fits my personality,'' he said. ``My father  
couldn't have picked a better name.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rainer has made 14 solo tackles in the Browns' first four  
exhibition games. After Spielman was helped off the field last 
Saturday, Rainer came in with the starting defense and on his first 
play stopped running back Edgar Bennett for a 1-yard loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Rainer knows all eyes will be on the middle of the Browns'  
defense as he tries to replace Spielman, a football icon he only 
had as a teammate for a short time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could go on and on talking about what I learned from him,''  
Rainer said. ``The biggest thing is that you play every play like 
it's your last. He did it in practice and in the game. I want to be 
the same player that he's been for a lot of years and get the 
respect from the around the league he got.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
