<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Named in Free Speech Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush won a victory in one  
lawsuit even as he found himself the target of another. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge on Monday dismissed a subpoena that sought Bush's  
testimony in a whistleblower lawsuit filed by the fired head of the 
Texas Funeral Service Commission, Eliza May. While the governor 
isn't a defendant in the case, May alleges she lost her job over an 
investigation of a Houston-based funeral company that had given 
Bush campaign contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	Her lawyers said the Republican presidential front-runner was a  
``co-conspirator'' in the case. But Ms. May is a former Texas 
Democratic Party treasurer, and District Judge John Dietz threw out 
her subpoena after Attorney General John Cornyn called the lawsuit 
political. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a search for the truth. This is about harassment.  
This is about politics,'' Cornyn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Bush was named in a lawsuit Monday accusing him of  
violating the free speech rights of environmental protestors at the 
governor's mansion. 
</P>
<P>
	The environmentalists allege that Bush has given state troopers  
``unbridled discretion'' to target protesters picketing in front of 
the mansion on a public sidewalk. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Texas Constitution does not stop at the sidewalk in front  
of the governor's mansion,'' said Rick Abraham, executive director 
of Texans United, one of the groups suing Bush. Abraham said he was 
arrested twice. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush aides say the protesters strayed from a designated protest  
area. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decision regarding protesters was made by the Department  
of Public Safety to protect the safety of pedestrians and 
protesters around the Governor's Mansion,'' Bush spokesman Ray 
Sullivan said. ``They were concerned that protesters blocking 
sidewalks could result in people walking in the street or otherwise 
jeopardizing their safety.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The arrests took place four times -- March 11, March 29, April 19  
and May 25 -- and in each case the Travis County's district 
attorney's office dropped charges of blocking an entry way. 
</P>
<P>
	Previous governors of both parties allowed protesters to picket  
on the sidewalk, Abraham said. ``People were not arrested. Not 
until George Bush decided to run for president. Then the arrests 
started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. May's lawyers wanted to question Bush about the  
investigation of Service Corp. International, which resulted in 
recommended fines of $445,000 that the company is fighting. The 
company denies wrongdoing and says the commission misinterpreted 
state embalming law. 
</P>
<P>
	She alleges that SCI, whose political action committee gave Bush  
$45,000 in 1996 and 1997, worked with Bush's staff to interfere 
with an investigation of the company. Her lawyers said they would 
push forward with the case and question key Bush aides, including 
the governor's chief of staff and his general counsel, about the 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The judge has, in essence, ruled that he wants us to seek the  
evidence from others who were involved in the matter at issue. We 
will be doing that,'' said Chuck Herring, one of Ms. May's 
attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press reporter Renae Merle  
contributed to this story. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
