<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Militiamen Block Roads in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Angry militiamen blocked roads and  
stopped separatists from boarding planes and ferries out of East 
Timor's capital today, amid expectations that the Indonesian 
loyalists lost a vote on the troubled territory's future. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of machete-wielding, gun-toting militia members  
returned to the streets, menacing villages and parts of the 
capital, Dili, and raising fears that they might launch a new 
campaign of terror against those who favor independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Pro-Jakarta militias have been battling separatists for decades  
in the impoverished region, which Indonesia invaded in 1975, 
shortly after Portugal pulled out as colonial ruler. The militias 
are supported by elements of the Indonesian military, which have 
business interests in the province. 
</P>
<P>
	The militias say they want to stop independence leaders from  
leaving to avoid a political vacuum that could plunge the territory 
into chaos, similar to what followed Portuguese withdrawal. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. spokesman David Wimhurst said in Dili that he could not  
confirm a news report that three local U.N. staff members had been 
killed there. The slaying of one staffer after polls closed Monday 
was widely reported at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	In Geneva, Switzerland, the U.N. refugee agency said it was  
talking to Australian officials about setting up a base in the city 
of Darwin ``in case some major aid operation is needed in East 
Timor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said it fears a new flood of people could be  
displaced despite Monday's relatively peaceful referendum. 
</P>
<P>
	Police and U.N. advisers spent several hours negotiating the  
safe passage of a 17-vehicle convoy trying to leave Gleno in Ermera 
district, about 28 miles southwest to the capital, Dili. 
</P>
<P>
	In the town of Hera, 10 miles south of Dili, hundreds of militia  
members armed with machetes and homemade guns roamed the streets 
searching for independence activists. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't try to come in here. It is very dangerous,'' said one of  
the militiamen. 
</P>
<P>
	The blockade took place as the United Nations estimated that  
98.6 percent of East Timor's 438,000 registered voters had taken 
part in Monday's ballot. Another 13,000 voted overseas. The ballot 
gave Timorese the choice between remaining part of Indonesia as an 
autonomous region or independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Poll observers and independent activists say the high voter  
participation points to a big victory for those wanting to break 
free of Indonesia, which invaded in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	President B.J. Habibie said today the election was ``very good,  
peaceful and fair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important thing is that we have to honor the decision  
of the East Timorese people,'' Habibie told reporters in Jakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	Eurico Guterres, the leader of Dili's Aitarak militia, said  
pro-independence students and members of the political elite could 
not leave East Timor from today on. 
</P>
<P>
	Roadblocks were reportedly set up on highways leading out of the  
territory. Departing independence activists had been stopped and 
turned around, witnesses said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the airport, one witness said the militias ``stood outside  
the terminal at the airport and grabbed tickets out of the hands of 
passengers.'' The person spoke on condition of anonymity, fearing 
reprisals. 
</P>
<P>
	Five militia members chased an ethnic Chinese family out of the  
terminal after they had checked into a flight bound for the 
Indonesian tourist island of Bali. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian airport police ordered the gang members to stop but  
were ignored. 
</P>
<P>
	Guterres said the blockade would last until at least the result  
of the vote is announced by the United Nations on or before Sept. 
7. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said today that Indonesia will hand  
over the interim administration of East Timor to the United Nations 
-- not to Portugal, which hastily pulled out of their troubled 
colony nearly a quarter-century ago before Indonesia invaded. 
</P>
<P>
	A 25-member reconciliation commission, made up of pro- and  
anti-independence representatives was scheduled to convene its 
inaugural meeting today, but the session fell apart when the 
militias walked out, saying they'd been the targets of U.N. bias 
and an ``international conspiracy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have withdrawn from these important negotiations with  
UNAMET,'' said Basilio Dias Araujo, a spokesman for one of the 
militias, using the acronym for the United Nations' elections team 
in East Timor. ``Clearly UNAMET has violated the polling 
regulations which it itself had laid down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations today denied the accusations, but said any  
wrongdoing by staff members would be investigated by an independent 
electoral body. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people have expressed themselves massively,'' Wimhurst  
said. ``It is imperative that everybody lays down their arms and 
ceases all violent activity as it is completely futile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, hundreds of blue plastic ballot boxes were brought into  
the provincial capital, Dili, by white U.N. helicopters from tiny 
villages across the half-island territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Counting is expected to start Wednesday at the city's museum.  
Poll organizers say the centralized vote count will ensure voter 
secrecy and lessen the risk of reprisals after months of violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Observers, including officials from rival factions, will be  
allowed to monitor the count. 
</P>
<P>
	However, they will be sworn to secrecy to prevent false and  
incomplete results being leaked, said Carina Pirelli, the chief of 
the U.N.'s Electoral Assistance Division. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
