<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Finances Eyed in Gingrich Divorce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA, Ga. (AP) -- Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich wants to  
use a financial agreement he worked out with his wife more than 10 
years ago to settle his pending divorce. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich filed a request Friday in Cobb County Superior Court  
asking a judge to rely on a separation agreement signed by the 
couple and notarized in December 1987. There is no indication the 
agreement was ever filed. 
</P>
<P>
	The request comes about three weeks after Gingrich's wife,  
Marianne, asked a judge to freeze the couple's assets until their 
divorce is final. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gingrich claims her husband transferred ``substantial  
portions of certain valuable assets'' before filing for divorce. 
Gingrich has denied the allegation. A hearing on her request is 
scheduled Sept. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	The separation agreement -- worked out during a six-year  
separation -- called for Mrs. Gingrich to get $2,000 a month for six 
months, control over money market and checking accounts and the 
couple's 1984 Ford Thunderbird. It made Gingrich responsible for 
the couple's bank loans and a Hecht's department store account. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple also divided the furniture in their Washington  
residence and in their apartment in Jonesboro. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple married in 1981, just months after Gingrich divorced  
his first wife, Jackie Battley. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich's divorce attorney, Thomas Browning, said Mrs. Gingrich  
called her husband on his birthday in June 1987 to tell him she was 
leaving him. Gingrich, he said, returned to Georgia to find an 
empty home. 
</P>
<P>
	``All she left was a television and a guest bed,'' Browning  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Gingriches maintained separate residences for six  
years before reconciling in late 1993 or early 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich resigned as House Speaker after Republicans lost seats  
in the 1998 elections. He again separated from his wife May 10 and 
filed for divorce July 29, amid allegations of an affair with 
33-year-old congressional aide Callista Bisek. 
</P>
<P>
	Randolph Evans, Gingrich's attorney, has denied the allegation.  
</P>
<P>
	In court papers filed Friday, Gingrich's attorneys indicated  
they would not oppose the deposition of Ms. Bisek, which is 
tentatively scheduled for Sept. 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gingrich, a county planner and business consultant from  
Ohio, referred questions pertaining to the divorce to attorney John 
Mayoue. Mayoue was out of his office Monday and could not be 
reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich now runs a political consulting firm.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
