<HEADLINE> Teens Shop for Back-to-School Wear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Forget worries about tough teachers  
and too much homework. 
</P>
<P>
	With the start of the school year around the corner, kids today  
are more concerned about one thing: What should they wear? 
</P>
<P>
	Are flare jeans in or out? What pant styles look best rolled up  
at the bottom? Is orange the ``hot'' color? Are flower appliques 
acceptable in the fall? 
</P>
<P>
	The back-to-school shopping season is well under way, and the  
nation's stores and malls are filled with parents and children 
seeking out the must-have fashion items of the new school year. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to the booming economy, retailers are expecting sales to  
be particularly strong this year as shoppers buy up everything from 
new clothes and shoes to notebooks and pens. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent study of 1,500 parents and teens by American Express  
found that families planned to spend $455 per child on 
back-to-school purchases, up 12 percent from a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	And even with all of the recent hype about the Internet, the  
survey found that only 4 percent of teens were making some of their 
back-to-school purchases online. The rest were heading straight to 
the mall. 
</P>
<P>
	One recent afternoon, a reporter checked out what's hot for  
back-to-school with a group of teens spending the day at The 
Westchester, a mall in the New York suburb of White Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	``We could spend days at the mall getting ready to go back to  
school. It's really important to look good the first few days we 
get back,'' said 16-year-old Jenny Fleisher. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Fleisher's first trip to the mall for back-to-school  
shopping, one of many visits that will come in the next few weeks. 
She was accompanied by other soon-to-be 11th graders -- Jamie 
Horowitz and Amanda Kremer -- her best friends and fashion 
consultants. 
</P>
<P>
	The first scream of shopping bliss came five minutes into the  
five-hour outing and it could be heard across the selling floor 
</P>
<P>
	``That is soooo cute!'' bellowed Fleisher, pointing to a pair of  
black flared pants her friend was holding up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to try them on,'' said Horowitz. ``Love them.''  
</P>
<P>
	Yes, flared pants were the big thing of the day. Also popular  
were khakis, or anything with cargo pockets or drawstrings. The 
three young women combed through hundreds of pairs of pants in 
stores such as Nordstrom, Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, J. Crew and Guess. 
</P>
<P>
	As for when to cuff the bottoms of their pants, the group said  
it was OK to roll up those with straight legs but never those with 
a flare. 
</P>
<P>
	When it came to color, orange was it. Really it. All they wanted  
was orange -- whether it was solid or just a hint of the bold color 
in belts, shirts and shoes. At Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, khakis with an 
orange accent around the ankle got big cheers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The orange makes it soooo cool and trendy,'' Horowitz said.  
``I bought a belt with orange yesterday and just love it. It is so 
different from anything I own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forget wearing sleeves that come down to the wrist. Every shirt  
that they eyed had cropped sleeves -- most coming slightly below the 
elbow. Some came in T-shirt material, while others buttoned up. All 
had a touch of Lycra to make them stretchy. 
</P>
<P>
	Appliques were also popular -- on the neckline, on the ankle,  
along the sleeve. Flowers, yes. Asian designs, very much yes. But 
``nothing too big and no big labels. We hate big labels,'' said 
Kremer. 
</P>
<P>
	Then onto shoes. Adidas and Puma sneakers -- resembling those  
worn in the 1980s -- were must-haves, not for phys ed but to wear to 
class. Also noteworthy were platform shoes with super-size heels: 
``They make me so tall but who cares. They look good. I can't 
resist,'' Fleisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time they left the mall, the three -- whose bills were  
being paid by their parents -- had purchased five pairs of pants, 
seven shirts, four pairs of shoes, one beaded necklace and one MAC 
lipstick. Total for the day: almost $800. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not bad for a day's work,'' Fleisher said. ``But don't think  
we are done. We've just begun to scratch the surface. Once we go to 
school, I'm sure we will see more things we like and then we'll be 
running back here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the 11th graders were buying up a storm, Fleisher's  
12-year-old sister, Sara, and her two friends were also circling 
the mall. It was the first time that they had gone back-to-school 
shopping without their parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the older girls, they went for the casual look.  
Oversized, stretch athletic pants with matching shirts. They loved 
sweatshirts, especially those with hoods. And anything fleece -- 
vests, pants, shirts, hats -- was an absolute. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all about being comfortable,'' said Tiffany Betz, a  
seventh grader from Harrison, N.Y. ``I like looking good but I 
don't want to wear stuff that isn't comfortable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sara Fleisher made the big purchase of the group, buying a gray  
and black fleece vest and a long-sleeve shirt from Abercrombie &AMP; 
Fitch. Both items had a huge ``Abercrombie'' labels on them. 
</P>
<P>
	But before she made the purchase, she consulted with shopping  
buddy Krista Ventura, who is considered one of the fashionable 
girls in school. 
</P>
<P>
	``Labels are soooo important,'' Ventura said. ``You want  
everyone to know where you are buying it, especially Abercrombie 
because everyone likes this store.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the other things that the younger girls were hot to have:  
$14 glass ball bracelets. The different colors mean different 
things -- intelligence, money, serenity, happiness. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are definitely what everyone will have when we get to  
school and I didn't have any, so I decided that I'd get two,'' Sara 
Fleisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also popular -- and a must-have for the first day back at school  
-- are tattoos. The three were searching for cool temporary tattoos 
to apply to their upper arms and ankles. 
</P>
<P>
	But the big spending was really left to the older girls. The  
12-year-olds did lots of browsing, but were still nervous about 
forking over big bucks without their parents' consent. They ended 
the day spending about $170. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still like shopping with my mom,'' said Sara Fleisher.  
``Sometimes I still need her input.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
