<HEADLINE> Blue Jays Sign Borders As Free Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Pat Borders, Toronto's World Series MVP in 1992,  
signed as a free agent with the Blue Jays on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Borders, who was released by the Cleveland Indians earlier  
Tuesday, will join the Blue Jays on Wednesday night. The 
35-year-old catcher played in six games with Indians, hitting .300 
with three RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Jays also announced they will call up right-hander John  
Hudek from Triple A Syracuse. 
</P>
<P>
	To make room on the 40-man roster, the Blue Jays transferred  
infielder Craig Grebeck and outfielder Rob Butler to the 60-day 
disabled list. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 16:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colts Release Lineman Leeuwenburg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Indianapolis continued rebuilding its  
offense Tuesday with the release of Jay Leeuwenburg, the Colts' 
most experienced offensive lineman. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts got down to the league roster limit by terminating the  
contract of Leeuwenburg, who lost his starting job during training 
camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Leeuwenburg, who started 37 consecutive games for the Colts,  
made every offensive snap last year at center for a line that 
allowed only 22 sacks. 
</P>
<P>
	He was replaced in the starting lineup by second-year pro Larry  
Moore, who was moved from guard. Moore's spot on the starting line 
was taken over by Waverly Jackson, another second-year lineman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prior to the start of training camp, back in May and in early  
June, we brought Jay in and told him that we were going to rotate 
him with Larry and Waverly,'' Colts coach Jim Mora said. ``We told 
him that we felt like we had some good young offensive linemen here 
that we wanted to take a long look at. 
</P>
<P>
	``We told Jay that he would have the chance to compete for a  
starting job. But as camp progressed, we decided that we wanted to 
go with Larry at center and Waverly at guard. We thought that they 
had played well enough through training camp to have the 
opportunity to start for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mora said that the decision to let the veteran Leeuwenburg go  
was not an easy one. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since I've been here and long before that, Jay has been a  
consummate professional for the Indianapolis Colts,'' the coach 
said. ``It was a tough decision to let Jay go. ... He's been a true 
leader on this ballclub since he's been here. 
</P>
<P>
	``But, I told Jay that the guys we have are playing better at  
this time of their careers than he was. ... That's why we made the 
move. It was not a decision made for the future. We're looking at 
it as a now decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leeuwenburg was scheduled to be paid $1.3 million in the last  
year of the four-year contract he signed in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``He handled it very professionally,'' Mora said of the release.  
``He accepted it with a lot of class. I know it was not easy for 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leeuwenburg, 30, was starting his eighth NFL season. He had  
started 48 consecutive games for the Chicago Bears before signing 
with the Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	The release gives the Colts an offensive line with two players  
starting their third year in the league and three second-year 
performers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts have 68 players on the roster, including three exempt  
from Tuesday's limit of 65 because they played for NFL Europe. The 
team must be down to 53 players, including the three NFL Europe 
exemptions, by Sunday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
