<DOCNO> APW19990831.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 08:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charismatic Ready for Life As Stud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERSAILLES, Ky. (AP) -- Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes  
winner Charismatic, who broke down near the finish of the Belmont 
Stakes, is getting ready for his career as a stud horse. 
</P>
<P>
	Lane's End Farm said Charismatic, who was co-bred by Lane's End  
owner William Farish and is owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, arrived 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lane's End expects to begin hand-walking the colt this week. His  
stud career begins next year, and his stud fee will be $35,000 for 
a live foal. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic ran twice in $62,500 claiming races last winter,  
then emerged unexpectedly as the best of the 3-year-old crop, 
winning the Lexington Stakes, Kentucky Derby and Preakness in 
succession. 
</P>
<P>
	Going into the Belmont on June 9, the D. Wayne Lukas-trained  
colt was poised to be the first horse to sweep the Triple Crown 
since Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Belmont, Charismatic led with an eighth of a mile to go,  
but took a bad step and fractured his left foreleg as Lemon Drop 
Kid swept by to win. Charismatic finished third, 1 1/2 lengths back. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors have said the fracture, which shattered Charismatic's  
cannon bone and broke his sesamoid, easily could have proved fatal 
had the bone broken the skin. They praised jockey Chris Antley for 
dismounting quickly and lifting Charismatic's injured leg to take 
weight off it. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic had surgery and has been recuperating in Lukas' barn  
at Belmont. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 07:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Contract War in Options Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The same competitive threat from electronic  
trading systems that has taken U.S. stock exchanges by storm has 
emerged recently as the catalyst for dramatic changes in the more 
obscure world of options trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The planned opening in January 2000 of an alternative electronic  
options exchange -- called the International Securities Exchange -- 
has prompted three of the four existing options exchanges to 
encroach on one another's territory, breaking a long-standing 
policy of allowing each exchange exclusive trading rights certain 
popular options. The policy is known as single listing. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, the Chicago Board Options Exchange, the  
largest of the four bricks and mortar exchanges, fired the first 
salvo when it began trading Dell Computer Corp.'s options, one of 
the most widely traded contracts in the options market, which for 
years had traded exclusively through the Philadelphia Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	CBOE Chairman William Brodsky said the decision to open a  
competitive war was easy. ``We wanted to control our own destiny,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the face of pending competition from the electronic exchange,  
CBOE officials felt they should reach out for market share wherever 
the opportunity presented itself, Brodsky explained. 
</P>
<P>
	Options are generally used to hedge bets against stock  
investments. An option allows the purchaser the right to buy or 
sell stock at a specific price for a fraction of the cost of buying 
the actual stock. 
</P>
<P>
	For more than two decades, the four U.S. options exchanges -- the  
CBOE, the Philadelphia exchange, the American Stock Exchange and 
the Pacific Stock Exchange -- had agreed not to list each others' 
popular contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry claimed the policy came about and stayed in place  
because the exchanges saved money by not having to build the 
support systems needed to trade all of the existing popular 
contracts. Instead, each exchange was content to have a handful of 
singly-listed, high-volume contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	The single-listing policy has recently come under scrutiny,  
however, from the U.S. Justice Department, which is investigating 
whether the exchanges colluded to keep the policy in place in order 
eliminate competition and artificially keep trading costs high. The 
exchanges have denied collusion. 
</P>
<P>
	But whatever arrangement existed between the exchanges became  
moot when the ISE announced plans to open an electronic exchange 
where investors will be able to trade 600 of the most popular 
options cheaper and faster than on the traditional exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia exchange retaliated immediately against the  
CBOE's encroachment by introducing trading in Coca Cola Co. and 
Apple Computer Inc. options. Coca Cola's options had previously 
been exclusive to the CBOE, and Apple to the Amex. The Amex, in 
turn, also began trading Dell options. 
</P>
<P>
	And the war has escalated since then, with the participating  
exchanges upping the ante almost daily by listing more and more 
previously singly-listed contracts. The Pacific Exchange has so far 
stayed out of the fray. 
</P>
<P>
	The demise of the single-listing policy was inevitable once the  
ISE filed with the Securities and Exchange to become an options 
exchange, said Michael Schwartz, chief options strategist at 
investment bank CIBC Oppenheimer and chairman of the Committee on 
Options Proposals, an industry group. 
</P>
<P>
	``It all boils down to competition,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The effect of the ISE has been felt in other areas of the  
options industry, as well. For example, the traditional exchanges 
have slashed their trading fees by as much as 30 percent in order 
to retain customers once the alternative exchange opens. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes are being driven by options trading's increasing  
popularity. Trading volume in equity options nationwide has nearly 
doubled this decade, to 406 million in 1998 from 210 million in 
1990, according to CBOE statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there are potential pitfalls to the increased level of  
competition in the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Some options experts argue that the options market could become  
too fragmented as exchanges vie for market share among popular 
contracts. Since the various exchanges aren't currently linked, 
investors may have trouble finding the best price available. The 
same criticism has been leveled at the electronic stock trading 
systems that are putting competitive pressure on the New York Stock 
Exchange and the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have fragmented markets, getting the best execution  
is difficult without linkage,'' said Joseph Stefanelli, executive 
vice president for derivatives securities at the Amex. ``And the 
more markets are fragmented, the more difficult it is to access the 
best market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is also concern that the computer system used by the  
exchanges to distribute price quotes will become overloaded if the 
system has to carry data on every contract traded on each exchange. 
In the past, single listings held the volume of information in 
check. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
