<DOCNO> APW19990831.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 23:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Competitors Snipe at New Dictionary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- The first new English dictionary in 30  
years is being billed as more contemporary, more global and more 
tuned-in than the hidebound tomes collecting dust on the shelf. 
</P>
<P>
	Assembled by 320 editors and consultants in 20 countries via --  
you guessed it -- e-mail, the Encarta World English Dictionary 
promises to define the pop culture of ``yadda yadda yadda'' 
alongside the linguistic legacy of Shakespeare. 
</P>
<P>
	But rival publishers say the new dictionary backed by the  
resources of Microsoft may be a little too hip -- why, they wonder, 
is Madonna the pop singer placed before Madonna the mother of 
Christ? 
</P>
<P>
	``If the name Microsoft provides the user with no more  
guarantees about the reliability of its dictionaries than ... its 
software, then people will not take the dictionaries to be 
particularly authoritative,'' said Geoffrey Nunberg, a Stanford 
University linguist and chairman of a usage panel at competing 
American Heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	The established publishers began sniping at Encarta shortly  
after its arrival on store shelves last month. They scoffed at such 
editorial decisions as including a picture of Microsoft founder 
Bill Gates, but not ones of Adolf Hitler or even President John F. 
Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a tight market,'' said Garrett Kiely, an executive at  
Microsoft's dictionary publishing partner, St. Martin's Press. ``We 
are a new entry into the dictionary world. Microsoft is a big entry 
into it. People get their toes stepped on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Selling for $50, the print version of Encarta directly competes  
with ``The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language,'' 
which came out in 1969 in response to criticism that 
Merriam-Webster's dictionary was getting too trendy. 
</P>
<P>
	The new dictionary defines such neologisms as nose stud,  
no-fly-zone, and the yadda yadda yadda of Seinfeld fame. But 
critics fault a preachy tone that labels words like ``crone'' and 
``butch'' as offensive but dares not even define them. 
</P>
<P>
	They also fault some outright mistakes. Union Gen. George Gordon  
Meade, for example, is incorrectly identified as a Revolutionary 
War soldier; he fought in the Civil War. 
</P>
<P>
	In perhaps the greatest irony, some critics wonder why Microsoft  
didn't push the technology further. Why not have a much larger 
Internet dictionary with links to demonstrate a word's context? Why 
not provide access to much more of Encarta's database, with almost 
limitless illustrations, audio and video? 
</P>
<P>
	``As technology has changed our lives, something as traditional  
as a dictionary hasn't changed all that much,'' Kiely said. Thus, 
Encarta is full of ``quick definitions'' that summarize, in bold 
face, the longer definitions ``in a bow to the way we live today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As far as the other criticisms, Kiely said typos are inevitable  
in a work of 3.5 million words and that the many flags for 
offensive language simply reflect today's realities. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps predictably, Merriam-Webster, the Springfield-based  
industry leader, has also given Encarta a poor review. 
</P>
<P>
	``While it's always exciting to see something new come on the  
market ... we're pretty confident that the Merriam-Webster 
Collegiate Dictionary brings with it an air of authority and years 
of experience,'' said Deborah Burns, the marketing director for 
Merriam-Webster. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiely points to the technological advances of the new dictionary  
as one of its benefits: With Encarta built entirely on a computer 
database, it will be easy to update the print or CD-ROM versions. 
</P>
<P>
	But he acknowledged it will be hard for Microsoft to crack the  
market: ``Americans keep their first dictionary for a very long 
time.'' 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
