<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Inconvenient, Not Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOREHEAD CITY, N.C. (AP) -- The 50-foot oak in Patty Russell's  
front yard survived more than a century of hurricanes. More than 
that, it had survived generations of kids playing in its gnarled, 
moss-encrusted branches. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had nails right here and nails right here, and we would use  
the nails to climb up,'' the Morehead City woman said. ``We never 
built a tree house in it because Daddy wouldn't let us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Hurricane Dennis passed through, the massive tree with the  
10 1/2-foot girth lay against her house, broken off just about the 
ground, one of its branches through her kitchen window. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to miss my tree,'' Mrs. Russell said Monday as her  
13-year-old son, Stephen, sawed off stray limbs. ``A lot of 
memories tied up in that tree.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But as bad as Dennis was for the Russells, he was little more  
than a blowhard compared to past North Carolina storms like Fran, 
Bonnie and Bertha. 
</P>
<P>
	``A mullet blow is what we call this,'' Jeff Turnage, a line  
serviceman for Carolina Power &AMP; Light Co., said as he surveyed 
downed power lines in Atlantic Beach on Monday. ``Just a lot of 
wind and rain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although some residents of North Carolina's fragile Outer Banks  
were surprised by the high winds and rain, there was a sense that 
things could have been a lot worse along the state's southern 
coastline. 
</P>
<P>
	But forecasters warned not to write off Dennis too quickly. The  
National Hurricane Center in Miami said Dennis would stall at sea 
for a few days, then come back toward the coast possibly near 
Norfolk, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Dennis steered mostly clear of southeastern Virginia,  
but caused blustery conditions that left flooded streets, scattered 
power outages and other minor damage behind in Hampton Roads. 
</P>
<P>
	Tides in Virginia Beach were at about 6 feet, or a couple feet  
above normal, and there were reports of minor coastal flooding, 
said Mark Marchbank, deputy coordinator of emergency services for 
Virginia Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	In Norfolk and Chesapeake, flood waters made several  
intersections impassable. 
</P>
<P>
	Langley Air Force Base in Hampton planned to send 36 F-15  
fighter jets to Grissom Air Reserve Base in Indiana. But the 
crosswinds were so high that the planes could not leave and had to 
be tied down on the flight line instead, Langley spokeswoman Lt. 
Dawnita Bruner said. Fifteen jets were moved to hangars. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy sometimes sends ships to sea during bad weather, but  
Monday decided to let ships ride out the storm at their piers at 
the Norfolk Naval Station. Sailors were on standby in case plans 
changed. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderous surf and lethal rip tides from Dennis also closed  
beaches up and down the Maryland and Delaware coasts. Most people 
abandoned the beaches for shelter from the wind, and those that 
wanted to test the rough water found themselves barred by 
lifeguards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our water's completely closed,'' said Capt. Tim Ferry of the  
Bethany Beach, Del., beach patrol. ``We're not even allowing people 
to wade in the shallow stuff because that tide is so dangerous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In North Carolina's Morehead City, an empty tin grain silo on  
U.S. Highway 70 blew down, and the Sanitary Fish Market lost its 
awning and some roof. Down the road at the 60s and 70s Museum, a 
plywood cutout of late rocker Jim Morrison took a ride on the 
storm. 
</P>
<P>
	The high winds overturned newspaper boxes and garbage cans in  
Beaufort, and the heavy rains flooded some low-lying streets in 
Atlantic Beach. But there were very few injuries or structural 
damage reported in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Duffey and four friends were delivering a 35-foot fishing  
boat, the Carp, from New York to Sebastian, Fla., when Dennis 
forced them to make an unscheduled stop. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any other idiots out here?'' the Long Island man screamed as  
the group scrambled to tie the vessel up at the Gulf Dock in 
Morehead City. ``We're living on the edge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not long after Dennis skirted the coast, people in Morehead City  
were venturing into the trash- and limb-strewn streets. On the 
waterfront, neither Jeremy Coy of Newport nor his children, Summer 
and Aaron, seemed impressed by Dennis. 
</P>
<P>
	``This one right here has been slack,'' Coy said.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Allen G. Breed is the AP's Southeast regional  
writer, based in Raleigh. 






  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
