<DOCNO> APW19990831.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 00:50:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Raines Sees Former Teammates in NY </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tim Raines brought laughter to the New York  
Yankees' clubhouse so often last season, lightening the mood with a 
subtle dig or a practical joke. 
</P>
<P>
	So it was only appropriate that his former teammates played the  
joke on Raines, when he saw them for the first time since learning 
he had Lupus. 
</P>
<P>
	Raines, traveling with the Oakland Athletics for the first time  
since leaving the team with the chronic illness earlier this month, 
came to Yankee Stadium on Monday night to visit with friends and 
receive his World Series ring from last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Raines walked onto the field to a standing ovation from the  
crowd, the Yankees and the Athletics. New York manager Joe Torre 
handed him a box, Raines opened it and it was empty. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees broke into laughter as they went en masse toward  
Raines. Bernie Williams handed his former teammate his ring, and 
Raines joined them in laughter and a hug. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was emotional. Very emotional,'' Raines said of seeing his  
former teammates. ``This was my first time seeing these guys since 
this happened. It's my first time back in New York since the World 
Series parade. It's been an emotional day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There have been a lot of emotional days recently for Raines, who  
has a disease with no known cure. Lupus is a connective tissue 
disease in which the immune system turns against a person's own 
body. It affects various parts of the body, especially the skin, 
joints, blood and kidneys. 
</P>
<P>
	Its symptoms can be treated and Raines is taking medication  
daily and intravenous treatment once a month. While his season is 
over, the 39-year-old Raines vows to return to baseball by spring 
training and still is committed to one day playing with his son, 
Tim Jr., who is in the Baltimore Orioles' farm system. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the one thing I want to do,'' Raines said. '' I want to  
do the Griffey thing. I'm going to play again. I know that. I can 
play five or six more years. I feel like a rookie again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Raines became bloated and mysteriously gained 15 pounds near the  
All-Star break. A kidney biopsy was performed July 23 and he was 
then diagnosed with Lupus. 
</P>
<P>
	Raines underwent four days of treatment in the hospital, where  
he was given high doses of medications designed to relieve the 
swelling in his kidneys and to try keep his immune system from 
attacking his own body. 
</P>
<P>
	He has since lost about 25 pounds and has already begun to taper  
off his medication. Doctors say if the disease is in remission, 
Raines could return to play. 
</P>
<P>
	Raines, one of baseball's top base stealers and leadoff hitters  
during his 20-year career, was told he by doctors he probably had 
Lupus for more than a year. The disease could have contributed to 
knee and hamstring problems when he played with the Yankees from 
1996-98. 
</P>
<P>
	While those injuries slowed him, he still contributed enough to  
help the Yankees win two World Series championships during his 
stay. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there is one person we miss, not necessarily because of his  
at-bats but because of his presence, it's Rock,'' Torre said. ``He 
had an infectious laugh.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That laugh and presence were visible Monday. There was Raines  
telling Paul O'Neill he could still pick up a bat and swing. He 
chastised Ramiro Mendoza for not throwing enough fastballs. He even 
played a practical joke on Mariano Rivera. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivera walked up behind Raines and gave him a hard pat on the  
back. Raines turned around and shot Rivera a glare. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ain't that healthy anymore. Don't hit me like that,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivera stepped back with a worried look on his face. Then came  
that laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got you. I got you,'' Raines squealed.  
</P>
<P>
	Rivera broke into a smile and hugged his former teammate. Once  
again he brought laughter to a serious situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``He helped us win two World Series,'' Tino Martinez said.  
``Just look. You can see how he is.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 18:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Jays, Twins Brawl in Toronto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- After allowing seven unearned runs in the fourth  
inning, Toronto reliever Paul Spoljaric threw a pitch over the head 
of Minnesota's Cristian Guzman, who charged the mound and started a 
brawl. 
</P>
<P>
	Both benches and bullpens emptied as Guzman tackled Spoljaric.  
Both players were ejected, and Spoljaric left the field with a 
black eye. 
</P>
<P>
	Guzman, who had two plate appearances in the inning, led off the  
fourth with a ground ball to third baseman Tony Fernandez, who let 
it slip under his glove for an error. 
</P>
<P>
	The Twins then sent seven men to the plate before Jacque Jones  
capped the seven run outburst with a three-run homer. Spoljaric 
then threw the next pitch over Guzman's head. 
</P>
<P>
	Spoljaric gave up seven runs, none earned, in 1 2-3 innings.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 00:50:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Raines Sees Former Teammates in NY </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tim Raines brought laughter to the New York  
Yankees' clubhouse so often last season, lightening the mood with a 
subtle dig or a practical joke. 
</P>
