<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 13:40:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jaguars' Smith Makes Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Larry Smith is still catching on to  
the subtleties of technique and assignments. The bigger picture -- 
knocking offensive linemen on their backs -- seems to be coming more 
quickly to the Jaguars defensive tackle. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacksonville's second-round draft pick has made an immediate  
impact, both in practice and in games, where offensive linemen are 
having difficulty blocking him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a talented player,'' said Jaguars tackle Tony Boselli,  
who doesn't block Smith in practice, but works next to the guys who 
do. ``He's got a lot to learn, but if he keeps working, he's going 
to be good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A 6-foot-5, 283-pound tackle out of Florida State, Smith was  
projected as anything from a first- to a fourth-round draft pick. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL personnel staffs had plenty of concerns:  
</P>
<P>
	--Smith missed the NFL scouting combine in February because his  
girlfriend was recovering from an auto accident. 
</P>
<P>
	--He skipped a March workout in front of scouts at Florida State  
because he was recovering from food poisoning that caused him to 
lose 15 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	--He missed significant time at Florida State in 1998 because of  
an ankle injury. 
</P>
<P>
	--He is 24 years old, considered old for a rookie. He entered  
college late because he went to prep school after high school. 
</P>
<P>
	None of these concerns could overshadow what the Jaguars saw in  
Smith -- overwhelming talent, energetic play on every down and 
something of a mean streak. 
</P>
<P>
	``That kind of temperament could be good for us,'' coach Tom  
Coughlin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Through three exhibition games, Smith has five tackles, one sack  
and four quarterback pressures, although statistics don't tell the 
whole story. 
</P>
<P>
	He has frequently overwhelmed players on the Jaguars' interior  
line in practice and makes penetration in games. Against the 
Chiefs' second team last week, he looked like an All Pro. 
</P>
<P>
	``He plays well against the first-string guys, too,'' Coughlin  
said. ``He has done a lot of nice things this preseason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Coughlin has criticized him for not playing `assignment  
football.'' At times, Smith's eagerness to get to the quarterback 
has left gaps open for other teams to run through. But his mistakes 
offer glimpses of the raw physical talent that even his doubters 
knew he had. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I first got into camp, I told myself, `This is the  
NFL,''' Smith said. ``You've got to go hard, 100 percent every 
play. And when I feel tired, I know the guy across me is tired, so 
I just try to keep the motor going at all times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith has already secured a spot in the defensive line rotation.  
It looks as if it will be hard to keep him out of the starting 
lineup for long. Even the players trying to hold him off are 
impressed. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's already a great pass rusher,'' defensive lineman Seth  
Payne said. ``He didn't have to play a lot of disciplined run 
defense at Florida State, so that's what he's working on now. He's 
a hard worker. He wants to be a complete football player. He 
definitely has they physical potential to do it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
