<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower Tuesday,  
dragged down by another sharp fall on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed  
482.41 points, or 2.69 percent, to close at 17,436.56. On Monday, 
the average closed up 319.60 points, or 1.82 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo share prices opened lower as investor sentiment was damped  
by another overnight fall in New York and the weaker U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average lost 176.04  
points to close Monday at 10,914.13, declining for the third 
consecutive session. 
</P>
<P>
	Disappointment over weak month-end demand from foreign fund  
managers also pushed down the Nikkei. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 110.18 yen,  
down 0.86 yen from its level of 111.04 yen late Monday in Tokyo and 
below its late New York level of 110.73 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar moved as high as 111.11 yen during the day, bolstered  
by worse-than-expected economic data from the Japanese government. 
Industrial production in July fell 0.6 percent from the previous 
month, below forecasts for a 0.2 percent increase. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar's gains were quickly eroded on the view that the  
Group of Seven industrialized nations are not likely to support the 
dollar against the yen in the short-term. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 205.89 points,  
or 1.5 percent, closing at 13,482.77. On Monday, the index had 
surged 305.53 points, or 2.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said Hong Kong investors took profits following Monday's  
sharp fall on Wall Street amid lingering fears of another rise in 
U.S. interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian shares closed slightly higher on bargain-hunting in  
select blue chips. 
</P>
<P>
	Market sentiment remained weak with many investors sidelined,  
closely watching developments in East Timor after Monday's polls to 
decide the province's future. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index edged up 0.356  
point to 567.026. 
</P>
<P>
	The Malaysian market was closed Tuesday for Independence Day  
celebrations. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower. The benchmark  
NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 2.69 points, or 0.1 percent, to 
2,152.62. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed lower for the fourth straight  
session as concerns over higher interest rates weighed on investor 
sentiment. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 
27.42 points, or 1.2 percent, to 2,173.82. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed higher for the second straight  
session on selective bargain-hunting. The market's key Weighted 
Stock Price Index rose 86.37 points, or 1.1 percent, to 8,157.73. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed lower, pushed down by  
Wall Street's decline. The All Ordinaries Index fell 41.1 points, 
or 1.3 percent, to 2,951.9, its lowest close since Aug. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed mixed. The Korea Composite Stock  
Price Index fell 4.69 points, or 0.4 percent, to 937.88. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Singapore shares closed lower on profit-taking in  
light trading. The benchmark Straits Times Index fell 34.21 points, 
or 1.6 percent, to 2,117.17. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices closed lower in line with losses in  
most regional bourses. The Stock Exchange of Thailand index fell 
6.21 points, or 1.4 percent, to 440.27. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
