<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux's Pitch Should Be Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mario Lemieux helped to save the Pittsburgh  
Penguins as a player. He's close to doing the same as an owner. 
</P>
<P>
	The former NHL great planned to meet with the league's Board of  
Governors today to make a presentation to buy the troubled team for 
his group at a cost of $95 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The board is expected to approve the takeover. The league has  
endorsed Lemieux's group all along in a determined effort to keep 
the Penguins in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	However, it's still up to a bankruptcy court in Pittsburgh to  
make the final determination. That could come later this week, 
hopefully before Saturday when the Penguins are scheduled to open 
training camp. The Penguins will play their first exhibition game 
Sept. 11 against the New York Islanders. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes you move into a house that needs (to be) painted,''  
NHL spokesman Frank Brown said Tuesday. ``This is no different.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux still needs to work out specifics of a $5 million  
investment in the team from SMG, a Philadelphia-based group that 
operates the Civic Center, the Penguins' home arena. Lemieux and 
SMG have reportedly reached an oral agreement on most of the points 
and could seek court approval as early as Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux is the first retired player to take over ownership in  
one of the four major North American pro sports leagues. He led the 
Penguins to the Stanley Cup title in 1991 and 1992. A six-time NHL 
scoring champion, Lemieux retired following the 1996-97 season and 
went directly into the Hall of Fame without the usual three-year 
waiting period. 
</P>
<P>
	By converting $25 million in deferred salary and cash into an  
equity stake, Lemieux will have the largest financial stake of an 
ownership group that numbers more than a dozen investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Lemieux stepped forward, there was still some doubt  
whether the Penguins would remain in Pittsburgh, or even in the 
NHL. The team went into bankruptcy during last season and was only 
able to meet its payroll with the help of a bank loan. 
</P>
<P>
	If the deal goes through, it would not be the first time that  
Lemieux helped to save the Penguins franchise. Before he joined 
them as a player in 1984, the Penguins had dire financial problems. 
The Penguins were losing games, fans and money. 
</P>
<P>
	Attendance plunged to the bottom of the NHL, and there was talk  
the team would be moved out of town. With Lemieux on the ice, 
attendance soared and the Penguins eventually became a solvent and 
winning team. 
</P>
<P>
	It has been a long road for Lemieux in his attempt to buy the  
team. 
</P>
<P>
	The arena lease accounted for much of the delay in Lemieux's  
takeover. Under the lease, SMG will continue to control the 
38-year-old Civic Arena until 2004, when it will revert to Lemieux, 
with SMG as the arena manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations with SMG have been tough for Lemieux to resolve.  
The Penguins blamed the high cost of their lease with SMG to play 
at the Civic Arena for helping push the franchise into bankruptcy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 05:40:33 </DATE_TIME>
