<HEADLINE> Rockets, Houston Plan New Arena </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- The Houston Rockets and the city have reached a  
tentative agreement for a new $160 million sports arena that 
includes the city and team splitting costs, according to a 
published report. 
</P>
<P>
	Six hours of negotiations led up to the tentative agreement late  
Monday. Sources told the Houston Chronicle and KRIV-TV in Houston 
that Rockets owner Les Alexander appeared willing to accept Mayor 
Lee Brown's offer to an even split of the cost for designing and 
building a new facility. 
</P>
<P>
	During six hours of negotiations, the newspaper said, both the  
city and the team made significant concessions on major issues. 
KRIV reports the two sides would split the $160 million cost 
equally, with Alexander picking up the tab for all overruns. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for both sides were instructed to work out the details  
for review today in the next meeting. If the two sides continue to 
agree, the deal would be presented to the Harris County-Houston 
Sports Authority during a special 2 p.m. meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The next step would be a Nov. 2 referendum, following agreement  
of authority board members agree. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
