<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Turn Higher; Dow Up 14.88 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks edged higher today as continuing worries  
over interest rates kept many investors out of the market. 
</P>
<P>
	In late morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 14.88 at 10,929.01. The index fell as much as 32 
points and rose as much as 67 as low volume contributed to 
exaggerated price swings. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also rose slightly. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was up 3.66 at 1,327.68, and the Nasdaq composite 
index was up 2.02 at 2,714.71. 
</P>
<P>
	In a quiet week, with many Wall Street professionals taking  
vacations, many investors are willing to wait for each new piece of 
economic data to guide their decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board said today its consumer confidence index  
fell in August for the second straight month. The index, which 
measures consumers' likeliness to spend, edged down 0.4 of a point, 
less than analysts expected. The study offered confirmation that 
worries over interest rates have taken hold with U.S. consumers, 
but stocks barely reacted to the report. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts expect two more widely watched barometers to spark some  
activity later this week: The National Assocation of Purchasing 
Managers report on Wednesday and the Labor Department's jobless 
report Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Any suggestions that the U.S. economy is growing too quickly  
could convince investors that the Federal Reserve will raise 
interest rates for a third time this year. Higher rates can 
threaten stocks by cutting into corporate profits and increasing 
the value of alternative investments, like bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond held steady today  
at 6.05 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil companies were helping the Dow, as Chevron rose 15/16 to 92 1/4  
and Exxon rose 1 1/4 to 79 1/16. Crude oil futures jumped sharply 
Monday after Venezuela, Mexico and Saudi Arabia decided against 
raising production. 
</P>
<P>
	Office Depot was unchanged at 10 1/2 after shedding 26 percent in  
after-hours trading Monday. The company said it expects to miss 
earnings expectations for the rest of 1999 as weaker sales and 
price erosion on paper supplies hurt gross margins. Shares of 
competing office supply stores fell today. Staples lost 2 3/8 to 19 
9/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 226.7 million 
shares, ahead of Monday's quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 200 index of smaller company stocks was down 0.28 at  
427.08. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
