<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 17:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Decides To Pay Unwed Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Undoing what almost everyone agreed was an  
injustice, the state crime compensation fund on Tuesday agreed to 
give money to victims who had broken minor laws such as living with 
a member of the opposite sex while unmarried. 
</P>
<P>
	The Crime Victims Compensation Commission will pay families of  
14 murder victims whose claims had been rejected because the 
victims -- all unmarried -- were living with a member of the opposite 
sex. That violates a rarely enforced 1805 state law against 
cohabitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the beneficiaries Tuesday was Diana Zambory of Newport,  
who was originally denied compensation after her 24-year-old 
daughter was killed by her live-in boyfriend. Now, two people who 
covered her daughter's funeral costs will receive $1,677. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm extremely grateful now that the right thing will be  
done,'' Ms. Zambory said. ``I would love to have the record 
stricken where my daughter was accused of being a criminal, but I 
don't think that will ever happen. And that still hurts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission pays up $7,500 to cover the funeral expenses for  
murder victims and the medical costs for other victims. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, the state toughened its compensation law after a judge  
ruled that a man who was shot and paralyzed while committing a 
robbery was entitled to victim's benefits upon parole. 
</P>
<P>
	The law required the commission to reject a claim for a victim  
who was involved in a felony or nontraffic misdemeanor. That meant 
victims were ineligible even if they were guilty of cohabitation or 
fishing without a license. 
</P>
<P>
	The state commission denied 47 claims on the basis of  
cohabitation alone through June 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But in July, Gov. Jim Hunt signed a new law allowing the  
commission to merely consider nontraffic misdemeanors when making 
awards, instead of making it mandatory to deny those cases. The 
cohabitation law remains on the books, however. 
</P>
<P>
	The law also allows the panel to reconsider some previously  
denied cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had some really tough decisions that hopefully now we  
don't have to repeat,'' said Jonathan Babb, the commission's 
attorney. ``This is a good step, especially when you have the crime 
of murder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More cases, including those denied for reasons other than  
cohabitation, also will be reconsidered, said the commission's 
director, Robert Reives. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 08:06:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians, Israel Close to Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian and Israeli officials are  
optimistic they will reach an agreement on reviving a U.S.-brokered 
peace plan by the time Secretary of State Madeleine Albright 
arrives this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations resumed today, a day after Israeli and Palestinian  
officials had made their most positive statements in months about 
the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I imagine within two or three days we will reach a  
conclusion,'' Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The positive atmosphere, however, was threatened late Monday by  
the discovery of the bodies of a slain Israeli couple near the West 
Bank border. Police suspected the killings were politically 
motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	The killings near the Megiddo forest, a popular nature reserve  
straddling Israel and the northern West Bank, could complicate the 
grueling talks on reviving the long-delayed Wye River peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak expressed his ``deep shock'' over the killings.  
</P>
<P>
	Palestinians, though, agreed the two sides were close to a  
resolution. ``I have to say that these people intend to implement 
the agreements,'' senior negotiator Saeb Erekat said Monday after 
another four-hour session with his Israeli counterpart, Gilead 
Sher. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright is due in the region on Thursday and expects an accord  
by the time she arrives, her spokesman said in Washington. Egypt 
also hopes to host a signing ceremony launching the implementation 
of the Wye agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat traveled to Alexandria, Egypt,  
today to meet with President Hosni Mubarak -- the fifth visit 
between the two leaders this summer. After the meeting, Egyptian 
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said an implementation agreement might 
be signed in Alexandria on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The two sides will intensify their negotiations'' in an effort  
to reach an agreement, Moussa said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, signed last October, called for three Israeli  
withdrawals from the West Bank in return for security measures by 
Yasser Arafat's Palestinian government. 
</P>
<P>
	But after a single pullback in December 1998, former Israeli  
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu froze the deal, alleging 
Palestinian noncompliance. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak defeated Netanyahu in May elections, pledging to revive  
Wye. But before Monday, talks had largely been stalemated. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel and the Palestinians appeared closer than ever on the two  
issues that have deadlocked the sides until now: a timetable for a 
long-delayed Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank, and the release 
of Palestinians jailed for anti-Israel acts. 
</P>
<P>
	Differences over a timetable for a withdrawal from the West Bank  
were down to less than a month: Israelis are sticking to a Jan. 20 
deadline, and the Palestinians want the pullback to be completed by 
Dec. 31. On the prisoners issues, the Palestinians demand that 650 
will be freed, while Israel says it would release a little more 
than 300. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright's spokesman, James B. Foley, said the secretary wanted  
to look beyond the Israeli withdrawal and focus on more difficult 
issues concerning a final settlement between Israel and the 
Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel and the Palestinians are still apart on a new deadline  
for such an agreement, which would address issues like the final 
borders of the Palestinian entity and the status of Jerusalem. The 
Palestinians seek April 2000 as a target date, while Israel has 
proposed December 2000 as a new deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright also wants to review the status of Israeli and Syrian  
peace talks, which broke off three years ago, Foley said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen evidence that each side is eager to resume those  
negotiations,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
