<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Will Vote on Lemieux Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Funding for the bankrupt Pittsburgh Penguins  
will continue until final details of the franchise's sale are 
worked out. 
</P>
<P>
	Funding from a $20 million loan from French bank Societe  
Generale was scheduled to expire Aug. 31. Salvatore Galatioto, 
Societe Generale managing director and head of sports finance, said 
today the loan would be extended. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to extend it until we need to,'' Galatioto said.  
``It's not going to be a problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations between the Pens and SMG, the private,  
Philadelphia-based partnership that managed the Civic Arena, were 
continuing Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mario Lemieux may be one day away from owning the Pittsburgh  
Penguins, the team he led to two Stanley Cup championships earlier 
in the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, who spent last week closing on his $95 million purchase  
of the bankrupt franchise, will meet Wednesday with the NHL's 
executive committee to review his takeover. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless the executive committee unexpectedly balks, Lemieux is  
expected to be voted in as an owner during an NHL Board of 
Governors meeting that afternoon in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Swift approval is expected since the league has already endorsed  
Lemieux's takeover, the first by a recently retired player in one 
of the four major North American professional sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, a six-time NHL scoring champion, retired following the  
1997 season. By converting $25 million in deferred salary and cash 
into an equity stake, he will have the largest financial stake of 
an ownership group that numbers more than a dozen investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins open training camp at their Southpointe practice  
rink in Washington County on Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
