<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 23:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paterno Keeps Lions Humble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- For Penn State players who endured  
1997 and 1998 -- lean years by Joe Paterno's standards -- dismantling 
Arizona on Saturday was quite a rush. 
</P>
<P>
	This was a victory over a Top 5 team, the Nittany Lions' first  
in five years. And it came in sensational fashion, with tough 
defense and a big-play offense that looked more like a Pac-10 team 
than Paterno's team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this is the best feeling we've had in a long time,''  
quarterback Kevin Thompson said. 
</P>
<P>
	By Monday, the veterans knew, the time for savoring was over:  
Paterno had spent the weekend dissecting game tape. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to make sure we're humble,'' fullback Aaron Harris  
said after No. 2 Penn State won 41-7, sending Arizona tumbling to 
No. 15 in the rankings. ``As soon as we watch this film, he'll find 
50,000 mistakes with a good play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So how many did Joe turn up?  
</P>
<P>
	``Probably more than Aaron thought,'' Paterno joked Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Actually, there really were problems hidden in the glow of 504  
yards of total offense. Paterno is never one to depend on the 
surprise play, and beyond surprise plays, Penn State's offense 
wasn't quite so dominating. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were very inconsistent running the football. We had some  
breakdowns in pass protection. We had four sacks,'' Paterno said as 
the Lions prepared for Akron, which visits Saturday. ``When they 
start taking the gimmicks away from you, then you've really got to 
be able to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next team will be ready for inside reverses and first-down  
passing. They're not the usual Penn State fare, but they went for 
three touchdowns in the first half against the poor-tackling 
Wildcats. 
</P>
<P>
	A better team might also have made the Lions pay for their  
errors. Quarterback Rashard Casey tripped as he stepped away from 
center on fourth-and-goal. Thompson had a pass picked off. The 
offensive line was called for two false starts in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	And lost in the celebration was this troubling statistic: The  
Lions fumbled six times, losing two. 
</P>
<P>
	``You fumble six times in a close football game and you're out  
of it. You're out of it,'' Paterno said. ``We were minus-2 in 
turnovers. Most big games, you're minus-2 and you're licked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So maybe Paterno had a point when he tried to rein in the  
postgame lovefest. Interestingly, this team didn't seem to need 
Paterno's reminders about the long road ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	There were a few errant comments: ``We won't be surprised if we  
score 70 points,'' said receiver Corey Jones, who pulled a 
hamstring and might miss the Akron game. 
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, the experienced Lions weren't getting carried away by  
the victory -- even with the lowly Zips next on the schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly one of the major things the coaches have stressed  
upon us is that we can't have a letdown,'' Thompson said. ``We've 
got to come out and we've got to be able to run the football 
effectively and pass the ball effectively. We're not going to fool 
everybody this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They may not need to fool the Zips, who were 4-7 last year. They  
have yet to beat a Top 25 team in a dozen Division I-A seasons, 
with ranked teams piling up 54.3 points per game. In 1997, Nebraska 
routed them 59-14, and LSU blanked them 56-0. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've played a lot of games in my tenure at Akron like this,''  
said Zips coach Lee Owens, going into his fifth season. ``The 
biggest risk we've taken in the past is the risk of embarrassment 
and loss of confidence. It's really important to leave this game 
feeling good about ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If it sounds as if Owen has already given up, he hasn't. In  
fact, he reminded his team of Sept. 10, 1983: Cincinnati 14, 
defending national champion Penn State 3. 
</P>
<P>
	The circumstances were a little different; Nebraska defeated the  
Lions 44-6 the week before, but Paterno has also cautioned his team 
about that Cincinnati game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I worry more about these games than about the Arizonas,''  
Paterno said. ``I'll be disappointed if this team isn't mature 
enough to understand what can happen to them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
