<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Raptors Re-Sign Charles Oakley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- The Toronto Raptors ended months of speculation  
and re-signed veteran power forward Charles Oakley today. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Oakley was courted by eight other teams, including  
the Los Angeles Lakers and the NBA champion San Antonio Spurs, 
there was little doubt the 35-year-old free agent would re-sign 
with the Raptors because of the salary cap. 
</P>
<P>
	Most teams were not able to offer anything close to the  
three-year, $18 million deal the Raptors reportedly did. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-9 Oakley has played 14 NBA seasons, including 10 with  
the New York Knicks before being dealt to Toronto last June for 
forward Marcus Camby, more than 10 years his junior. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakley averaged 7.0 points last season and was second on the  
team behind Kevin Willis with 7.5 rebounds per game. For his 
career, he averages 10.6 points and 10.3 rebounds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
