<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 31, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Russian Troops Resume Rebel Attack  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian aircraft and artillery  
pounded a mountainous stronghold of Islamic militants for a third 
straight day today in a battle for control over a volatile southern 
region. The attack on several remote villages in Dagestan follows 
two weeks of intense fighting in another part of the impoverished 
republic earlier in August. Government forces are again using 
helicopter gunships and heavy artillery in an attempt to crush the 
rebels who have imposed strict Islamic law in several small 
villages they control. 

</P>
<P>
	North Korea Marks Missile Launch  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- North Korea marked the anniversary of its launch of  
a long-range missile over Japan one year ago today with boasts of 
scientific and technological advances. Japanese government 
officials and media, meanwhile, urged vigilance lest the North 
decide to launch yet again. ``Over the course of the year, our 
scientists and engineers have seen the successful results of over 
50 meaningful research and development projects,'' said a broadcast 
by Korean Central Radio, which is monitored in Tokyo by the 
Radiopress agency. 

</P>
<P>
	Farmers OK New Milk Pricing System  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Even though it could cost them money, dairy  
farmers overwhelmingly approved an overhaul of the way milk is 
priced around the country rather than have the government end its 
regulation of their industry. The new plan, which was developed by 
the Agriculture Department to smooth regional disparities in the 
prices that farmers receive for milk, is likely to undergo revision 
in Congress this fall before it takes effect. The current system 
expires Oct. 1. USDA's plan received near-unanimous approval in 
most regions of the country, according to results of the Aug. 2-6 
referendum that were released today. 

</P>
<P>
	Princess Diana Remembered  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Two years after Princess Diana's fatal car crash,  
flowers, toys and photographs again decorate the gates in front of 
her Kensington Palace home and admirers come to mark her death. 
``Where's Diana's memorial?'' read a placard that summed up what 
many people feel about today's anniversary of Diana's death in a 
Paris car crash on Aug. 31, 1997. In recent weeks, the Mirror 
newspaper has been campaigning for a permanent Diana memorial and 
claims to have had 144,000 phone calls of support. A memorial 
committee set up last year had proposed a commemorative garden near 
Kensington Palace, but the plan was quietly put on hold after local 
residents objected. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Warns Ethnic Albanians on Disarmament  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke told  
ethnic Albanian leaders that congressional support will evaporate 
if they don't disarm their guerrilla army. Holbrooke, newly 
confirmed as U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, travels to 
Albania today to continue talks on ways to stabilize the southern 
Balkans after a 78-day NATO bombing campaign against Yugoslavia. 
``Let me just stress again what ethnic differences in this region 
really are. They're just racism,'' Holbrooke said Monday after 
meetings with ethnic Albanian leaders in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Palestinians, Israelis Near Deal  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian and Israeli officials appear  
optimistic they will reach an agreement on reviving a U.S.-brokered 
peace plan by the time Secretary of State Madeleine Albright 
arrives this week. The positive atmosphere, however, was threatened 
late yesterday with the discovery of the bodies of a slain Israeli 
couple near the West Bank border. Police suspected Palestinian 
militants. The killings near the Megiddo forest, a popular nature 
reserve straddling Israel and the northern West Bank, could 
complicate the grueling talks on reviving the long-delayed Wye 
River peace deal. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Close Sharply Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks closed sharply lower today. The  
Nikkei shed 482.41 points to close at 17,436.56. 

</P>
<P>
	Giants 6, Phillies 4, 10 Innings  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Barry Bonds' second homer of the game, a  
two-run shot in the 10th, gave the San Francisco Giants a 6-4 win 
last night over the Philadelphia Phillies. Bill Mueller walked to 
open the 10th and Bonds hit the first pitch from Billy Brewer over 
the center-field fence. Bonds has 28 homers this season. He moved 
past Andre Dawson into 23rd place on the career list with his 438th 
and 439th homers. 

</P>
<P>
	Padres 8, Cubs 4  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Quilvio Veras hit a tying three-run double in  
the seventh, then scored the go-ahead run on catcher Jeff Reed's 
throwing error as the San Diego Padres beat the Chicago Cubs 8-4 
last night in a sloppy game between last-place teams. The Padres 
kept Sammy Sosa from adding to his major league-leading total of 54 
homers. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
