<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ad Agency Studies Teen Shopping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Paul Florio and Erica Grossman, young and  
hip, have just been given $200 to buy anything they want. 
</P>
<P>
	The money did not come from their parents. It came from a  
Stamford advertising agency that wants to get into the brains of 
teen-agers as they shop for back-to-school merchandise. 
</P>
<P>
	North Castle Partners, which specializes in youth-market ads,  
sent seven teen-agers on shopping sprees in Connecticut and New 
York in August. The goal of this unconventional research was not 
only to see what's hot, but to see what's on teen-agers' minds. 
</P>
<P>
	The hooded sweatshirts, T-shirts and surfer wear Florio and  
Grossman bought will help the agency accurately depict teens in 
their print and television ads. But even more important to the 
agency's clients is what the teens talked about during the shopping 
sprees. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not so much to stay in tune with trends, because trends  
are elusive. It's more what's really happening with teens and 
what's important to them,'' said Grant MacDonald, a partner at 
North Castle. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency has designed ads for popular teen snacks such as Slim  
Jim, Lifesavers, Planter's Nuts and Coca-Cola, as well as the 
pHisoderm line of facial cleansers. 
</P>
<P>
	Teens spent about $141 billion last year -- $94 billion of their  
own money and $47 billion of their parents' money, according to 
Teenage Research Unlimited, a research firm based in Northbrook, 
Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Castle agency sent Susan Chaggaris, an account  
executive, to accompany the students on their shopping sprees. 
</P>
<P>
	At the upscale Stamford Town Center, Chaggaris handed $200 in  
cash to each of four teens: Florio, 17, and Grossman, 15, both 
students at Stamford High; Chantal Dore, 15, a sophomore at New 
Canaan High; and Matt Barcello, 16, a junior at Stamford's Westhill 
High. 
</P>
<P>
	The four teens went from store to store together, buying fairly  
typical fare: compact discs, videos, lip gloss and of course, 
clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	They bought polo shirts and vests from The Gap, cargo pants from  
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, surfer wear from Pacific Sunwear and music 
from Sam Goody. 
</P>
<P>
	The teens said they hoped the research would help manufacturers  
and retailers better understand their peers. 
</P>
<P>
	``They get to see what kids really like,'' Florio said.  
``There's a lot more diversity (among teens) than people think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In between purchases, Chaggaris asked the kids about topics  
ranging from handling peer pressure to the importance of good 
grades. Chaggaris received a unanimous response when she asked them 
what they were looking forward to about going back to school: 
seeing friends. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad agency plans to tell its clients that their advertising  
should reflect a strong sense of belonging. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all about social acceptance and being part of  
something,'' said MacDonald. ``So, if we were going to be working 
with a client ... we'd say, how do we connect them to social 
acceptance or belonging?'' 
</P>
<P>
	MacDonald said the agency also got an idea for a promotional  
campaign just by looking at the jewelry worn by the teen shoppers. 
Florio sports three silver earrings and a silver barbell in his 
tongue. Grossman has a tongue barbell and a belly button piercing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Typical teen promotions are music, music, music ... but  
looking at how involved these teens are in jewelry, I think there's 
a provocative thought for marketers. Why not do promotions around 
jewelry?'' MacDonald said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gail Lee, associate marketing director for Chattem Inc., the  
maker of pHisoderm, said the ad agency has designed ``edgy'' and 
``slightly uncomfortable'' ads that have been highly effective in 
reaching teens. 
</P>
<P>
	One recent print ad for its 4-way Daily Acne Cleanser shows a  
girl holding a sander to the side of her face. On the handle of the 
sander is the message, ``Zit Be Gone.'' The tagline says, ``It's 
better to use pHisoderm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lee said she thinks pHisoderm can use the information North  
Castle gleans from the shopping sprees, even though the teens did 
not buy the company's skin care products. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you might come up with an idea that if teens are  
buying this type of jeans ... maybe there's an opportunity for them 
to tie that to our product to make it more relevant,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the more you know (about teens), the better off you  
are.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
