<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockets' Francis Feels No Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- If Steve Francis feels pressure because the  
Houston Rockets traded a third of their playoff roster to get him, 
the former Maryland star isn't admitting it. 
</P>
<P>
	After ending last season with their second consecutive  
first-round playoff exit, the Rockets on Monday introduced Francis 
and Tony Massenburg, two of the principals in last week's 11-player 
deal with Vancouver and Orlando. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis is projected as the Rockets' starting point guard, with  
Cuttino Mobley possibly moving over to the other guard slot. 
They'll join front-court players Hakeem Olajuwon, Scottie Pippen 
and Charles Barkley, who is expected to re-sign soon with Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I don't lead the league in assists playing with those  
guys,'' he said, ``something will be wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to describe his game, Francis mentioned the influence of  
Isaiah Thomas, then touched on several of the league's current 
point guard stars. 
</P>
<P>
	``There aren't many guys that are fast, can run, jump and  
shoot,'' he said of the difficulty finding players he could model 
his game after. ``I think I'm a combination of Allen Iverson and 
Stephon Marbury put together. I take a lot of pride in my defense 
like John Stockton. It's a lot of different guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockets said Francis is not as anxious to shoot as the  
comparison with Iverson and Marbury might indicate. Rockets coach 
Rudy Tomjanovich said Francis leans more toward playmaking. 
</P>
<P>
	``This guy was so exciting when you see the highlight reels on  
him. There are a lot of players that can get on highlights. But he 
is a team player. I watched a lot of tape on him and I thought 
sometimes he was so unselfish as times, he could have done more,'' 
Tomjanovich said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every coach that he's had said he is a team player, and they  
had a good relationship with him, and I think that's important. The 
point guard is connected to the head coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``You would think he took a lot more shots. He took less than 12  
shots (per game) this year. Talking to (Maryland coach) Gary 
Williams, Gary said, `You would think he took a lot more shots. But 
he plays to win. He plays defense.''' 
</P>
<P>
	In the largest deal in NBA history, Vancouver and Orlando added  
some much-needed depth in return for the rights to Francis, picked 
No. 2 overall by the Grizzlies in the June draft. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
