<HEADLINE> West Wildfires Char 150,000 Acres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	APPLE VALLEY, Calif. (AP) -- Smoke rose into the Mojave Desert  
sky from the north flank of the San Bernardino Mountains today as 
firefighters struggled to contain active forest and brush fires 
that had burned 150,000 acres in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	The largest uncontrolled blazes were being fought in Idaho,  
Montana, Utah and California. Fires had been contained in Nevada 
and Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest concentration of firefighters worked to tame a  
50,000-acre blaze that had destroyed 12 homes since Sunday about 80 
miles east of Los Angeles, between the resort town of Lake 
Arrowhead and the high desert of Apple Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all we have,'' resident Steve Chisholm said today as he  
stood in a pile of ash that was once his living room. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire was spreading along the mountains east toward Lucerne  
Valley today, but none of the widely scattered rustic homes in the 
area of scrub and Joshua trees were threatened. San Bernardino 
County fire spokeswoman Kathy Saindon said at least 200 people had 
voluntarily evacuated. 
</P>
<P>
	Five people were arrested Monday for allegedly looting abandoned  
homes, sheriff's spokeswoman Jennie Risley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Erratic wind that fanned flames during the night eased today. On  
Monday, wind blew smoke from the fire more than 180 miles to the 
northeast, tinting the sky over Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sunrise this morning was blood-red, it was gorgeous,''  
said Bob Leinbach, spokesman for the Clark County (Nev.) Fire 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifty miles west of Apple Valley, more than 780 firefighters  
worked in the San Gabriel Mountains to contain a 2,500-acre 
wildfire that damaged three cabins in the Angeles National Forest. 
Several thousand people, mostly campers, were ordered out of the 
area when the fire broke out Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Northern California, a 34,441-acre fire in Modoc National  
Forest was 50 percent contained, and firefighters in Butte County 
expected full containment of several fires that burned 33,924 
acres. Six other fires were burning on 8,353 acres in Plumas 
National Forest. 
</P>
<P>
	A cluster of fires in Shasta and Trinity counties had blackened  
17,059 acres, and other fires had burned 4,547 acres in the 
Shasta-Trinity National Forests. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderstorms were believed responsible for two wildfires on  
Utah rangeland west of Salt Lake City, including a 3,000-acre blaze 
up Peepstone Canyon and a wind-blown 750-acre fire about 40 miles 
west of Salt Lake City. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
