<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Fair to partly cloudy skies covered much of the eastern part of  
the country on Tuesday, while the Plains and the West were mostly 
fair as well, 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Dennis continued to weaken east of North Carolina.  
Light rain associated with the storm dropped on parts of the state. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure located over the Northeast was responsible for  
fair skies and dry weather. A frontal boundary stretching along the 
Gulf Coast from Florida, west into southeastern Texas, brought a 
few showers and thunderstorms. 
</P>
<P>
	In Houston, the storms packed winds of 60 mph, knocking down  
power lines, breaking windows and killing a roofer who was crushed 
when a motel under construction collapsed. Nearly 100,000 homes 
were without power late Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms also moved onshore in the Florida Panhandle, southern  
Alabama, southern Mississippi and southern Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers were scattered across parts of Kansas. The remainder of  
the Plains were under fair to partly cloudy skies. 
</P>
<P>
	A frontal boundary pushed into the northern Plains from the  
Rockies, bringing an increased threat of scattered showers and 
thunderstorms. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the West was fair and pleasant.  
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from a low of 25 in  
Burns, Ore., to an early-afternoon high of 92 in Austin, Texas. 
With the heat index, it felt like 104 in Biloxi, Miss. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
