<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kidney Donor Homeless, Needs Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A woman who was so generous that she gave a  
little boy one of her kidneys now has no place to live. 
</P>
<P>
	Marian Neal, 40, moved into a northern Virginia homeless shelter  
after housing officials in the Washington suburb of Alexandria, 
Va., said she was breaking the rules by living in a friend's public 
housing unit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is my first time in a homeless shelter, but it's OK,''  
Neal said Monday in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	She remains optimistic that her situation will improve. ``I'm  
number 60 on the city's housing list, so that's good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neal said she was sharing her friend's apartment, because a  
spinal condition has kept her from working for the past few years 
and she was denied Social Security benefits. She lives on $340 a 
month in food stamps and general relief. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been real, real difficult,'' Neal said.  
</P>
<P>
	But she said one of the benefits of living with her friend was  
that she got to know her 7-year-old neighbor, Terrance Varner and 
his grandmother, Elaine Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	Terrance suffered from kidney disease, and Neal volunteered to  
take him to dialysis three days a week so Harris wouldn't miss 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	Within a few months, Neal offered one of her own kidneys to save  
the boy. The transplant took place in December and was a success. 
</P>
<P>
	Terrance now has his health but says he misses his neighbor. He  
says he ``hopes she finds a new place to live and she has money to 
pay the rent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neal says no matter where she ends up, the two will always be  
connected in a special way. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has a part of me,'' she said. ``Nothing financial could  
make me feel as good as I have when I look at Terrance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Terrance's grandmother says she wishes she could help but says  
the city law prevents her from inviting Neal to live with them. 
</P>
<P>
	Neal is not letting it get her down.  
</P>
<P>
	She has received a federal grant to attend Northern Virginia  
Community College. And while she says she doesn't know what she 
wants to do with her education, she's certain of one thing: ``I 
want to help people.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
