<DOCNO> APW19990831.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 23:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Underwood Pledges Full Commitment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIE, Fla. (AP) -- Dimitrius Underwood's new teammates with the  
Miami Dolphins are curious to see how he develops after missing 
virtually all of training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he comes in and does a spectacular job, we might start  
scratching our heads and say, `Hmm, maybe we don't need training 
camp,''' linebacker Derrick Rodgers said jokingly. 
</P>
<P>
	After weeks of wavering, the unpredictable Underwood pledged 100  
percent commitment to the Dolphins and practiced with them for the 
first time Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The workout was the first for the rookie defensive end since  
Aug. 2, when he walked out on the Minnesota Vikings after one 
practice to focus on his faith. Underwood said his career with the 
Dolphins will last longer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy to be here,'' he said. ``I'm going to get on my  
horse and get going. I've got a lot to prove. You want to be the 
best of the best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, 22, arrived at the Dolphins' complex one day late  
after missing two flights from Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had some loose ends to tie up,'' he explained.  
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-6 Underwood reported at 270 pounds, a few less than  
his playing weight. Wind sprints at the end of practice left him 
gasping, and he admitted that he needs to get into shape, but he 
looked quick during team drills. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood has a five-year contract, and the Dolphins consider  
him a long-term investment. But coach Jimmy Johnson didn't discount 
the possibility that his newest lineman will play this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had an excellent practice, and without question he's an  
excellent prospect,'' Johnson said. ``We had him rated as the top 
defensive end in the entire draft, and nothing he did today makes 
us change our mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota took Underwood with the 29th pick in the first round.  
He considered a career in the ministry after leaving the Vikings, 
and they released him Aug. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood was claimed on waivers by Miami after 23 other teams  
passed. He declined to tell reporters what changed his mind about 
playing football. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be like Einstein trying to explain the theory of  
relativity to you guys,'' he said. ``It would take all day and you 
still probably wouldn't understand it. I know I wouldn't. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to do something until I make up my mind to. I  
told the Minnesota Vikings I wasn't ready because I wasn't fully 
committed. I'm not going to give 50 or 75 percent. When I get ready 
to do something, I can guarantee it's going to be 100 percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Money isn't his motivation, he said, even though he has twin  
17-month-old children. Underwood sacrificed a $1.75 million signing 
bonus by leaving the Vikings, and he'll settle for a base salary of 
$395,000 with Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a higher power than money,'' he said. ``The NFL is a  
great thing, but what wakes people up every day is not the same 
thing for everybody. Some wake up for the money. I wake up to a 
different beat -- the beat of God.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
