<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bears Coach Expects To Win Now </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- He looked like Dick Jauron. He sounded like Dick  
Jauron. But the words were vintage Mike Ditka. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago Bears rookie coach doesn't care if everyone else  
expects his team to finish at the bottom of the NFC Central. He and 
his players think the Bears can win this season, and that's all 
that matters. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the end of the season, we'll see where those predictions  
are,'' he said Tuesday, speaking to a sold-out crowd at the 
inaugural Kickoff Luncheon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our future is now,'' he added. ``All of us. We want to win  
every game and we want to win now. I think we have a chance, and I 
think we have a chance because we all believe we have a chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wow. Pretty strong words for a coach who inherited a team that  
was 4-12 the last two years and who still doesn't have a starting 
quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	But that's Jauron. He might come across as calm and  
mild-mannered -- some might even say boring -- but he's got plenty of 
``Da Coach''s fire in him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We call it the championship season,'' he said. ``We call it  
that because at the end, there's going to be a champion, and we 
want to be that team. We want to be that team this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	OK, not to crash the kickoff party, but let's talk reality for a  
minute. The Bears will start either rookie Cade McNown or Shane 
Matthews, a veteran who's never started an NFL game, at 
quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	Curtis Enis, the cornerstone of the running game, is recovering  
from a season-ending knee injury last year. Rookie Russell Davis 
will likely start at right defensive end. And insurance policy 
Brian Gowins was cut Tuesday even though Jeff Jaeger isn't fully 
recovered from a hip injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really believe when a team commits to each other ... that we  
have a chance. And I think we have a strong chance,'' Jauron said. 
``Does that mean we'll win every game? No, it does not. But we 
can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jauron isn't the only one talking big these days. Ted Phillips,  
who became the team's president when Michael McCaskey was booted 
upstairs, doesn't want to hear about timetables or building 
processes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears had some growing pains during the preseason, but they  
also showed promise, Phillips said. They might have finished 2-2, 
but that's the best preseason record Chicago has had since 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``The team has shown ability to win football games, and that's  
the most important thing,'' Phillips said. ``I believe the passion 
and commitment to winning has been reignited.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
