<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 13:40:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newest Economic Reports Are Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consumer confidence fell for the second straight  
month in August as interest rates rose, while economic activity in 
the manufacturing sector grew for the seventh consecutive month, 
according to two private reports released today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board said its consumer confidence index, which  
measures consumers' likeliness to spend, edged down 0.4 of a point, 
less than analysts expected, to 135.8 from a revised 136.2 in July, 
but still close to the 30-year high reached in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the National Association of Purchasing Management  
said its index measuring industrial activity rose to 54.2 percent, 
up from 53.4 in July. A measure of inflation, which tracks prices 
paid by industry for raw materials and supplies, also rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchasing executives report had been scheduled for  
Wednesday, but the figures were mistakenly released today, the 
group said. 
</P>
<P>
	The surprise report of a stronger-than-expected economy rattled  
Wall Street, which briefly gave up its early gains on fresh 
inflation jitters and started sinking sharply before recovering a 
bit on bargain-hunting late in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow, which fell sharply in each of the past three sessions,  
was off as much as 132 points early this afternoon before regaining 
the lost ground. It was up slightly as the final hour of trading 
began, then sank again to close down 84.85 at 10,929.28. 
</P>
<P>
	The two reports painted a picture of an economy that remains  
strong. 
</P>
<P>
	``The overall picture is one of continuing growth in  
manufacturing activity during the month of August,'' Norbert J. 
Ore, chair of the National Association of Purchasing Management's 
business survey committee, said in a statement. ``Production and 
new orders remain positive and provide encouragement that the 
manufacturing sector will continue on a path of growth into the 
second half of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That sentiment, however, revived inflation fears on Wall Street.  
The Dow Jones industrial index, which had been up nearly 68 points 
during morning trading, quickly reversed course on worries the 
robust economy would push interest rates even higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's two reports are viewed as key information on the current  
state of the economy because both are measurements from August. In 
contrast, figures in many government economic releases are at least 
a month old. 
</P>
<P>
	The declines in consumer confidence in July and August followed  
eight consecutive monthly increases that led to the 30-year high 
reading of 139.0 in June. 
</P>
<P>
	``The numbers are just still so high,'' said Diane Swonk, chief  
economist with Chicago-based Bank One Corp. ``Consumers are still 
willing to spend at a fairly rapid clip.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer sentiment is an important economic indicator since  
consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the nation's overall 
economic activity. 
</P>
<P>
	While consumer confidence remains near record levels, Americans  
may begin to curtail purchases of cars and washing machines in 
light of rising interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve has raised key interest rates twice this  
summer in an effort to cool consumer and business spending, which 
could drive up prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hikes in interest rates, severe drought conditions in the  
Northeast, and rising gasoline prices have helped dampen overall 
consumer optimism,'' said Lynn Franco, director of the Conference 
Board's Consumer Research Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers are less confident about current economic conditions  
and job prospects than they were in July, the survey said, with 
slight increases in the proportion saying business conditions are 
bad and jobs are hard to get. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dip in optimism in August did not carry over into  
Americans' expectations for the next six months. About 17 percent 
of all consumers look for business conditions to get better, 
roughly the same as in July. About 17.5 percent predict the job 
market to improve during the next six months, up a bit from July. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer confidence survey is based on a representative  
sample of 5,000 U.S. households. The monthly poll is conducted for 
the Conference Board by NFO Research Inc. of Greenwich, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey of purchasing managers is compiled from monthly  
replies to a survey of executives in more than 350 industrial 
companies. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
