<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 12:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northwestern's Matt Hartl Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) -- Matt Hartl, one of the leaders of the 1995  
Northwestern football team that played in the Rose Bowl, has died 
after a lengthy battle with Hodgkin's disease. He was 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Barnett, Hartl's coach at Northwestern and now the head  
coach at Colorado, said Hartl died Monday night. A Northwestern 
spokesman confirmed that Hartl had died but did not have any 
details. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was just what you would want your son to grow up to be,''  
Barnett said of the player he recruited out of a Denver high 
school. ``He had an appreciation for everybody, all walks of life. 
He was a tough guy when he needed to be tough, and sensitive when 
he needed to be sensitive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hartl helped lead the team that became the first Wildcats' squad  
to play in the Rose Bowl since 1949. A redshirt freshman fullback, 
Hartl was used primarily as a blocking back. 
</P>
<P>
	Within a few months of the Rose Bowl, doctors discovered a tumor  
in his chest and diagnosed him with Hodgkin's disease, the same 
cancer his mother, Eleanor, had beaten more than 20 years earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	After missing the 1996 season while undergoing treatment, he  
returned for the 1997 season, starting in 11 games for the 
Wildcats. 
</P>
<P>
	He planned to play the next season but could not because the  
disease reoccurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartl's death came about two years after his mother died at the  
age of 45, her heart fatally weakened by the radiation treatments 
that helped cure her cancer years before. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnett said he had heard recently that Hartl's condition had  
worsened and that he had lapsed into a coma. Still, Barnett said he 
held out hope. 
</P>
<P>
	``In classic Hartl fashion he'd beat all the things he wasn't  
supposed to beat, so we were hoping he might beat this, too,'' the 
coach said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
