<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> California Gunman Remains at Large </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GARDEN GROVE, Calif. (AP) -- A gunman who killed two people and  
wounded four others when he opened fire at an auto accessories 
store remained at large today as police sought a motive. 
</P>
<P>
	Bursts of gunfire began about 1:10 p.m. Monday inside the  
Robotek store, which sells performance car accessories. A customer 
inside the store was killed and three other people were wounded, 
including the shop owner, Lt. Frank Hauptmann said. 
</P>
<P>
	The gunman then shot two more people outside the store, killing  
one, Hauptmann said. 
</P>
<P>
	The gunman used a semiautomatic weapon capable of firing bursts  
of bullets. He fled in a gray 1990 to 1994 Mazda MPV minivan, and 
another man may have fled with him, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	An employee at Vina, a pager store a couple of doors down, said  
he heard about 10 gunshots. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so scared, I hide behind my counter and I didn't see  
anything,'' said the employee, who declined to give his name. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the store was a popular hangout for young people.  
</P>
<P>
	The shooting was similar to an unsolved June 2 attack on another  
auto store that killed one person and injured another. However, 
Hauptmann said investigators had not drawn any direct connection 
between the two shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	The dead were identified as customer, Mario Taborga, 21, of  
Anaheim, killed inside the store; and Tony Ngo, 18, of Fountain 
Valley, who was killed by shots fired through the window of his 
parked car. 
</P>
<P>
	The wounded were identified as shop owner Charlie Kim, 48, of  
Garden Grove, listed in critical condition today; customer Edward 
Kim, 18, of Garden Grove, in fair condition; Han Vo, 17, also in 
fair condition; and a 15-year-old boy who was treated for an ankle 
wound and released. The Kims were not related, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Garden Grove is about 35 miles southeast of Los Angeles.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
