<HEADLINE> Clintons Like $1.7M N.Y. Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SKANEATELES, N.Y. (AP) -- The house-hunting first family wants to  
buy a $1.7 million property in Westchester County near New York 
City, according to two people familiar with the search. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, are  
searching for a post-White House home in New York to help Mrs. 
Clinton establish residency in anticipation of her bid for a vacant 
Senate seat. The Clintons and daughter Chelsea toured the house in 
Chappaqua on Saturday on their way from one vacation stop on 
Martha's Vineyard off the Massachusetts coast to another on New 
York's Long Island. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear if they were prepared to make an offer, but two  
people familiar with the visit said the Clintons had their heart 
set on the house. They spent nearly two hours inspecting the white 
Georgian colonial, which boasts a swimming pool out back and an 
exercise room on the top floor. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials have said they will release details on any  
particular property only after a deal is sealed, not wanting to 
sour the Clintons' ability to negotiate. 
</P>
<P>
	The always cumbersome home-buying process is even further  
complicated for the Clintons, who must confer with the Secret 
Service about security issues and the White House counsel about 
legal matters related to their transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	The house sits screened by evergreens at the end of a cul-de-sac  
called Old House Lane, in a community described by neighbors as a 
quiet area with good schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very nice house, but we don't have any announcement to  
make,'' Clinton said after the visit. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
