<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Insists KLA Must Demilitarize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amid mixed signals from the Kosovo Liberation  
Army about its intentions, the State Department said Tuesday the 
KLA must abide by its promise to demilitarize by Sept. 19 and 
become a political entity. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman James Foley said the KLA military leadership has  
promised to fulfill that pledge during discussions this week with 
Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	But KLA military commander Agim Ceku said Monday the KLA would  
become a ``Kosovo army'' -- an entity not provided for in a June 
agreement signed by the KLA. 
</P>
<P>
	``The KLA will transform in several directions, not just into a  
military guard,'' Ceku said. ``One part will become part of the 
police, one part will become civil administration, one part will 
become the army of Kosovo, as a defense force. And another part 
will form a political party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Foley said the June agreements are unambiguous on what the  
KLA must do. 
</P>
<P>
	By Sept. 19, he said, ``the KLA must place all automatic  
small-arms in secure weapons storage sites and must cease wearing 
military uniforms and insignia ... September 19 is the last 
deadline envisaged under the agreement for KLA demilitarization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech at the American Enterprise Institute in Washington,  
Army Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's top commander in Europe, said 
demilitarization of the KLA ``seems to be very much on track.'' He 
said he was pleased at signs that some Serbs who had fled Kosovo 
are beginning to return. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., who has been visiting the Balkans  
this week, said Monday that congressional support for Kosovo 
Albanians would ``evaporate overnight'' if it became apparent they 
were not pursuing a democratic path. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the arrival of NATO-led peacekeepers in Kosovo last June,  
revenge killings and violence by ethnic Albanians targeting Serbs 
have derailed international attempts to establish normality. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, former U.S. Ambassador Thomas Melady, writing an  
opinion piece in Tuesday editions of the Washington Post, said the 
administration's policy of ``immediate reconciliation'' between 
Kosovo Albanians and Serbs is mistaken. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my opinion, it will not work,'' Melady wrote. ``Worse than  
that it will encourage more violence and instability in Kosovo. We 
now need a period of recuperation and healing. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we know from our Western experiences in the past several  
centuries, meaningful reconciliation will come after healing. In 
the West, it has come from the people; it has not been imposed by 
outside forces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Melady, who has served as ambassador to the Vatican, Burundi and  
Uganda, said his observations were based partly on his experience 
in Burundi. 
</P>
<P>
	He said there has been repeated ethnic strife there between  
Hutus and Tutsis since independence in 1962 despite the 
determination by ``outside forces'' that the two groups should live 
together in ``pluralistic democracy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
