<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 00:50:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Underwood a No-Show for Dolphins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIE, Fla. (AP) -- Rookie defensive end Dimitrius Underwood  
failed to show for his first practice with the Miami Dolphins, 
which didn't seem to bother coach Jimmy Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, who left the Minnesota Vikings unannounced to focus  
on his faith, was claimed off waivers Aug. 16 by the Dolphins and 
agreed to report for practice Monday. But he failed to make his 
flight Sunday night from Michigan to Fort Lauderdale. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said he's not bothered by Underwood's pattern of  
unreliability. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a tendency to straighten out those patterns,'' Johnson  
said. ``If the pattern stays the same, obviously we'll have to 
address it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood caught a later flight, arrived Monday night and was  
expected for practice today. The rookie's tardiness raised renewed 
doubts about his commitment to a football career. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to understand our motive here,'' Johnson said.  
``Our whole thought process was to get an outstanding talent for 
the future. It would have been fine with me if he had reported next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel he's going to want to play football eventually. We  
just didn't know when.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, 22, was taken by the Vikings with the 29th pick in  
the first round of the draft. He was released Aug. 11 by the 
Vikings after practicing just once, and this month he changed his 
mind about whether to play football at least four times -- maybe 
five. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood is already not the most popular player in the  
Dolphins' locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the guy can get his act together,'' said veteran  
defensive end Trace Armstrong, sitting across from Underwood's 
vacant stall. ``He's like everybody else -- he's got to earn a spot 
on this team. He's not off to a good start.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood's wavering between football and faith has attracted  
considerable national publicity. He made an appearance last week on 
Jim Rome's talk show on Fox Sports Net. 
</P>
<P>
	``I notice he did make the flight for the Jim Rome show,''  
Armstrong said. ``The thing that sticks in your throat is that if 
you bring a guy like that in, you're going to have to let somebody 
go. That can be tough to swallow, given the circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Underwood joins the team, he'll bump another defensive  
lineman from the roster even though he's unlikely to play much this 
season. His conditioning is questionable because he sat out last 
season at Michigan State with a sprained ankle, and the Dolphins 
don't need to rush him into the lineup because of their depth in 
the front four. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
