<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Excuses in `Alarm School' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OXNARD, Calif. (AP) -- Think of it as traffic school with bells  
and whistles. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents and business owners whose security systems keep going  
off, causing police to come running one time too many, can escape 
fines by taking a two-hour class on how to avoid false alarms. 
</P>
<P>
	The concept is believed to have been pioneered in Los Angeles,  
where about 129,000 false-alarm calls came in last year. Residents 
in the nation's second-largest city get two false calls, then a 
choice between an $80 fine or False Alarm Reduction Class. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar program recently began in Oxnard, a city of 160,000  
where police responded to 6,931 alarm calls in 1998. Of those, 98.8 
percent were false. It costs Oxnard police about $62.04 to respond 
to each call -- meaning $424,725 a year is wasted on false alarms. 
</P>
<P>
	In Oxnard, the class is for people whose burglar alarms have  
been wrong three or more times. City law forgives the first two, 
but a third false call carries a $75 fine, and $150 per call after 
that. Those who attend an alarm-school session, however, get a $150 
credit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is like traffic school,'' Sgt. Tom Chronister told the 45  
alarmists at the city's first-ever class. ``We want to work with 
you people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most homeowners said they forgot to close a door or window, but  
many were reluctant to admit they were at fault. 
</P>
<P>
	``A spider set it off,'' said one woman so security-conscious  
that she refused to give her name. 
</P>
<P>
	There were similar excuses:  
</P>
<P>
	``The motion detector was set too sensitive and there was a  
mouse. We got rid of that problem,'' said a man who also refused to 
give his name. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Santa Ana wind moved the drapes,'' a woman said.  
</P>
<P>
	``Birds get through the roll-up door and trigger the motion  
detector,'' a businessman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Vince Nigro, president of Southern California Security  
Association, stepped to the front of class with a helium ``Happy 
Birthday'' balloon. He used it to show how it can set off motion 
detectors by bobbing and floating around. 
</P>
<P>
	He said dogs and ceiling fans are also frequent motion-detector  
violators, and pointed out how even dust in the air can foul alarm 
sensors. 
</P>
<P>
	Chronister was an Oxnard canine unit officer who was so fed up  
with false-alarm calls that he organized the alarm education 
program. Already there has been a decrease in false alarms, Police 
Chief Art Lopez said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles, the classes might not be able to stop some of  
the worst offenders: local government and the police department 
itself. The LAPD, which is exempt from alarm fines, had 97 false 
alarms last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's embarrassing,'' said Lt. Ron Marbrey, who heads the  
force's alarm unit. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 10:18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> David Bowie Plans Album on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Rock star David Bowie is to release his new album  
on the Internet weeks before it appears in record stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans will be able to download ``hours...'' from the Web sites of  
about 50 major music retailers including Tower Records and Virgin 
from September 21 for a fee. CDs of the recording will not hit the 
shelves until Oct. 4 in Britain and the following day in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't be more pleased,'' Internet enthusiast Bowie said  
in a statement. He said he is determined to help Internet music 
releases become the norm rather than the exception. 
</P>
<P>
	A credit card payment will allow customers to download the album  
to their hard drive but, to combat piracy, they will not be able to 
transfer it to a disk. 
</P>
<P>
	The price will be set independently by the retailers but could  
be much lower than the cost of purchasing a conventional recording. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Bowie broke new ground with an Internet-only  
release of his song ``Telling Lies.'' Bowie also has his own 
Internet service provider, BowieNet, where fans who pay a monthly 
subscription can access a full news and sports service as well as 
watch the musician rehearsing in the studio. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowie's Internet site is at http://www.DavidBowie.com.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 08:02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Diana Remembered Two Years Later </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Two years after Princess Diana's fatal car crash,  
flowers, toys and photographs again decorate the gates in front of 
her Kensington Palace home and admirers come to mark her death. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where's Diana's memorial?'' read a placard that summed up what  
many people feel about today's anniversary of Diana's death in a 
Paris car crash on Aug. 31, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	John Loughrey, 44, from southwest London, held a vigil outside  
the palace gates today. ``I was here last year, and I was here for 
four days without sleep when she died,'' he said. ``I will keep 
coming back every year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, the Mirror newspaper has been campaigning for a  
permanent Diana memorial and claims to have had 144,000 phone calls 
of support. 
</P>
<P>
	A memorial committee set up last year had proposed a  
commemorative garden near Kensington Palace, but the plan was 
quietly put on hold after local residents objected. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are not so many people out here this year, and it's  
going to get less and less. That is why we need a permanent 
memorial,'' said Joyce Vanherring, 42, who visited the palace 
Monday with her daughter Emma, 13. 
</P>
<P>
	In Paris, meanwhile, French police stood guard today at the  
Flame of Liberty, the Paris statue that has become Diana's shrine 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	The monument attracted almost as many television news crews as  
tourists. Of the Diana fans who did stop by, most simply snapped a 
few pictures before heading on to other Paris sites. 
</P>
<P>
	England's Royal National Rose Society was to launch a new breed  
of rose today called England's Rose in honor of the princess. The 
rose is creamy pink with an apricot blush. Its fragrance is 
described as delicate, yet deceptively powerful. Five thousand 
plants will initially be released. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a rose of the greatest delicacy and charm,'' said  
breeder David Austin. ``I can think of no rose more suitable to 
bear Diana, Princess of Wales' name.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the princess' family planned low-key remembrances.  
</P>
<P>
	Diana's sons, Prince William, 17, and Prince Harry, 14, are  
spending the day at Balmoral, the royal estate in Scotland. On 
Sunday, they attended a prayer service at a nearby church along 
with their father, Prince Charles, Queen Elizabeth II and other 
members of the family. 
</P>
<P>
	Diana's brother, Earl Spencer, was to spend today at Althorp,  
the family estate where the princess is buried on an island. There 
is also an exhibition there about her, which is open to the public 
during the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the final day the exhibition was open, Althorp  
officials said there was a surge in visitors, many of whom didn't 
have tickets but wanted to pay their respects. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would estimate that there are at least 500 next to the lake,  
and as always the mood is very reflective and quiet,'' said 
Spencer's spokeswoman, Shelly-Ann Claircourt. 
</P>
<P>
	Debbie Martin, 34, who visited with her family, said: ``It was a  
wonderful experience -- very moving, and I am pleased we have been 
able to make it this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Calleja, 35, visiting from New York, was less  
impressed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a bit too commercial for my liking,'' she said. ``But  
it is nice to know I have been here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The anniversary came amid a controversy over a book planned by  
James Hewitt, Diana's former lover. Hewitt is reportedly going to 
publish his life story late this year or early next year, and is 
selling serialization rights to a tabloid. 
</P>
<P>
	Rival tabloids are expressing outrage at the distress this would  
cause Diana's sons and say he plans to make public some of the 
letters she wrote to him. Hewitt has said in the past he would 
never publish them, and his lawyer said Sunday that the letters 
would not be featured in the book. 
</P>
<P>
	Buckingham Palace on Monday refused to comment about Hewitt's  
book. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 08:02:13 </DATE_TIME>
