<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Said To Eye Reform Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PLYMOUTH, N.H. (AP) -- Pat Buchanan, the three-time presidential  
candidate whose 2000 campaign has been faltering, has intensified 
discussions about bolting the Republican Party. Supporters say he 
is more likely than ever to join the Reform Party. 
</P>
<P>
	The supporters, including top advisers to his campaign, say the  
discussions have included talk about possible running mates and 
potential strategy for capitalizing on the media attention that 
would be generated by his departure. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials spoke on condition of anonymity.  
</P>
<P>
	However, his sister and campaign adviser Bay Buchanan said in a  
recent interview that Buchanan is considering a switch. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is seriously considering this, but he won't have a decision  
anytime soon,'' said Buchanan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Associated Press reported earlier this month that Buchanan  
was mulling a departure from the Republican Party, but Bay 
Buchanan's comments marked the first on-the-record confirmation. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent meetings, Buchanan advisers have discussed how they  
could dovetail the release of his latest book, a foreign policy 
thesis and the accompanying book tour, with the announcement of his 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The advisers say the talks increasingly are conducted under the  
assumption that he will decide to leave the party. 
</P>
<P>
	In one recent meeting -- described as a brain storming session by  
one adviser -- Buchanan was said to have discussed the most 
politically beneficial attributes for a Reform Party running mate: 
an old-line Democrat with roots in the labor community. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials stressed that Buchanan has not made it clear  
whether or not he will leave the party but they said a decision 
could come as early as next month. He has not made a final 
decision, although the aides say he is leaning in the direction of 
a switch. 
</P>
<P>
	If he does leave, Buchanan would not be assured of the  
presidential nomination in the fractious Reform Party. Backers of 
Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura have wrested the party leadership from 
associates of party founder Ross Perot. 
</P>
<P>
	While Perot supporters, including 1996 vice presidential  
candidate Pat Choate and past chairman Russell Verney, would 
welcome Buchanan to the party, Ventura has been cool to the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reform Party nominee will have access to more than $12  
million in federal funding, millions more than Buchanan is expected 
to raise as a GOP candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said the intensified discussions about Buchanan moving to  
the Reform Party began after his disappointing fifth place finish 
in the GOP straw poll in Ames, Iowa, earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Buchanan was said to be worried that the Republican  
nomination process is geared in favor of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, 
and that he has little chance of winning or even pushing his social 
and economic issues to the forefront of the debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders worry that a Buchanan defection would drain  
support of the GOP's most conservative voters. Already, 
conservative Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire has abandoned the 
Republican Party for a third-party run at the White House. Buchanan 
defended him against criticism from GOP leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	In a little-noticed television interview in July, Buchanan  
complained that the GOP establishment had decided that he was not a 
viable candidate. ``If they slam those doors shut,'' he warned, 
``we'll just have to look for another way.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 18:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies' Manager Mum on Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Colorado Rockies manager Jim Leyland would not  
comment Tuesday on speculation that he wants to take a break from 
baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston Globe reported Sunday that the 54-year-old Leyland  
has told friends he wants to take a year off because he is worried 
he can no longer relate to the modern player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just don't want to comment about it,'' Leyland said Tuesday  
before Colorado's game against the Pittsburgh Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	Leyland, who signed a three-year, $6 million contract last  
winter, hinted he would return for at least another year as he 
talked about looking forward to seeing Colorado's young prospects 
during spring training in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockies have done little to inspire Leyland this season.  
With virtually the same roster that finished 77-85 under Don Baylor 
last year, the Rockies were 60-73 -- last in the NL West -- entering 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Leyland, who won the World Series with Florida in 1997, was  
expected to get Colorado back into playoff contention this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the team has struggled and he has expressed frustration  
with the limitations of managing at Coors Field, Leyland has not 
given any clear indication that he will leave the Rockies at the 
end of the year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 12:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Rules for Million Youth March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge ruled Tuesday that the Million Youth  
March can go forward in Harlem this weekend over the city's 
objections because the First Amendment protects even offensive 
speech. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Denny Chin said that many statements made by  
the event's organizers, including Khallid Abdul Muhammad, were 
``bigoted, hateful, violent and frightening.'' But he said that did 
not justify denying a permit for the rally. 
</P>
<P>
	The right to free speech ``applies not only to politically  
correct statements but also to statements with which we may 
disagree and, indeed, abhor,'' he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least as frightening as the rhetoric of Mr. Muhammad is the  
possibility of a society where freedom of speech is not respected 
and where the right to speak publicly can be denied on the basis of 
administrative whim, personal dislike or disapproval of anticipated 
content.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The city had said it would appeal any ruling that allowed the  
rally to go forward. It refused to grant a permit for the event, 
scheduled for Saturday, after organizers threatened to hold it with 
or without a permit. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Hess, the city's chief lawyer, argued that the rally  
should not be protected by the First Amendment because organizers 
made it clear they hoped to incite violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, a federal appeals court allowed a similar rally to  
take place but limited its size and duration. Twenty-eight people 
were injured, including 16 police officers, in a clash between 
police and participants. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said in a lawsuit that this year's rally will push  
for the elimination of police brutality and misconduct. It also 
will call for reparations for descendants of slaves, jobs for young 
people and an increase in spending on education. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Wareham, a lawyer for the Million Youth March, told the  
judge that the rally organizers were urging peace and could not be 
held accountable for everything every speaker said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not an official position that people should come armed  
and initiate action against the police,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wareham said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had a vendetta against  
Muhammad, who last year encouraged the crowd to beat or shoot 
officers if they were attacked. Some in the crowd threw barricades, 
chairs and bottles in the closing moments of the rally. 
</P>
<P>
	At a Harlem news conference Monday, Malik Shabazz, a march  
organizer, vowed that ``all efforts to stamp out the Million Youth 
March will be met with divine doom and destruction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shabazz insisted he was not advocating violence. But he decried  
the police shooting earlier this year of African immigrant Amadou 
Diallo and said: ``The only solution to us being gunned down and 
murdered like this is, every time you see a funeral like Amadou 
Diallo's funeral, that you see an equal funeral go down in the 
white community.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 00:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ways To Stem Employment Losses Eyed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is looking for ways  
to stem employment losses among the nation's manufacturers, who 
have lost nearly half a million jobs over the last 18 months 
despite the strong economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president and vice president have been committed to  
putting a specific focus on any part of the economy that has not 
shared in the strong economic times,'' said Gene Sperling, director 
of the National Economic Council. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is working with economists and labor leaders  
to come up with proposals the president can make in his next State 
of the Union address in January. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal in the task force is to take a broad-based look at  
everything from export policies to tax policies,'' Sperling said in 
a recent interview. Worker training is also under scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor is a key Democratic party constituency, one that Vice  
President Al Gore is counting on to support his 2000 presidential 
campaign. The administration also wants to involve manufacturers in 
the process. 
</P>
<P>
	But some business leaders are not convinced there is a problem.  
They note that while manufacturing employment is down, productivity 
is on the rise. 
</P>
<P>
	``The focus of the task force should be to investigate ways to  
sustain manufacturing's decade-long resurgence, not formulate a 
centrally planned national industrial policy or attempt to fix a 
nonexistent problem,'' said Paul Huard, a vice president of the 
National Association of Manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	But the AFL-CIO, in a report to the administration, said the  
manufacturing sector ``is in crisis, having lost 491,000 jobs since 
March 1998. Little has been done to assist manufacturing companies 
in coping.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sperling agreed that there have been ``significant losses'' in  
manufacturing over the last year and a half. However, he said the 
sector lost as many as 2 million jobs in the decade before 
President Clinton took office. 
</P>
<P>
	The sector gained 800,000 back during the first five years of  
his administration, thanks in part to federal support for 
shipyards. 
</P>
<P>
	He and labor analysts agree that the Asian financial crisis and  
subsequent monetary devaluations around the globe are largely to 
blame for the U.S. job losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor and business leaders both would like to see greater  
incentives for manufacturers to invest in retraining workers. 
</P>
<P>
	But some of labor's suggested solutions are unlikely to win  
administration support, such as devaluing the dollar and urging the 
Federal Reserve not to raise interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has long been our policy that we are for a strong dollar  
and not using it as an instrument of trade policy,'' Sperling said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other labor proposals include renegotiating the North American  
Free Trade Agreement to increase worker protections, making it 
easier to invest pension funds in pro-union businesses, and cutting 
foreign tax credits. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has committed to resisting any weakening of  
worker protections in the upcoming round of World Trade 
Organization talks and enforcing such safeguards in other trade 
agreements. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 16:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Verdicts Out in Two Oil Suits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A jury rejected California's claim that Exxon  
Corp. owed the state up to $750 million for underpricing oil pumped 
from public lands during the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	In a similar case, a subsidiary of Los Angeles-based Occidental  
Petroleum agreed to pay $7.3 million to settle claims that is 
undervalued oil it pumped from federal land, the Justice Department 
announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Exxon case, a Superior Court jury deliberated 16 days  
before deciding Monday that California received fair royalty 
payments for oil taken from the 8,000-acre Wilmington field near 
Long Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors also said Exxon did not act in bad faith or manipulate  
oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
	California claimed that the company had shortchanged the state  
about $350 million for oil pumped from 1981 to 1989. With interest, 
that sum would have grown to $750 million, said Larry Feldman, a 
Santa Monica attorney who represented Irving, Texas-based Exxon. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision showed there was no basis for the state's  
allegations, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A jury looked at this for three long weeks and concluded that  
there was no basis for this suit,'' Feldman said. ``I hope this 
sends a message that the government's argument is plain wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The decision also could discourage future royalties lawsuits,  
said Martin Brian McMahon, an attorney for the state. 
</P>
<P>
	The state argued Wilmington crude oil was sold at up to $4 per  
barrel less than Alaska's North Slope crude oil. That oil was 
purchased by the same refineries that bought the Wilmington crude 
oil. The state said in a competitive market, prices should have 
been the same after adjustments for quality differences. 
</P>
<P>
	Exxon said other factors, such as shipping costs, can affect the  
price. 
</P>
<P>
	Texaco, Union Oil, Mobil Oil and Shell Oil had already paid the  
state $345 million to settle the same claims stemming from their 
operations at the Wilmington field. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Occidental case, Oxy USA Inc. was accused of undervaluing  
oil pumped between 1988 and 1997 from federal lands. The lawsuit 
was filed in U.S. District Court in Lufkin, Texas. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
