<HEADLINE> Pakistan Army Claims Indian Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Indian soldiers crossed the volatile  
Kashmir border into Pakistan to try to capture a military post, but 
were repulsed, the Pakistani army said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	India denied launching an attack.  
</P>
<P>
	A statement from the Pakistani army said Indian soldiers, backed  
by heavy artillery fire, entered Pakistan Monday to launch a ground 
assault on a post in Shyok-Turtok. That is near Kargil, where 
Pakistani and Indian soldiers waged a bitter battle this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``A large number of enemy troops were killed and injured,'' the  
army statement said. It said three Pakistani soldiers were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	An Indian army spokesman, Col. Shruti Kant, said ``no such  
attack was launched.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, India rejected Pakistan's demand for $60 million  
in compensation for shooting down a naval surveillance plane three 
weeks ago, killing 16 Pakistani personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a combat aircraft. It was on a military mission,''  
Foreign Minister Jaswant Singh told reporters. ``It was violating 
Indian air space.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan says the plane was on a routine training mission and  
that India shot it down inside Pakistan's air space. 
</P>
<P>
	Relations are uneasy between the world's newest nuclear  
neighbors. They are locked in a protracted dispute over Kashmir, a 
Himalayan state divided between Pakistan and India after British 
rule in the region ended in 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	New Delhi accuses Islamabad of supporting Muslim insurgents in  
Kashmir, who are waging a decade-old war demanding either outright 
independence or union with Islamic Pakistan. Pakistan says it gives 
only political and diplomatic support. 
</P>
<P>
	Kashmir has been the flash point of two wars between Pakistan  
and India. It came very close to sparking another war this summer 
after Pakistan-backed militants took control of Indian military 
posts in the Kargil sector of Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan ordered the militants to withdraw, but tension between  
the two neighbors remained high. Then, on Aug. 10, India shot down 
the Pakistani military aircraft. Pakistan has demanded a United 
Nations-sponsored investigation as well as the financial 
compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	Singh said Tuesday he would probably meet with Pakistan's  
foreign minister at the United Nations, and was not laying any 
preconditions for the resumption of peace talks between the 
countries. But, he said, referring to the Kashmiri rebels, ``for 
reasonable, meaningful talks to take place between India and 
Pakistan, it is imperative for Pakistan to stop supporting 
terrorism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Singh also accused Pakistan of encouraging a regional small arms  
and narcotics trade stemming from instability in Afghanistan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
