<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Close Sharply Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks closed sharply lower on Tuesday,  
following an overnight drop on Wall Street and further weakness in 
the U.S. dollar against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 482.41 points,  
or 2.69 percent, to 17,436.56 at the end of daily trading. On 
Monday, the average closed up 319.60 points, or 1.82 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 110.78 yen, down 0.26 yen from its level of  
111.04 yen late Monday in Tokyo but higher than its late New York 
level of 110.73 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Tokyo share prices started lower as  
investor sentiment was damped by another overnight fall in New York 
and the weaker dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average lost 176.04  
points to close Monday at 10,914.13, declining for the third 
consecutive session. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest Japanese economic report showing worse-than-expected  
industrial production figures was also weighing on Japanese stock 
prices, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ministry of International Trade and Industry said production  
fell 0.6 percent in July from June after adjustment for seasonal 
factors. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists surveyed by Dow Jones Newswires had projected on  
average that industrial output would be up 0.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Retreats outnumbered gains 861 to 337 on the Tokyo Stock  
Exchange's First Section, while 100 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section closed down 40.92 points, or 2.73 percent, to 
1,457.02. The TOPIX closed up 19.56 points, or 1.32 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar moved as high as 110.95 yen  
early in the session after the Japanese government released the 
industrial output data. 
</P>
<P>
	But the greenback's gains were quickly pared on expectations the  
yen will strengthen as Japan's overall economy heads for recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 116.58 yen, up from  
116.09 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.9150 percent from Monday's finish of 1.9850 percent, 
driving its price up to 99.87 yen from 99.29 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
