<HEADLINE> Indians' Gooden Activated From DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Dwight Gooden was activated from the 15-day  
disabled list by the Cleveland Indians on Tuesday, just hours 
before he was scheduled to make his first start since Aug. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Gooden was placed on the DL on Aug. 3, one day after he was  
removed from a start in Boston after just 2 2-3 innings because of 
a strained right shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	In 21 appearances this season, 17 starts, the right-hander is  
3-3 with a 5.81 ERA. On Tuesday, he will start against Anaheim's 
Chuck Finley, the left-hander the Indians pursued before the July 
31 trading deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	To make room for Gooden, the Indians optioned left-handed  
reliever Tom Martin to Triple-A Buffalo. He was 0-0 with a 9.00 ERA 
in two appearances since coming off a four-month stay on the DL 
following off-season shoulder surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, the Indians faced the possibility that Sandy  
Alomar's left knee may keep him out of the playoffs, acquiring 
catcher Tyler Houston from the Chicago Cubs for minor league 
pitcher Richard Negrette. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians added two other players to their 25-man roster in  
anticipation of Tuesday's midnight playoff roster deadline, 
purchasing the contract of lefty reliever Jim Poole from Double-A 
Akron and right-hander Sean DePaula from Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	Poole, signed to a contract on Aug. 26 after being released by  
Philadelphia, is in his third career stint with the Indians. The 
33-year-old pitched for the Indians in 1995-96 and made 12 
appearances for Cleveland last season after being let go by San 
Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1998 playoffs, Poole did not allow a run in six  
appearances against Boston and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Cleveland placed right-hander Jason Rakers on the  
60-day disabled list with a pulled groin, and right-hander David 
Riske on the 15-day DL, retroactive to Aug. 25, with a pulled 
oblique muscle. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians also sent left-hander Jimmy Hamilton to Baltimore to  
complete the Harold Baines trade. Hamilton split the season between 
Akron and Buffalo, posting a combined 1-4 record in 51 games. 
  	   	
</P>
