<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hatch Visit Unwelcome in Iowa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KEOKUK, Iowa (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Orrin Hatch  
made an unexpected -- and unwelcome -- address to a meeting of area 
economic development officials from Iowa, Illinois and Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	``He should not have been here,'' Paul Elgatian of the  
University of Illinois Extension Service said after Monday's 
meeting. ``I respect the senator, but I am disappointed that he was 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 70 participants were holding a brainstorming session on ways  
to develop and market value-added agricultural products from the 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	The Utah senator spoke to the group for about 30 minutes,  
emphasizing the need to appoint conservative federal judges, and 
took questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Elgatian advised members to disregard Hatch's  
comments and not let them color their views. ``It taints the 
process,'' Elgatian said. ``It gets people thinking in a different 
direction, not their own perspective. You have to divorce yourself 
of those influences and it's not easy to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elgatian, whose party affiliation was not known, said he had not  
invited Hatch and did not know who did. 
</P>
<P>
	Des Moines County Supervisor Ben Diewold, the Democratic  
chairman of the Tri-State Value-Added Agricultural Marketing 
Committee, also said he had not invited the senator and that 
Hatch's speech ``took up a lot of our time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of these people took time off from their work to be  
here,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Diewold said Tuesday, ``No one said his visit was not  
appreciated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch's Iowa campaign director, David Wolfson, said the  
invitation was extended by an aide to Robert Ireland, CEO of 
Roquette America, which helped sponsor the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Roquette said he did not invite Hatch.  
</P>
<P>
	He said the Hatch campaign had called his office hoping to set  
up a tour of his plant, which turns corn starch into a variety of 
products including pharmaceuticals and corn-syrup products. But the 
campaign was told a visit could not be arranged because he would be 
attending the meeting. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
