<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congo Rebels Sign Cease-Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) -- Congolese rebel leaders today signed a  
cease-fire to end the year-old Congo civil war, raising hopes for 
peace in Africa's biggest multinational conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifty-one founding members of the rebel group, Congolese Rally  
for Democracy, took part in the signing ceremony, ending six weeks 
of wrangling over whose names should appear on the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Emile Ilunga, head of the largest faction of the Congolese Rally  
for Democracy, added his signature to the accord, which was passed 
to the rebel leaders in alphabetical order of their names. His 
chief rival in the split group, Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, was to be 
one of the last to sign in the ceremony at a Lusaka hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Rachid Lallali of Algeria, nominated as neutral head of a  
Joint Military Commission to oversee the cease-fire until 
international peacekeepers are in place, witnessed the signing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our expectations are very high...that the agreement will be  
fully implemented now that all political leaders are supporting it 
jointly,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The peace accord calls for a cease-fire within 24 hours between  
the rebels, Congolese President Laurent Kabila and the adjacent 
nations that support one side or the other. It also calls for the 
formation of a joint military commission headed by Lallali and a 
90-day political dialogue to be followed by free elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The Congolese Rally for Democracy, or RCD, had been the only  
group not to have signed the pact mediated by Zambian President 
Frederick Chiluba. 
</P>
<P>
	Bringing the seven warring parties to the peace table has  
consumed diplomatic efforts throughout Africa for the past year, 
starting with the first peace conference in Victoria Falls, 
Zimbabwe, last August. 
</P>
<P>
	Chiluba and Tanzanian and South African leaders have shuttled  
around the continent, trying to round up signatures from the six 
countries and two rebel groups involved in the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Kabila and leaders from the countries that backed him --  
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- signed the peace accord, which calls 
for free elections on July 10. The leaders of Rwanda and Uganda, 
which have backed rebels trying to unseat Kabila, also signed. 
</P>
<P>
	But fighting continued in Congo as the two rebel groups -- the  
RCD and the Congolese Liberation Movement -- refused to sign the 
accord. 
</P>
<P>
	The Congolese Liberation Movement finally signed several weeks  
ago, but the larger of the two groups, the RCD, did not. It was 
split by a leadership dispute that spilled over into violent 
battles in the Congolese town of Kisangani in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Congolese war has threatened development and security in  
central Africa, continuing the chaos that started when Kabila 
unseated former dictator Mobutu Sese Seko in 1997, when the country 
was still known as Zaire. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations expects to deploy the first 17 military  
liaison officers in the capitals of Congo, Rwanda, Uganda and 
possibly Zambia by Saturday to prepare for a U.N. role in 
implementing the peace accord. Observers from the Organization of 
African Unity are also expected to be deployed. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials estimate a future peacekeeping operation could  
require a minimum of 25,000 soldiers. South Africa has already 
promised troops. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
