<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Intrudes on Clintons' Vacation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SKANEATELES, N.Y. (AP) -- President Clinton and the first lady  
came in for a little needling Tuesday during their vacation at the 
Finger Lakes when the Republican National Committee began airing a 
commercial touting the GOP's tax cut plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most folks in Skaneateles don't get to stay for free in  
multimillion-dollar vacation estates; don't get to travel free on 
planes paid for by the taxpayers,'' RNC chairman Jim Nicholson said 
at news conference in nearby Auburn, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad showed Nicholson seated next to an open briefcase with  
$10,000 in cash -- the amount he said an average New Yorker would 
save over 10 years if Clinton signed the GOP tax cut. ``Most folks 
never get to see what $10,000 looks like,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Airing only on cable television in Skaneateles, where the  
president and Hillary Rodham Clinton are spending the second week 
of their vacation with daughter Chelsea, the ad was unlikely to 
influence many voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson said it was intended primarily for the president's  
consumption, but the timing and placement suggested that its 
creators also hoped to rain a little on the Clintons' vacation, 
which has included several fund-raisers and public events to 
benefit Mrs. Clinton, who is likely to run for New York's open 
Senate seat next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Clinton ... won't you take a moment from your vacation to  
talk about real tax relief with Hillary and Al (Gore)?'' Nicholson 
said in the ad. ``You'll be glad you did when you're living in New 
York -- or whatever state you decide to call home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes also is running  
radio commercials in the area that criticize Vice President Al 
Gore's role in U.S.-Russia relations and urge Clinton to sign the 
$792 billion package of tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Jake Siewert said Mrs. Clinton's  
exploratory committee has paid for events that White House lawyers 
determined were political in nature, including a stop Monday at the 
New York State Fair. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's committee also has a separate advance team and  
spokesman working the area. Siewert said the rules Mrs. Clinton 
must follow for her own political endeavors are no different from 
rules previous first ladies obeyed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The exact same rules applied, whether another first lady  
campaigned for another candidate or the party or her husband,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Siewert said Clinton still intends to veto the proposed tax-cut  
bill when Congress sends it to him because it wouldn't do enough to 
shore up Social Security or pay down the national debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Alluding to recent public opinion polls, he also suggested that  
Republicans have failed to garner much public support for the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that the longer the Republicans talk about their  
tax cut, the less popular it seems to be,'' Siewert said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons didn't let the political back-and-forth interrupt  
their fun in the sun. The president played golf with Democratic 
fund-raiser Terence McAuliffe, who hails from Syracuse, and a few 
local political and business leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton spent much of the day reading at the vacation  
house, a spokesman said. Chelsea went on a sightseeing trip through 
the village of Skaneateles and stopped to shake hands. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
