<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Hears Case on Kerouac Estate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA FE (AP) -- The state Supreme Court heard arguments Monday  
on the tangled estate and literary archives of Jack Kerouac, whose 
1957 novel ``On the Road'' chronicled the restless spirit of the 
Beat generation. 
</P>
<P>
	After an hour of argument, the court gave no indication when it  
would rule on an appeal from a San Francisco Bay area writer who 
hopes to protect the disputed interests of Kerouac's daughter, the 
late Jan Kerouac. 
</P>
<P>
	The daughter had been in the midst of contesting the will of  
Kerouac's mother when she died in Albuquerque in 1996. The will of 
Kerouac's mother, Gabrielle Kerouac, left the Kerouac property to 
the author's third wife. The wife died in 1990, leaving the 
property in the hands of her relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerouac biographer Gerald Nicosia, who was named ``literary  
executor'' of the daughter's estate, maintains Kerouac's estate, 
including unpublished manuscripts, journals, and thousands of 
letters, which could be worth as much as $20 million. Jack Kerouac 
died of liver failure in 1969 at age 47. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicosia argued that Jan Kerouac's wishes for her father's estate  
deserve to be honored by courts in New Mexico and Florida, where 
the daughter had been contesting her grandmother's will. 
</P>
<P>
	She wanted to place her father's archives with the Bancroft  
Library at the University of California, Berkeley, where they would 
be available to scholars and writers, rather than having them sold 
piecemeal to collectors, Nicosia said. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Sept. 1998, the New Mexico Court of Appeals had ruled  
against Nicosia, finding that he had no legal authority to make 
decisions about a lawsuit contesting the will of Kerouac's mother, 
who inherited her son's property when he died in 1969. 
</P>
<P>
	That court ruling gave Jan Kerouac's ex-husband, John Lash of  
Brussels, Belgium, complete authority of her estate. Lash has 
sought to drop her 1994 Florida lawsuit challenging the will. 
</P>
<P>
	That effort is on hold pending a resolution in New Mexico  
courts. 
</P>
<P>
	If Nicosia's efforts are ultimately successful, Jan Kerouac's  
estate would receive one-third of her father's estate, her cousin 
would get one-third and the Sampas family retain one-third. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicosia's lawyer, Jerome Field, contended that Jan Kerouac's  
will made his client responsible for all decisions involving 
literary works and archival materials. 
</P>
<P>
	Lash's attorney, David Reynolds, argued that Nicosia's role was  
limited to serving as a ``literary agent'' and responsible for 
getting the ``best return'' on literary rights currently held by 
Jan Kerouac's estate. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides ``On the Road,'' Jack Kerouac was known for books such  
as ``The Dharma Bums'' (1958) and ``Desolation Angels'' (1965). 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 08:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CompUSA Loss Less Than Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Shares of CompUSA fell today after it announced  
layoffs and posted a loss yesterday. The loss, however, was less 
than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Looking to remake itself as a leaner company in touch with its  
customers, CompUSA announced it is laying off 1,800 sales people 
and reassigning many of those who remain. 
</P>
<P>
	The cutbacks at the Dallas-based computer retailer were prompted  
by another money-losing quarter. The company posted a loss of $14.9 
million, or 16 cent a share, in the quarter ended June 26. Analysts 
had predicted a loss of 24 cents a share. In the same quarter last 
year, the company lost 19 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading today, shares of CompUSA dropped about 10 percent  
before recovering slightly. By late morning, shares were down 43 3/4 
cents to $6.25 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief executive Jim Halpin acknowledged that the past year has  
been a difficult one. The Computer City stores that CompUSA bought 
are still underperforming, and the chain has been hammered by 
steadily dropping prices of its major commodity, personal 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Halpin said the cost-cutting should save $100 million a year,  
and while ``today, there's not too much we can do about employee 
morale'' amid all the layoffs, he vowed to communicate the 
company's strategy to the remaining employees, starting with 
broadcast presentations to store employees today. 
</P>
<P>
	Halpin said many of the workers being laid off at stores around  
the country worked with unprofitable corporate, government and 
education customers. Another 300 layoffs are coming, he said, which 
will bring the total since June to 2,700. 
</P>
<P>
	To get out of the tailspin, CompUSA is recasting itself as an  
all-around consumer electronics store, trying to copy the strategy 
of its more-successful rivals, Minnesota-based Best Buy and 
Virginia-based Circuit City. It will emphasize products such as 
handheld personal organizers, digital cameras and camcorders, and 
DVDs. 
</P>
<P>
	Halpin said he is pleased with progress of a company  
restructuring that was announced in June, and analysts seemed 
generally pleased with the company's recent moves. 
</P>
<P>
	``With a company as much in transition as CompUSA is, what's  
important is the direction they're headed,'' said Harry Katica, an 
analyst for Prudential Securities. ``I think they're reacting 
appropriately to very difficult industry circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings report had been delayed nearly two weeks while the  
company finished details of restructuring efforts. The company has 
closed four stores and Halpin said another 10 ``marginal'' stores 
could be closed. 
</P>
<P>
	The retailer reported net sales in the fourth quarter of $1.46  
billion, up 23 percent over a year ago, but sales at stores open 
one year or more rose just 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	For the 1999 fiscal year, the company reported an operating loss  
of $54.2 million, or 50 cents per share, compared with operating 
income of $57.2 million, or 33 cents per share for fiscal 1998. 
Sales in stores open at least a year fell 3.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials also said they hope to spin off an Internet  
subsidiary, CompUSA Net.com Inc., first with a private offering and 
later a public offering. Halpin said the company will retain 
majority interest in the Internet operation even after a public 
sale of stock. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 15:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers' West Hopeful on New Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Jerry West, a couple of days removed from  
completing reconstruction of the Los Angeles Lakers, paused Tuesday 
to contemplate the remarkable difference a year can make. 
</P>
<P>
	In a month, the Lakers will open camp with new, high-profile  
coach Phil Jackson, a stable roster to which the one missing piece 
-- a power forward -- is about to be added, all while preparing to 
move into a glittering new home and knowing they will be playing an 
82-game season. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the next couple of days, we will acquire another veteran  
player to help us up front,'' West said. ``The sooner, the 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers had been courting Charles Oakley, but he re-signed  
with Toronto on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	West would not specify whether he continues to pursue a free  
agent or work a trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's too much talk and speculation as it is,'' the Lakers'  
vice president said. ``I prefer to keep it behind the scenes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But West, in Anaheim to bring attention to the Lakers' Oct. 28  
exhibition game in the Arrowhead Pond against the Utah Jazz, did 
not try to hide his enthusiasm for the coming season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always valued continuity, not having a lot of changes,  
and we're at that point in time,'' West said. ``I believe we have 
three of the top 25 players in the NBA. We already had the top two 
draws (Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant), then we added a premier 
shooter (Glen Rice). 
</P>
<P>
	``There are many reasons for hope and enthusiasm for our veteran  
players, and for fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, the NBA was barricaded by a lockout that would slash  
the season to 50 games. The Lakers endured more turbulence than 
most teams, going through two coaches, Del Harris and Kurt Rambis, 
and the weirdness of Dennis Rodman, on their way to being swept out 
of the playoffs by eventual champion San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had a lot of people around the league come up to me and  
say that was the most miserable season they've ever went through,'' 
West said. ``But we had nothing to be ashamed of. As unsettling a 
year as it was, we were fortunate to win as many games as we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the summer, the Lakers re-signed Derek Fisher and Rick  
Fox to long-term contracts and quickly invoked their contract 
option on Rice. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've definitely put together a team to pursue a  
championship,'' said Fox, who accompanied West to the news 
conference. ``We have the best players and the best coach to go 
with them. It's gratifying, to me, to know I'm in business with 
people who understand what's needed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That, West reiterated, does not include Rodman, who recently has  
been trying his hardest to talk his way back into the Lakers' 
picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really think it's time to put Dennis Rodman behind us,''  
West said. ``If he were to come back, I'd welcome him with open 
arms because we now have a coach who can handle him. But I really 
think it's time to put that to rest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers' appearance at the Pond, their final exhibition game  
of the preseason, will be their last southern California appearance 
before they play their first game at the new Staples Center. Los 
Angeles will open its season on Nov. 2 against the Jazz in Utah, 
then meet Vancouver at Staples on Nov. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a little depressing for us old folks,'' West said of the  
move out of the Great Western Forum. ``There are a lot of memories 
there. Every time I fly over it, it's very nostalgic, and I'll miss 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``But that (Staples) building is amazing, with all the  
amenities. '' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 18:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Juror Giuliani Hears Scalding Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- All eyes were on the jury box and the No. 1  
juror -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani -- as testimony got under way Tuesday 
in a state courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor was picked Monday to hear a $7 million civil case in  
which a man is suing his landlord claiming he was badly scalded 
while taking a shower. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Giuliani strolled from City Hall to the courthouse  
Tuesday, the former federal prosecutor said he was looking forward 
to jury duty. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is basically a fascinating experience to be on the other  
side,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 35 people watched portions of the trial and the court  
assigned four security guards to the case, three more than normal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't usually have that many people in the audience, and  
they're here, obviously, because your honor the mayor is here,'' 
Justice Elliot Wilk told jurors. ``Your focus must be on the case 
and not anything else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though the testimony often included graphic language, the mayor  
remained impassive, his arms folded. He watched the attorneys and 
witnesses carefully. 
</P>
<P>
	New York passed a jury reform law in 1995 that eliminated  
exemptions for lawyers and other professionals. Giuliani was chosen 
as foreman of the six-member jury solely by virtue of his seat 
assignment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 18:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs Trade Beck, Houston </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Last year, the Chicago Cubs were chasing the NL  
wild card. This year, they're dealing players like a spare parts 
shop. 
</P>
<P>
	With any hope of the playoffs -- or even a .500 record, for that  
matter -- dead for weeks, the Cubs traded closer Rod Beck to the 
Boston Red Sox and catcher Tyler Houston to the Cleveland Indians 
on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``From year to year you're going to have turnover on your  
roster,'' Cubs general manager Ed Lynch said. ``It's pretty clear 
that we're going to try to do the best we can to improve the club. 
</P>
<P>
	``More of a motivation for us,'' he added, ``when we have a  
chance to add quality arms, I think that's important that we 
continue to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs got reliever Mark Guthrie and a player to be named for  
Beck, and minor league pitcher Richard Negrette for Houston as 
clubs in the pennant race tried to beef up their rosters. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a solid, dependable reliever who can help us get the last  
couple of outs in the ballgame,'' Boston general manager Dan 
Duquette said. ``Beck is a reliable, dependable closer with playoff 
experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs wouldn't have reached the NL playoffs without Beck last  
season. He became the fifth pitcher with 50 saves, converting 51 of 
58 opportunities. But he faltered at the start of this year, going 
2-4 with four blown saves and a 10.54 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	He was placed on the disabled list May 17 with bone spurs and  
chips in his right elbow, and underwent surgery five days later. He 
was activated July 21. 
</P>
<P>
	``Naturally, had I been healthy all year, maybe things would  
have been different here,'' Beck said. ``I know I'm ready to go, 
but I'm also pleased that Boston had enough confidence in me to 
know what kind of player I am, that I am going to be healthy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He has a 5.51 ERA and no decisions in 15 games since returning  
from the DL, though he pitched six scoreless innings in his last 
four outings. He has an overall record of 2-4 with seven saves and 
a 7.80 ERA this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch said he didn't try to trade Beck, but Boston sought him  
persistently over the last few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a case of they don't want me here,'' Beck said. ``But  
the Cubs aren't going to win anything this year and I figure with 
the lean free agent market this year, they need to fill a lot of 
holes on this ball club and the only way they're going to do that 
is through trades.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beck, 31, signed with the Cubs as a free agent in January 1998  
after spending seven seasons in San Francisco. He is 26-36 with 257 
saves and a 3.23 ERA in 528 major league games, all in relief. 
</P>
<P>
	He signed a two-year, $9.5 million deal after last season, with  
a club option for 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, I'm moving up quite a bit in the standings and have  
a chance to do some winning,'' he said. ``But when I signed on here 
for three years, I sort of figured I would play here for three 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beck will report to Boston in time for Wednesday's game. He  
might be used as a setup man at first, though the Red Sox badly 
need another closer. 
</P>
<P>
	After Tom Gordon was lost for the season with an elbow injury in  
June, the Red Sox went to closer-by-committee with Derek Lowe and 
knuckleballer Tim Wakefield. 
</P>
<P>
	But when Bret Saberhagen was hurt earlier this month, Wakefield  
was moved back to the rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this time of the year, when you're going into the  
postseason, it's to a team's advantage to have two solid closers,'' 
Duquette said. ``Beck has regained the arm strength that made him 
one of the premier closers in baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guthrie, a left-hander, is 1-1 with a 5.83 ERA in 46 relief  
outings this season. He is 35-38 with 12 saves and a 4.14 ERA in 
491 games. 
</P>
<P>
	The 33-year-old has pitched for Minnesota, Los Angeles and the  
Red Sox in a 10-year career. He went to the World Series with the 
Twins in 1991, and made it to the NL playoffs in 1995 and 1996 with 
the Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians, facing the possibility that Sandy Alomar's left  
knee may keep him out of the playoffs, acquired insurance in 
Houston, who is hitting .233 with nine home runs and 27 RBIs in 100 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	The versatile, left-handed hitter has appeared in 18 games at  
catcher and 63 games at third base. He has a career major league 
average of .260 with 23 home runs and 115 RBIs in 346 games with 
Atlanta and the Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians will remove a player from its 40-man roster when  
Houston reports to Cleveland on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar, hitting .317 with three homers and 16 RBIs in 82 at-bats  
this year, went on the disabled list May 21, had surgery 10 days 
later and has been rehabbing ever since. 
</P>
<P>
	Negrette, 23, is 1-3 with one save and a 6.15 ERA in 33 relief  
appearances for Double-A Akron this year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 08:00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ethnic Albanians Warned To Disarm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Saying racism is at the root of  
ethnic tensions in Kosovo, U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke told ethnic 
Albanian leaders that congressional support will evaporate if they 
don't disarm their guerrilla army. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy rains forced Holbrooke, newly confirmed as U.S. ambassador  
to the United Nations, to cancel a trip to Albania today for talks 
on ways to stabilize the southern Balkans after a 78-day NATO 
bombing campaign against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he flew to Macedonia, where he met with Macedonian  
President Kiro Gligorov and praised his policies for keeping the 
country at peace in an area wracked by war. Holbrooke was scheduled 
to fly to Bosnia later today. 
</P>
<P>
	In Pristina, Holbrooke urged an end to the postwar ethnic  
violence blocking international efforts to establish normality in 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me just stress again what ethnic differences in this  
region really are. They're just racism,'' Holbrooke said Monday 
after meetings with ethnic Albanian leaders in Kosovo. ``The Serbs 
of this region have a historic right to live here, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke was referring to attacks against Serbs by ethnic  
Albanians seeking revenge for the atrocities committed against them 
by Serb-led Yugoslav forces during President Slobodan Milosevic's 
18-month crackdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Those attacks have persisted despite the presence of 40,000 NATO  
and Russian peacekeepers who arrived June 12 in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke was joined Monday in the Kosovo capital by the ranking  
Democrat on the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Sen. Joseph 
Biden. 
</P>
<P>
	Biden made clear that the Kosovo Liberation Army must cease to  
exist as an armed force by a Sept. 19 deadline set in an agreement 
between NATO and the ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it appeared as though the very forces ... and people we  
came to help were now not engaged on a path that was moving toward 
democratization, support from the U.S. Congress would evaporate 
overnight,'' Biden said at a joint news conference Monday with 
Holbrooke. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the KLA's military commander assured Holbrooke that  
the former guerrillas would honor the demilitarization agreement 
and meet the deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the commander, Agim Ceku, also said the KLA would  
become a ``Kosovo army,'' an entity not provided for in the June 
demilitarization agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The KLA will transform in several directions, not just into a  
military guard,'' Ceku said. ``One part will become part of the 
police, one part will become civil administration, one part will 
become the Army of Kosovo, as a defense force. And another part 
will form a political party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke refused to comment on Ceku's remarks or explain how  
they would coexist with the conditions set down in the June deal 
that followed the NATO air campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Biden said that despite ethnic violence, Washington remains  
committed to building a multiethnic society in this troubled 
province. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see a short-term solution,'' Biden said. ``But I think  
it would be a mistake of historical proportions if the West 
concluded that there was no possibility of multi-ethnicity in 
Kosovo and there was de facto partitioning in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There has been little sign of reconciliation between Serbs and  
Albanians, who formed 90 percent of Kosovo's prewar population of 
2.1 million. As a sign of the bitterness, ethnic Albanians in 
Orahovac refused again Monday to lift the barricades they erected a 
week ago to prevent Russian peacekeepers from entering the town. 
</P>
<P>
	Albanians claim Russian mercenaries fought with the Serbs during  
the 18-month crackdown. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 01:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Backs Off Boycotting Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura was ``kidding'' when  
he said he planned to cancel his office's subscriptions to the 
Saint Paul Pioneer Press, his spokesman says. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we're going to be canceling any newspaper  
subscriptions,'' John Wodele said Monday. ``He was kidding when he 
said it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura on Friday called the state's second-largest newspaper  
the ``Saint Paul Pioneer Porn'' for running advertisements for 
X-rated movies and strip clubs in its sports section. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura was angered by criticism from the paper's editorial page  
staff and columnists after the governor's guest appearance Aug. 22 
at SummerSlam, a World Wrestling Federation event. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor said the newspaper was hypocritical by criticizing  
him for appearing at an event with choreographed violence, scantily 
clad women and vulgar language when, at the same time, it runs 
advertisements for X-rated movies and strip clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura felt the newspaper ``ought to take a look at their own  
policies'' if they were going to criticize professional wrestling, 
Wodele said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura told listeners during his radio show that he planned to  
cancel all subscriptions to the newspaper in the governor's office 
and deny interview requests from the paper's reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Wodele refused to comment Monday on whether Pioneer Press  
reporters would be granted interviews with the governor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad he's changed his mind about canceling the Pioneer  
Press,'' said Walker Lundy, the newspaper's editor. Lundy, 
interviewed by CNN minutes after hearing the governor's latest 
comments, said he doesn't consider the situation with Ventura a 
feud. 
</P>
<P>
	But he added that if the governor ``attacks the newspaper  
inaccurately or unfairly,'' he wouldn't shy away from commenting on 
it. The newspaper maintains that it can't legally deny advertising 
space to sexually-oriented businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura's predecessor also criticized him Monday for his attack  
on the newspaper, saying the state's chief executive needs to treat 
all members of the press equally and fairly. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't serve all people if you're going to eliminate  
certain media, because that eliminates their audience,'' former 
Gov. Arne Carlson said on a Minnesota Public Radio call-in show. 
</P>
<P>
	This wasn't the first time the governor took aim at the Pioneer  
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura criticized the paper in March when it published  
allegations of academic misconduct by University of Minnesota 
basketball players the day before the Gophers opened the NCAA 
tournament. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0207 </DOCNO>
