<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 13:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Second Dragging Death Trial Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRYAN, Texas (AP) -- Jury selection began Tuesday in the murder  
trial of a second white man accused of dragging a black man to his 
death in Jasper last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty prospective jurors for the case against Lawrence Russell  
Brewer, 32, were dismissed for legal or health reasons. Those who 
remained were given a three-page questionnaire to fill out. 
Individual questioning was to begin Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer is the second of three alleged white supremacists accused  
of abducting and beating James Byrd Jr., chaining him to a pickup 
truck and dragging him to pieces. Prosecutors believe he was killed 
as a way to recruit members to a new white supremacist 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer could get the death penalty.  
</P>
<P>
	John William King, the first to be tried, was convicted in  
Jasper last February and sentenced to death. The case against 
Brewer was moved to Bryan, 150 miles away, after the defense argued 
that the people of Jasper would be inclined to convict Brewer to 
redeem their town's reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	No trial date has been set for the third defendant, Shawn Allen  
Berry. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 15:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oakley Re-Signs With Raptors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- The Toronto Raptors added an important piece to  
their offseason puzzle Tuesday by re-signing power forward Charles 
Oakley. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial details of the three-year contract weren't announced,  
but Toronto had reportedly offered the 14-year veteran $6 million a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakley, 35, was a free agent and had been courted by as many as  
eight NBA teams, including the Los Angeles Lakers and San Antonio 
Spurs. None had anywhere near enough salary-cap room to match 
Toronto's offer, yet Oakley was tempted by the possibility of 
joining a contender. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspense ended Tuesday when the Raptors received a signed  
contract via courier from the 6-foot-9, 245-pound forward. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took a little bit longer than we hoped and I know Charles  
wanted to get it done earlier, too,'' general manager Glen Grunwald 
said via conference call from Orlando, where he was on vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it was the first time in his long career that he had the  
opportunity to really decide where he wanted to play. I think you 
have to give the guy that benefit because he certainly deserved the 
right to choose where he wanted to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oakley wasn't available for comment Tuesday. He is scheduled to  
attend a news conference here on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oakley deal caps a hectic month for Grunwald. He also traded  
first-round draft pick Jonathan Bender to Indiana for veteran 
forward Antonio Davis, signed free-agent guard Dell Curry, 
re-signed center Michael Stewart and won an arbitration case 
freeing rookie center Alek Radojevic to join the team this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Re-signing Oakley, obtained prior to last season via a trade  
with the New York Knicks, was the key. Oakley's experience and 
leadership were instrumental in helping the Raptors post their best 
record ever (23-27) and contend for a playoff spot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we have a better team now than we did last year,''  
Grunwald said Tuesday. ``The key is making sure our younger players 
get better. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakley averaged a career-low 7.5 rebounds and averaged 7 points  
a game. For his career, the Virginia Union grad has averaged 10.3 
rebounds and 10.6 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``Charles has had discussions with me, Butch and the coaching  
staff about what would be more effective for him and I think we'll 
incorporate some of those things,'' Grunwald said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a new situation here and I think we were all still  
working through it last year, trying to find what worked for the 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grunwald isn't concerned that the NBA's decision to clamp down  
on clutching and grabbing next season will diminish Oakley's 
effectiveness defensively. 
</P>
<P>
	``What people overlook is Charles is not just a tough guy. His  
ability to help his teammates on defense, make plays and make the 
right pass are very important and I think those things will 
continue.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 08:00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fruit of the Loom CEO Steps Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Fruit of the Loom Ltd. CEO William Farley is  
stepping down as part of a corporate restructuring at the clothing 
company, though he will stay on as chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago-based company also said yesterday that production  
and customer service difficulties will cause financial results for 
the rest of the year to fall significantly below analysts' 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Board member Dennis Bookshester will serve as acting chief  
executive officer of the company, best known for its underwear and 
active wear, until a replacement is found for Farley. The search is 
expected to take six to nine months. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, Fruit of the Loom reported a second-quarter $2.3  
million loss as sales dropped 12 percent from the year-ago quarter 
to $551.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Moody's Investors Service earlier this month downgraded Fruit of  
the Loom's debt ratings, pointing to declining sales and earnings 
performance, a weak balance sheet and production and distribution 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Fruit of the Loom, in recent years, has transferred thousands of  
jobs to Mexico, Central America and the Caribbean to save money. In 
addition it has transferred its financial base from Chicago to the 
Cayman Islands. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 14:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rabid Bear in Iowa Spurs Search </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Health officials are trying to track  
down up to 400 tourists from as far away as Australia who played 
with a rabid bear cub at a petting zoo. 
</P>
<P>
	The disease was discovered after the 5-month-old black bear died  
Friday. That sent officials poring through the guest registry at 
the Wild Midwest Petting Zoo near Clermont in search of everyone 
who may have had contact with the bear. 
</P>
<P>
	``This exposure by a rabid bear to innocent tourists and  
children we should take very, very seriously,'' said Dr. Steve 
Gleason, head of the Iowa Department of Public Health. ``We could 
have rabies deaths in Iowa, Illinois, Wisconsin, Minnesota or any 
other states from which visitors might have come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 people had been called by Tuesday, but officials said  
many visitors probably didn't bother to sign the registry. 
</P>
<P>
	The bear also made an appearance at a barn dance near Dubuque  
before it died. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyone who may have been exposed to rabies must get a $1,500  
series of five shots to prevent the fatal disease. Although saliva 
from the animal must penetrate the skin to transmit the disease, 
doctors warned that no chances should be taken. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem with this virus is the minute you have symptoms,  
you're dead,'' Gleason said. 
</P>
<P>
	Scores of people were vaccinated Sunday and Monday at the  
hospital closest to the petting zoo. The hospital brought in extra 
vaccine to meet the initial rush. 
</P>
<P>
	State health officials said operators of the zoo broke no laws  
or regulations, because there was no way of knowning the animal had 
rabies before it died. 
</P>
<P>
	Health officials examined other animals at the petting zoo for  
signs of rabies Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
