<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 04:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury: Exxon Doesn't Owe California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A jury has rejected claims that Exxon Corp.  
owed the state of California $750 million for allegedly 
underpricing oil pumped from public lands. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court jurors decided Monday that the state received  
fair royalty payments during the 1980s for oil taken from the 
8,000-acre Wilmington field off Long Beach. Jurors also said Exxon 
did not act in bad faith or manipulate oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
	In its 13-year-old civil suit against Exxon, California claimed  
that the company had shortchanged the state about $350 million for 
oil pumped from 1981 to 1989. With interest, that sum would have 
grown to $750 million, said Larry Feldman, a lawyer who represented 
Irving, Texas-based Exxon. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Brian McMahon, an attorney for the state, said he was  
``obviously disappointed'' with the outcome. He said the state had 
not yet decided whether to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The state argued Wilmington crude oil was sold at up to $4 per  
barrel less than Alaska's North Slope crude. The state said in a 
competitive market, prices should have been the same after 
adjustments for quality differences. 
</P>
<P>
	Exxon said other factors, such as shipping costs, affected the  
price. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 14:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Fined Over Ribbon Violation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELOIT, Wis. (AP) -- A woman who tied about 500 yellow ribbons  
around trees and utility posts to support the military in Kosovo 
has been found guilty of violating a city ordinance and fined $320. 
</P>
<P>
	Mieke Veneman was issued two citations in April for putting up  
``signs'' in the form of yellow ribbons in the public right-of-way. 
She was found guilty Monday and said on Tuesday she will appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Her lawyer had asked that the case be dropped because the  
ordinance does not specifically refer to yellow ribbons as signs. 
But the case prosecutor said the ordinance applied because a clause 
also refers to signs as devices to attract attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Oxford American Dictionary defines `sign' as `a device  
with a special meaning,'' Municipal Judge William Henderson said. 
``Under this definition, a white flag which is the universal signal 
for surrender would constitute a sign.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
