<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras Exits, Agassi Now Favored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The U.S. Open received a jolt today when  
four-time champion Pete Sampras was forced to withdraw before 
playing a match because of a back injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras suffered a small herniated disc in his back according to  
Dr. Brian Hainline, medical director of the Open. ``It's not 
allowing him to move as he should,'' Hainline said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras withdrew from a tournament in Indianapolis two weeks ago  
because of a hip injury. He apparently injured his back during 
practice on Sunday and asked Open officials to delay his 
first-round match until Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Then today, he pulled out.  
</P>
<P>
	``The good part is that we discovered it early,'' Hainline said.  
``A large herniated disc could've jeopardized his future, so it's 
good we caught it early.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The withdrawal of Sampras, the Wimbledon champion, makes Andre  
Agassi the tournament favorite. The second-seeded Agassi began his 
quest under the lights on opening night at Arthur Ashe Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always enjoyed playing at night,'' Agassi said after  
turning in an outstanding performance Monday night. ``I'm used to 
it. I love the energy of the crowd. It almost feels like theater 
out there. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're just there to be entertained and enjoy.''  
</P>
<P>
	Seeking his third consecutive Grand Slam tournament final, the  
second-seeded Agassi capped the opening day of the year's final 
Grand Slam tournament Monday night with a 6-1, 6-1, 6-3 thrashing 
of Sweden's Nicklas Kulti. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi, who won the French Open in June and reached the final of  
Wimbledon in July, was in complete control against Kulti, making 
only four unforced errors in the opening set. He needed only 75 
minutes to grab a spot in the second set. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's never as easy as it looks,'' said Agassi, who equaled his  
best performance at the National Tennis Center. In 1997, he lost 
only four games in a second-round victory over Romanian Adrian 
Voinea 6-0, 6-2, 6-2.. 
</P>
<P>
	It definitely wasn't easy for 10th-seeded Marcelo Rios, who  
outlasted Martin Damm of the Czech Republic 6-4, 7-6 (7-5), 3-6, 
5-7, 6-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one seeded player lost on Day One: No. 6 Amanda Coetzer of  
South Africa, who fell to Romanian Irina Spirlea 6-1, 7-5. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Monday's winners in the women's singles were top-seeded  
Martina Hingis and No. 3 Venus Williams, Spirlea's on-court bump 
partner two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining Agassi and Rios in the men's second round included No. 3  
Yevgeny Kafelnikov, No. 8 Carlos Moya and No. 12 Richard Krajicek. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Lindsay Davenport began the defense of her women's  
singles title when she took on Corina Morariu of Boca Raton, Fla. 
Tonight's key matches pit seventh-seeded Serena Williams, Venus' 
younger sister, against fellow American Kimberly Po and defending 
men's champion Patrick Rafter, seeded fourth, against Frenchman 
Cedric Pioline. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi was magnificent as he made center court his stage,  
slashing winners from every angle, outslugging his Swedish foe from 
the baseline, forcing his will on which way the points were to be 
played. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looked easier than it is because it's never simple,''  
Agassi said. ``There's a lot of work that goes into making yourself 
play good tennis or focused tennis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like I was adjusting to the conditions rather quickly,  
was moving well ... and was returning really well, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Striking the ball cleanly, Agassi made only four unforced errors  
in the 22-minute-long first set. Kulti played well, but Agassi had 
the perfect answer to every challenge the Swede presented. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love playing,'' Agassi said. ``This is what I do, it's what  
I love. I truly am enjoying this stage of my life. 
</P>
<P>
	Hingis, who broke down in tears and had to be forced to return  
to the court for the trophy presentation after she lost the French 
Open, then was upset in the first round at Wimbledon, got off on 
the right foot in this Grand Slam event. She raced through the 
first set, then survived three breaks of her service in the second 
set to beat No. 74-ranked Czech Kveta Hrdlickova 6-1, 7-5. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Wimbledon, Hingis won two of the three tournaments she  
entered. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, knocked out early at the French Open by a qualifier  
she underestimated, took no chances this time and romped past 
another qualifier, Tatiana Poutchek of Belarus 6-1, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't take it seriously,'' Williams said of her short stay  
in Paris. ``You can't do that. I've learned my lesson. I had to 
learn it the hard way, in a Grand Slam. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each player -- like today, I'd never seen her before -- I'm  
really going out there to be serious about her. I'm not sure who I 
play next, or who I have the possibility of playing, but I'm 
definitely going to go into the match as serious as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Williams made a big splash in her U.S. Open  
debut, reaching the final before losing to Hingis. In the 
semifinals that year, she bumped into Spirlea, literally, when 
changing sides during a tiebreaker. 
</P>
<P>
	In her victory over Coetzer on Monday, Spirlea made 31 unforced  
errors, three more than her opponent, but had 10 more winners, 
14-4. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
