<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Nissan Exec Brings Some Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Former Renault executive Carlos Ghosn knows he is  
on a daunting mission -- reviving sputtering Nissan Motor Co. amid a 
culture of conservative management and distrust of foreigners. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ghosn believes Nissan's problems are so serious, it helps to  
be an outsider. 
</P>
<P>
	``It helps to come from the outside because people don't see you  
as anybody involved in past decision-making,'' he said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brazilian-born Ghosn (pronounced GOHN) took over as Nissan's  
chief operating officer in July, after Renault SA of France agreed 
to buy a 36.8 percent stake in the cash-strapped Japanese automaker 
for $5.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghosn's arrival generated fears and headlines about  
Western-style layoffs in a society where major corporations have 
long abhorred such job cuts as ``beheadings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign heads of big corporations were unheard of in Japan until  
Ford Motor Co. bought a controlling stake in Mazda Motor Corp. 
three years ago, and brought in a former Ford executive to head the 
company. Ghosn, 45, has become one of the most closely watched 
executives in town. 
</P>
<P>
	But overall, the lively, bespectacled 45-year-old manager is  
managing to stir hopes for change not only at Nissan but also in 
Japanese industry overall. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan can use the change. Despite a reputation for quality  
engineering, the automaker hasn't had a hit car in ages. It has 
lost money in seven of the last eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghosn, who said Nissan will return to profitability in the next  
fiscal year, acknowledged the company had grown too complacent and 
failed to act on obvious problems such as the need to streamline 
its broad selection of models, cut costs, and design more 
attractive cars. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just the fact that a company cannot for so many years  
lose money and decline in market share without a strong reaction,'' 
he said at Nissan headquarters in Tokyo. ``The solutions to 
Nissan's difficulties -- they're inside the company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicknamed ``Le Cost Killer'' for his successful cost-reduction  
campaign at Renault, Ghosn promises to announce a far-reaching 
turnaround plan in October. That plan is expected to be radical by 
Japanese standards in possibly including plant closures. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of things we need to do even if we don't like  
the consequences,'' Ghosn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghosn has decided to reduce the number of suppliers and choose  
global suppliers on the basis of quality and cost, rather than 
sticking to related companies out of the loyalty that was once a 
pillar of how business was done in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	But his energetic, levelheaded approach -- such as setting up  
teams of workers to draw ideas from the younger ranks -- has won 
praise as a welcome departure from Japan's staid corporate world. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're under pressure to show results,'' said Shuji Yamagata,  
an executive who has been taking English lessons to keep up with 
Ghosn's meetings. ``We must now clearly state our goals and 
concepts. We have to also do our utmost to reach promised 
targets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say Nissan has much to gain from joining with Renault.  
</P>
<P>
	Size alone in terms of production makes cost-slashing easier.  
Soon they will share basic auto parts as well as technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nissan people have gotten used to being losers for a long  
time,'' said Noriyuki Matsushima, auto analyst at Nikko Salomon 
Smith Barney in Tokyo. ``Whether that mindset can be changed in a 
year will be the test for Mr. Ghosn.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
