<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Journalists' Privilege Restored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal appeals court has ruled that  
journalists are protected from revealing unused material from 
nonconfidential sources, except in special instances. 
</P>
<P>
	In its ruling Friday, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court said  
journalists can block disclosure of nonconfidential materials, 
unless it can be proven they are not reasonably obtainable from 
other sources. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling stems from a case in which unbroadcast videotape for  
a segment on NBC's ``Dateline'' was subpoenaed. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court, while restoring the privilege for journalists  
it had taken away last September, said NBC must turn over the 
videotape because the material could not be obtained from other 
sources. 
</P>
<P>
	Susan Weiner, a lawyer for NBC, said it was unusual for the  
appeals court to reverse its position. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because this decision restores the privilege, it will be more  
difficult to get news materials except in cases where litigants can 
satisfy the standards set by the court,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The network had refused to turn over unbroadcast videotape that  
was subpoenaed in a federal civil rights lawsuit a Hispanic couple 
filed against a Louisiana deputy sheriff. 
</P>
<P>
	A producer from the program videotaped the officer pulling over  
a rental car with out-of-state plates to test a theory that law 
enforcement officers in Louisiana were pulling over drivers because 
of race, nationality or out-of-state license plates. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC refused to release the complete tape to either party in the  
lawsuit, saying the First Amendment provided qualified privilege on 
material reporters get from nonconfidential sources. 
</P>
<P>
	Perry R. Sanders, a Lake Charles, La., lawyer trying to get the  
videotape from NBC, did not immediately return a telephone message 
seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The court noted that judges in its region for nearly 20 years  
have consistently assumed that a journalists' privilege for 
nonconfidential materials exists. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the parties to any lawsuit were free to subpoena the press  
at will, it would likely become standard operating procedure for 
those litigating against an entity that had been the subject of 
press attention to sift through press files in search of 
information supporting their claims,'' the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court wrote that it now agrees there has been a  
qualified privilege in the past for journalists but said the 
privilege ``is less demanding than for material acquired in 
confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It said the ``wholesale exposure of press files'' would burden  
the press with heavy costs, damage its ability to do its job, 
encourage journalists to clean out files frequently and scare 
sources away or cause them to insist upon anonymity. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
