<HEADLINE> Astros OF Alou Out for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Houston Astros outfielder Moises Alou, recovering  
from major knee surgery, will be out for the season, general 
manager Gerry Hunsicker said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The team hoped Alou, who fell off a treadmill before spring  
training and underwent major knee surgery that has kept him out all 
season, would be able to return to the team in September. A biking 
accident on Sunday caused another setback. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, the Astros improved their depth in the outfield  
by acquiring Stan Javier from the San Francisco Giants for 
24-year-old right-hander Joe Messman. 
</P>
<P>
	``While things look bleak, I'm still leaving the door open that  
Moises will be able to come back this season,'' Hunsicker said. 
``But the chances are slim.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alou was riding his bike with his son Percio on Sunday when Alou  
stopped suddenly and fell off the bike and reinjured his knee. MRI 
results were negative and showed no structural damage occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	But the accident cause fluid to build up on the knee, leaving  
his return in doubt. 
</P>
<P>
	Alou had a career year with the Astros last season. He hit .312  
with 182 hits, 38 home runs and 124 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	Javier is a switch-hitter who can play all three outfield  
positions. In 112 games this season, he has made 45 starts in left 
field and 29 in right while hitting .276 in 333 at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros also asked for unconditional release waivers on  
pitcher Sean Bergman, a former member of the team's rotation, and 
Alex Diaz on Tuesday. They recalled pitcher Jose Cabrera from 
Triple-A New Orleans of the PCL. 
</P>
<P>
	Bergman was 4-6 with a 5.35 ERA in 19 games and 16 starts this  
season. He spent time on the disabled list with tightness in his 
right forearm. Bergman had a 12-9 record for the Astros last 
season, a career high for victories. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
