<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reputed Russian Mobster Faults FBI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A reputed Russian mob leader has denied any  
involvement in alleged money laundering through the Bank of New 
York, claiming in an interview published Tuesday that he is the 
victim of an FBI vendetta. 
</P>
<P>
	Semyon Mogilevich also suggested in the interview with the  
popular daily Moskovsky Komsomolets that the money laundering case 
was rooted in American politicians' resentment of Russia's 
increased clout since the conflict in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Mogilevich repeated a previous assertion that he didn't have  
anything near the $4.2 billion to $10 billion that news reports say 
investigators believe was funneled through the Bank of New York. 
The reports have said investigators believe Mogilevich was 
involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Mogilevich, who has never been prosecuted for his alleged role  
in Russian organized crime, alleged the FBI sought to tie him to 
the scandal because of the agency's failure to find evidence 
linking him to criminal activity. 
</P>
<P>
	His implication in the case was ``career tricks by some FBI  
agents who want medals and credit,'' Mogilevich said. 
</P>
<P>
	``American special services have many times raised the question  
of why haven't I been arrested yet,'' said Mogilevich, who lives in 
Hungary. ``To which Hungarians always said: We would arrest him in 
a moment, but give us at least the slightest reason for us to do 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mogilevich also claimed some U.S. officials were using the  
scandal to undermine Russia's global influence. ``After the swift 
deployment of our paratroopers in Kosovo ... Russia has 
strengthened its position in the world. And many don't like that,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about his personal fortune, Mogilevich said it was ``less  
than $10 billion. ... When I came home after the first report about 
the (scandal), we had an awful fight at home. My wife was yelling 
that she wanted a new rug, and I had been telling her that I had no 
money,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In an earlier interview, Mogilevich said he had only laundered  
money once in his life: When he inadvertently left five dollars' 
worth of Russian currency in a pocket of his shirt before washing 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest interview, Mogilevich dismissed other accusations  
leveled against him in recent years -- including involvement in drug 
trading, commissioning murders, running a prostitution ring, and 
controlling the arms industry in Hungary. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of New York scandal has been described as potentially  
one of the biggest money laundering affairs ever uncovered in the 
United States. Money laundering is the process of moving ill-gotten 
gains through a series of bank accounts until they appear to be 
profits from legal businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has been charged with any crime in the case.  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a major Russian oil company whose chairman has  
reportedly been linked to the scandal issued a statement Tuesday 
saying that Russia's failure to begin an intensive investigation 
into the case could cause all Russian businesses to be seen as 
criminal and ruin their relations with the West. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless something is done, Russian companies could face a full  
blockade,'' the company, Yukos, said in a statement carried by the 
Interfax news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's top prosecutor has called for an investigation of the  
charges. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990831.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 15:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain's 'Straigt Talk' Faces Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANCASTER, N.H. (AP) -- John McCain considers himself a  
blunt-speaking, pull-no-punches political maverick, but he is 
discovering aboard his ``Straight Talk Express'' campaign bus that 
he may have difficulty living up to his reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential candidate, opening a four-day tour  
of this initial primary state, stands accused of waffling on 
abortion to court moderate voters. And even as he cedes no ground 
on two other issues -- campaign finance reform and foreign policy -- 
McCain acknowledges that his tough talk could fall on deaf ears 
during the 2000 presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm addressing issues that I think are important to America,''  
he said in an interview. ``Whether it resonates with the public is 
not something I can control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is a critical state for McCain, who plans to bypass Iowa's  
caucuses to focus on what he suspects is a more independent-minded 
New Hampshire electorate. His poll numbers have steadily climbed 
from the low single digits to the teens in New Hampshire, though 
front-runner George W. Bush is still far ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's strategists hope his support will creep above 20  
percent, within 10 percentage points or so of Bush, after he 
highlights his personal history this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	A prisoner of war in Vietnam, McCain soon begins a book tour to  
promote ``Faith of my Fathers,'' a poignant memoir of his time in 
captivity and the standards set by his father and grandfather -- 
both war heroes and Navy admirals. 
</P>
<P>
	The book does not hide McCain's warts; he writes of his temper  
and provides a colorful accounting of his fast-living past that 
eventually led to destruction of his first marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain has a history of getting in trouble with his quick and  
cutting wit. He entertained reporters Tuesday with a litany of his 
blunders, including an ineffective joke he told last year about 
Chelsea Clinton, which McCain said was ``insensitive, stupid and 
cruel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview earlier, McCain said life is too short to watch  
every word. ``I get in trouble all the time and I will continue to 
get in trouble. I say what's on my mind to the frustration of my 
campaign people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Littleton, N.H., he chastised a man who challenged his  
open-trade policies, telling Jerome Danin that he is selling 
himself and his children short with protectionism. ``I did not know 
that your ambitions ... for your children were to work in a textile 
mill,'' McCain said. ``I would rather have you work in a high-tech 
industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He told voters in rural Lancaster that sacrifices come with  
making ``lifestyle choices'' to live in a rural community, 
including reduced access to health care. 
</P>
<P>
	He called the congressional tax-cut plan an ``exercise in  
political kabuki,'' criticizing GOP leaders for a bill that gives 
immediate tax cuts to special interests and delays reductions to 
taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He answered all of my questions, which I respect, even if I  
wasn't crazy about all the answers,'' said Paul Smith, one of 120 
people who came to a veteran's hall to hear McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	But on abortion, McCain has shown that he's not above hedging  
his bets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arizona senator surprised his staff and angered  
anti-abortion allies by appearing to suggest last week that he 
would not support repealing Roe vs. Wade, the 1973 Supreme Court 
decision legalizing abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	Under pressure, McCain tried to clarify his views with written  
statements saying he favors working to overturn the ruling while 
trying to reduce abortions through adoptions, counseling and other 
efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain was still struggling with the abortion issue this week.  
</P>
<P>
	``The issue of abortion is incredibly difficult and I believe  
life begins at conception,'' McCain told a small crowd in Dixville, 
N.H., late Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	That was as far as his staff expected him to go.  
</P>
<P>
	``But,'' he said, drawing an audible gasp from a senior aide,  
``I also want the Republican Party to be an inclusive party ... and 
we cannot impose a litmus test on this issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The answer left him open to criticism from voters on both sides  
of the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw his campaign bus on the way in here, but this wasn't  
straight talk. He was evasive,'' said Carol Roberts, an 
abortion-rights supporter from Winthrop, N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	The candidate tangled Tuesday with anti-abortion protester  
Arthur Morrill, who accused McCain of straddling ``both sides of 
the fence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``People want a choice. They want a clear choice. They want more  
than a 10 cents difference from Clinton,'' said Morrill. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry you misinterpreted my remarks,'' McCain replied  
briskly. 
</P>
<P>
	After broadening his portfolio all summer, McCain returned this  
week to his signature issue: Reforming campaign finance laws. 
</P>
<P>
	On foreign affairs, McCain says China and Russia are simmering  
troublespots mishandled by the Clinton administration. He wants to 
close military bases and increase military spending elsewhere, 
particularly on missile defense systems and on military pay. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the McCain team is unsure whether the issues will play in  
the campaign. Sen. Fred Thompson of Tennessee, who joined McCain on 
the bus tour, said he considered running for president himself but 
determined that the timing wasn't right for a candidate who wanted 
to talk about the dire challenges facing America. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a kinder and gentler period,'' Thompson said. ``People  
don't want to face up to things that they should face up to.'' 
Straight talk, he said, can be hard to stomach. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
