<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans Surge on Crop Downgrade / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures soared Tuesday on the Chicago  
Board of Trade after a government report unexpectedly downgraded the 
quality of the upcoming crop. Other grain prices also rose. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybeans led the gains after the U.S. Department of Agriculture  
said only 47 percent of all U.S. soybeans were in good to excellent 
condition -- a decline of one percentage point from a week ago. It 
was the sixth straight week the rating had declined. 
</P>
<P>
        Dry weather forecasts this week for the heart of the Midwest,  
along with a weaker U.S. dollar, also supported the gains. It was the 
highest close for soybeans since Aug. 11. 
</P>
<P>
        Corn followed suit, though not to as great an extent, on news  
that there have been no improvements in that crop. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat got a boost from the rally in soybeans and news that  
Egypt had placed an order to buy soft red winter wheat from the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for December delivery rose 5 1/4 cents to $2.82 1/4 a  
bushel; December corn rose 2 1/2 cents to $2.19 1/4 a bushel; December 
oats rose 2 cents to $1.16 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans rose 12 
1/2 cents to $4.83 cents a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while pork futures were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
        October live cattle fell .35 cent to 67.60 cents a pound; October  
feeder cattle fell .20 cent to 78.85 cents a pound; October lean hogs 
rose .03 cent to 45.80 cents a pound; February pork bellies fell .70 
cent to 58.75 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
