<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 23:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Seek Way To Prepare for Storms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Margaret and Charlie Highfill faced Hurricane  
Dennis in their Carolina Beach, N.C., home with a confidence born 
of having used the lessons of one storm disaster to protect 
themselves from another. 
</P>
<P>
	Now federal recovery experts are evaluating the experience of  
the Highfills and others like them to learn how to prepare 
communities for severe storms. 
</P>
<P>
	Through its Project Impact, the Federal Emergency Management  
Agency is teaching people how to protect their lives and property 
in advance of a hurricane rather than just waiting for the storm to 
hit and then helping them rebuild. 
</P>
<P>
	For the New Hanover County region of North Carolina that faced  
Dennis, damage prevention efforts got really serious after 
batterings by Hurricane Fran in 1996 and Bonnie last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think because of that, they're probably going to have  
minimal damage'' this time, said FEMA Director James Lee Witt. 
</P>
<P>
	The Highfills bought an older home on the beach in 1996 and  
seven days later Fran swamped it in four feet of water. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than simply cleaning up and fixing up, the Highfills  
elevated their home on pilings, strengthened the roof and upgraded 
the windows and siding. 
</P>
<P>
	``We spent a good bit of money,'' Charlie Highfill said in a  
telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it's worth it in the long run, because you don't have to  
do it again,'' his wife added. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what saved us,'' her husband said, recalling the  
arrival of Hurricane Bonnie last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had virtually no damage. The houses on either side of us  
and across the street that were still on the ground had as much 
damage'' as in Fran, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We stayed in our house'' Sunday night during Hurricane  
Dennis,'' added his wife, ``it was rocking and rolling.'' But the 
home and the Highfills weathered the storm well. 
</P>
<P>
	Witt would like more people to follow their example.  
</P>
<P>
	``If each of us take our responsibilities seriously, and  
individuals, too, then we'll have fewer deaths and a lot less cost 
in the recovery part of disaster. And that's the goal, because it 
will eventually save lives, strengthen the communities and save 
jobs,'' the FEMA director said. 
</P>
<P>
	Witt recalled touring the panhandle of Florida after 1995's  
Hurricane Opal. ``You could literally see the houses that were 
built after they had adopted local building codes and standards, 
because they survived, and the houses that were built before did 
not survive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Debbie Reed, the Project Impact coordinator for the area where  
the Highfills live, said the effort is paying off. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people in the community have taken mitigation measures,  
including elevation of their homes to take them out of harm's way 
from storm surge damage,'' she said. Some 80 to 90 homes are 
elevated at Wrightsville Beach, and there are 50 more at Carolina 
and Kure beaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Using corporate partners, Project Impact has organized storm  
shelters and weather stations, improved the emergency 
communications system, rewired sewer pump stations to use 
generators in emergencies, moved the police and fire station off 
the flood area and made other changes. As a result, residents of 
Carolina Beach began receiving a 15 percent discount on flood 
insurance in April. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not just hurricane-prone regions that can benefit. Project  
Impact is working in more than 120 communities across the nation, 
including Tulsa, Okla., where major efforts have gone into 
protecting from floods. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes it isn't even worthwhile to build better or stronger,  
Witt acknowledged. Instead it's best to admit that nature has won 
and move. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1993, FEMA has worked with state and local governments to  
buy out more than 25,000 pieces of property nationwide because of 
repeated flooding. One community in Missouri had been flooded 31 
times when FEMA arranged to buy out and move the town's 18 
businesses and 142 residents. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every dollar we've done this for we've saved $2 in future  
losses. But we've saved more than that. We've saved the pain and 
the anguish and the grief that people have gone through so many 
times,'' Witt said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
