<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybean, Grain Futures Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Soybean futures surged Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade  
amid concerns the coming crop may be smaller than expected despite 
badly needed late-summer rains. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, copper futures enjoyed their biggest  
single-day gain since July and cocoa futures advanced sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	The rise in soybeans came on the heels of a U.S. government  
report which showed a sixth straight weekly decline in the crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 47 percent of all U.S. soybeans were in good to excellent  
condition, according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture report 
issued late Monday -- a decline of one percentage point from a week 
ago and well under the 65 percent rating of a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerned that crop yields will fall this year, investors sent  
soybean futures to their highest closing price in nearly three 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've just continued to gradually deteriorate in our crop  
despite the rain,'' said Don Roose, president of Iowa-based U.S. 
Commodities Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasts of dry weather this week for the heart of the Midwest,  
along with a weaker U.S. dollar, also buoyed the gains. As the 
dollar declines against other major currencies, U.S. crops are less 
costly in foreign markets, making it easier to increase exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures also rose after the weekly report showed a slight  
decline in its crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn for December delivery rose 2 1/2 cents to $2.19 1/4 a bushel;  
November soybeans rose 12 1/2 cents to $4.83 cents a bushel; wheat for 
December delivery rose 5 1/4 cents to $2.82 1/4 a bushel; December oats 
rose 2 cents to $1.16 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper futures jumped after a three-month rally had stalled  
recently. Analysts said announcements by Germany and France that 
their economies will grow faster in 2000 would boost copper sales 
in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	After sinking to a 12-year low in May, copper prices have  
rebounded 27 percent amid a string of mine closures in North 
America and buoyed by stronger demand in Asia and Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's rise was the highest since July 30 and followed a  
price dip last week over news that the Highland Valley mine in 
British Columbia was poised to reopen. Some investors feared that 
its annual production of 170,000 tons would have an adverse affect 
on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper is used in wiring and plumbing.  
</P>
<P>
	High-grade copper for December delivery rose 3.10 cents to 79.20  
cents per pound on the New York Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Technical reasons appeared behind the advance in cocoa prices.  
</P>
<P>
	September cocoa rose 24 cents to $9.13 a ton on the on the  
Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange division of the New York Board of 
Trade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
