<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopeful About North Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) --The Clinton administration hopes a new round of  
talks with North Korea next week will help ease Cold War tensions 
on the divided peninsula. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James Foley said Tuesday that recent  
statements by the Pyongyang government show a willingness to 
improve relations with the United States and other nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the public statements by the North Koreans have given  
us hope that North Korea is taking seriously the path to better 
relations with the U.S. and the international community,'' Foley 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. envoy Charles Kartman and North Korea's Vice Foreign  
Minister Kim Gye Gwan will meet in Berlin Sept. 7-11. Washington's 
top priority in the talks is to persuade the North Koreans to forgo 
testing a long-range missile, which threatens stability in 
Northeast Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently bowing to threats of economic and diplomatic  
penalties by the United States, Japan and South Korea, North Korea 
said last week it was willing to resolve the missile dispute 
through negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Foley said that in the Berlin talks Kartman will stress ``the  
advantages to North Korea of taking steps to improve relations,'' 
including the United States lifting economic sanctions against the 
isolated communist country. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio, said Monday after a four-day visit to  
North Korea that the Pyongyang government ``wants to not only 
negotiate, it (also) wants us to continue food aid and lift 
sanctions. If we do that, they will respond in a favorable way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hall was speaking in Seoul, South Korea. Foley said  
administration officials plan to discuss his talks with the North 
Koreans when Hall returns to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Western military analysts believe the North is poised to test an  
advanced version of a long-range missile it fired over Japan a year 
ago. The United States, Japan and South Korea have warned that 
another launch could trigger economic penalties against North 
Korea. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
