<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 31, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	FBI Wants Independent Waco Probe  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- FBI Director Louis Freeh is pushing for an  
independent investigator to head the probe into why it took his 
agency six years to acknowledge using incendiary tear gas canisters 
in the waning hours of the Branch Davidian siege. Amid concern over 
the appearance of the FBI and Justice Department investigating 
themselves, Freeh has told Attorney General Janet Reno she should 
appoint an outsider to head the inquiry, an FBI official confirmed 
today. 

</P>
<P>
	Record Bush Funds Are Expected  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush's GOP presidential  
campaign expects to report within a month that it has raised over 
$50 million so far. That would be a record pre-nomination total. It 
might even surpass $60 million, a Bush adviser said today. ``I know 
there are some who are talking about my capacity to raise money, 
particularly some of my opponents,'' Bush said while campaigning in 
Omaha, Neb. ``I would suggest that if you ask them, they would like 
to trade places.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Mideast Accord Push Is On  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiators met in a  
secret location Tuesday to try to resolve disagreements blocking 
the way to peace in the region. Israeli envoy Gilead Sher and 
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat have already made some progress 
on deadlines for an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the West 
Bank. Both have expressed optimism that a deal may be set before 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrives in the region 
Thursday. 

</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Drifts Off N. Carolina  
</P>
<P>
	NAGS HEAD, N.C. (AP) -- Hurricane Dennis weakened and slowed to a  
near halt today just off the coast, leaving relatively sparse 
property damage along the North Carolina seaboard. A hurricane 
warning for the North Carolina coast was downgraded to a tropical 
storm warning. But Dennis could linger without moving much through 
Saturday, said Rod Gonski, forecaster at the National Weather 
Service in Raleigh. Because of the uncertainty, people have started 
calling oceanfront hotels in southeastern Virginia to cancel 
reservations for Labor Day weekend. 

</P>
<P>
	Wildfires Burn Parts of West  
</P>
<P>
	APPLE VALLEY, Calif. (AP) -- Firefighters today struggled to  
contain active forest and brush fires that have burned 150,000 
acres in the West. The largest uncontrolled blazes were being 
fought in Idaho, Montana, Utah and California. Fires were contained 
in Nevada and Washington. The biggest concentration of firefighters 
worked to tame a 50,000-acre blaze that has destroyed 12 homes 
since Sunday about 80 miles east of Los Angeles, near the resort 
town of Lake Arrowhead. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkey Aftershock Kills 1  
</P>
<P>
	IZMIT, Turkey (AP) -- Survivors of Turkey's powerful earthquake  
on Aug. 17 were rattled again today when a strong tremor struck the 
northwest part of the country, killing one man, injuring at least 
166 other people and knocking down quake-weakened buildings. 
Today's 5.2-magnitude shock came just two weeks after the 
devastating earthquake that killed more than 14,200 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Moscow Explosion Hurts 30  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A powerful explosion rocked a crowded shopping  
mall near the Kremlin today, injuring at least 30 people, police 
said. Police said a video game machine apparently exploded in the 
Manesh underground mall. A Moscow police spokesman said it was 
unclear whether the evening blast was a bomb or an accident. 

</P>
<P>
	Child Car Seat Rules Set  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Child car seats take on a new look starting  
tomorrow, when stricter head protection standards take effect. That 
means most seats will come equipped with a tether strap that 
anchors the top of the seat more securely so children move less in 
a crash. There are hundreds of thousands of child seats already in 
use, and parents should not abandon them. Seat manufacturers and 
automakers are offering kits to add the tethers and new attachment 
points. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 84.85  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as a report of growth in  
manufacturing ignited fears of inflation and hurt blue-chip 
companies. The Dow industrials fell 84.85 to close at 10,829.28. On 
the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,671-1,316. The Nasdaq rose 25.13 to 
2,737.82 as technology stocks benefited from a wave of new deals 
and products. 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras Quits Open With Back Injury  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pete Sampras, the world's No. 1 tennis player,  
withdrew from the U.S. Open before his first match today because of 
a back injury. The four-time champion has a small herniated disc. 
He apparently reinjured himself during practice Sunday. ``We caught 
it early and he should recover fully,'' said Dr. Brian Hainline, 
U.S. Open medical director. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
  	   	
</P>
