<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 07:50:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Airlines Reducing Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- China Airlines is cutting 68 flights in  
September, mostly on its lucrative Hong Kong-Taipei route, as part 
of a temporary reorganization following a deadly crash in Hong 
Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taiwanese airline has come under pressure from Taiwan's  
Civil Aeronautics Administration (CAA) to tighten up on safety and 
cancel some flights since one of its McDonnell Douglas MD-11 jets 
flipped and burst into flames Aug. 22 while landing in a tropical 
storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Three people were killed and over 200 were injured in the crash  
of Flight CI642 from Bangkok, Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of the plane and increased safety checks on other  
aircraft have reduced the number of passengers China Airlines can 
carry, airline spokesman Steve Chen said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Because September marks the beginning of the slower travel  
season, financial losses from the cancellations will not be too 
heavy, Chen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Canceled flights include one daily Taipei-Hong Kong round trip,  
or 60 total flights for the month, he said. Two round-trip flights 
between Taipei and San Francisco and two between Taipei and Los 
Angeles also will be canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	All will resume in October, the airline said.  
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the Hong Kong accident remains under investigation.  
</P>
<P>
	The crash was the third major disaster to strike China Airlines  
in less than a decade, reigniting a debate over safety standards at 
the Taiwanese state-controlled airline. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
